<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Korea-Library     05-23 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Korea-Library,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea Opens Library Devoted to Communism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stauchly anti-communist South Korea
today opened a new library featuring 10,000 books, periodicals and
films on rival North Korea and other communist nations.
   The library, located in a downtown post office, includes 4,500
books and documents on communist ideology and 50 magazines and
daily newspapers such as Pravda from the Soviet Union. It also has
5,000 books and 300 films on communist North Korea, a spokesman
said.
   The National Unification Board said the library was opened to
meet a growing demand for information as a result of the increasing
contacts and trade relations between South Korea and communist
countries.
   South Korea has been strongly anti-communist since the division
of the Korean peninsula into the communist north and the capitalist
south at the end of World War II.
   The Seoul government has diplomatic relations with only one
communist nation, Hungary, but has encouraged trade contacts with
others as a means to ease tension on the peninsula.
</TEXT>
