<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 0028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     05-23 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>`See No Evil, Hear No Evil' Retains Top Spot at Box Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``See No Evil, Hear No Evil,'' featuring the
comic adventures of a blind Richard Pryor and a deaf Gene Wilder,
was the No. 1 movie at the box office last weekend, taking in $6.1
million.
   ``Road House,'' with ``Dirty Dancing'' star Patrick Swayze as a
nightclub bouncer, debuted at No. 2 with close to $6 million in
weekend receipts as compiled by Exhibitor Relations Co.
   ``Field of Dreams,'' the Kevin Costner baseball fantasy that
brings big leaguers to a Midwest cornfield, moved down a notch to
third place with a gate of $5.1 million.
   ``K-9,'' a movie about a loveable police dog and his police pal
Jim Belushi, dropped a place to No. 4 with a $3.3 million draw,
followed in fifth by the Stephen King's thriller ``Pet Sematary.''
   Another baseball film, ``Major League,'' slid from fifth to
sixth in sales, while ``Rain Man'' fared well for the 23rd week
with $1 million in ticket sales.
   The Oscar-winning movie, starring Dustin Hoffman and Tom Cruise,
has earned more than $163 million since its release.
   ``Scandal,'' the movie about the Profumo sex affair that rocked
Britain in 1963, dropped a notch to No. 8 with about $900,000 in
ticket sales.
   Michael Keaton's ``The Dream Team'' was ninth with $831,250 and
``Miss Firecracker'' with Holly Hunter as a last-minute beauty
contestant, came in at No. 10 with $787,266.
   ``Miss Firecracker'' may have placed 10th in total take, but the
movie's average sales of $3,749 at the 210 theaters where it was
shown outranked top draw ``See No Evil, Hear No Evil'' which had an
average $3,634 per screen.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``See No Evil, Hear No Evil,'' Tri-Star, $6.1 million, 1,680
screens, $3,634 per screen, $15.6 million, two weeks.
   2. ``Road House,'' MGM-UA, $6 million, 1,927 screens, $3,092 per
screen, $6 million, one week.
   3. ``Field of Dreams,'' Universal, $5.1 million, 1,052 screens,
$4,830 per screen, $23.3 million, five weeks.
   4. ``K-9,'' Universal, $3.3 million, 1,695 screens, $1,935 per
screen, $26.6 million, four weeks.
   5. ``Pet Sematary,'' Paramount, $2.6 million, 1,585 screens,
$1,642 per screen, $42.7 million, five weeks.
   6. ``Major League,'' Paramount, $1.8 million, 1,443 screens,
$1,249 per screen, $41.8 million, seven weeks.
   7. ``Rain Man,'' MGM-UA, $1.1 million, 1,051 screens, $1,015 per
screen, $163.7 million, 23 weeks.
   8. ``Scandal,'' Miramax, $902,111, 352 screens, $2,563 per
screen, $4.4 million, four weeks.
   9. ``The Dream Team,'' Universal, $831,250, 950 screens, $875
per screen, $24.3 million, seven weeks.
   10. ``Miss Firecracker,'' Corsair, $787,266, 210 screens, $3,749
per screen, $1.1 million, four weeks.
</TEXT>
