<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 0114EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-KeanEndorsement     05-23 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kean Endorsement,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Popular NJ Governor Says He Will Not Issue Endorsement For Successor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Popular Gov. Thomas H. Kean ended nearly a
year of speculation Monday and said he will not endorse a candidate
in the heated Republican primary to succeed him.
   The GOP governor said in a statement that he had watched the
candidates in three televised debates, and felt any of the four
leading contenders would make a good competitor in the fall general
election and a good governor.
   Kean, who by law cannot seek a third consecutive term, urged
voters to ``concentrate on what the candidates are saying, the
positions they are adopting, and the solutions they are proposing.''
   With most polls showing up to half of the Republican primary
voters undecided, an endorsement by Kean was widely considered to
be a key weapon in swaying voters at the polls June 6.
   Some campaigns have said Kean's backing could help deliver up to
30,000 votes, a significant boost for an election in which some
believe as few as 100,000 votes may be enough to secure the
nomination.
   Kean spokesman Carl Golden said the governor weighed the
candidacies of former Attorney General Cary Edwards, Rep. James
Courter, Sen. William Gormley and Assembly Speaker Chuck Hardwick.
Polls show the four men have a significant lead over a fifth
candidate, Sen. Gerald Cardinale, who has said he did not want the
backing of the moderate governor.
   An endorsement would have been a tough decision for Kean because
all four men have close ties to the governor.
   Courter ran Kean's 1981 and 1985 campaigns, and Edwards has been
a top adviser. Gormley has been a loyal point man in the Senate and
Hardwick helped push many Kean initiatives through the Assembly
before breaking with the governor over several issues in the past
year.
   The decision was greeted happily by the Hardwick campaign, which
was considered the least likely to get Kean's endorsement.
   The other campaigns all said they would have welcomed an
endorsement, but have not planned strategy around the governor's
backing.
   Three other candidates also are seeking the GOP nomination, but
are considered longshots by observers.
</TEXT>
