<FIRST>r i PM-ArabSummit     05-23 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arab Summit,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon's Seat Remains Empty As Summit Gets Under Way</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASABLANCA, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arab League convenes a summit
meeting today marking the return of Egypt to the councils of the
Arab world, and for the first time in league history Lebanon's seat
is vacant.
   The reinstatement of Egypt to league membership following a
10-year suspension was accepted reluctantly by Libya's Moammar
Gadhafi, who held out to the last moment to try to prevent it.
   An uneasy compromise on Lebanon, on the other hand, resulted in
the temporary suspension of Lebanon's league membership.
   Morocco's King Hassan II hugged President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt
upon Mubarak's arrival in Casablanca on Monday and a 21-gun salute
boomed.
   Egypt had been excluded since 1979 for signing the Camp David
peace treaty with Israel. Most Arab nations warmly welcomed Egypt's
return to the 22-member League.
   ``Egypt has never ceased ... to serve the causes of our nation,
whether on the Palestinian front or in connection with the bloody
war which raged for eight long years between Iran and Iraq,'' said
Arab League Secretary-General Chadli Klibi.
   It was only after days of frantic mediation efforts by Syria,
Algeria and Tunisia that Gadhafi agreed to attend the Casablanca
summit. For a week prior to the meeting, he maintained that it
would be a waste of time because it could handle no urgent Arab
problems at the moment.
   A last-moment mini-summit of four nations in Tripoli, and later
in Oran, in western Algeria, apparently convinced Gadhafi that it
was better to attend reluctantly than be isolated in the Arab world.
   The Libyan news agency JANA announced his attendance without
explanation. JANA quoted the leaders of the four countries _ Libya,
Algeria, Syria and Tunisia _ as saying they agreed to ``confront
any concessions'' at the summit to the enemies of the Palestinian
people.
   The summit was called to offer support to the PLO in its
campaign for acceptance in the Arab-Israeli peace process and to
discuss ways to stop Lebanon's civil war.
   But delegates said privately that Gadhafi was, in fact, correct:
No urgent need for an Arab summit existed other than to arrange the
ceremonial re-entry of Egypt into the Arab family.
   At a preparatory meeting, foreign ministers failed to make
progress on the Palestinian problem and the division of Lebanon
under two rival administrations.
   Syria and the Palestine Liberation Organization were at
loggerheads over PLO peace moves, and Iraq was outspoken in defense
of Lebanese Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun.
   Because of its inability to solve the Lebanese crisis, a
ministerial preparatory committee came up with the unprecedented
solution of leaving Lebanon's seat empty for now.
   The committee felt that allowing both Aoun and his Moslem rival,
acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, to take the Lebanese seat jointly
would perpetuate the division of Lebanon, conference sources said.
   It decided that neither would be admitted as a delegate, but
both would be present in Casablanca. The final decision on who
represents Lebanon was left to Hassan.
   The PLO presented to the committee a document expressing concern
about the more than $600 million in Arab funds it was promised to
keep the 17-month-old uprising going. The PLO claims barely 10
percent has been paid.
</TEXT>
