<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill     05-23 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanker Skipper Indicted on Felony Charges; Cleanup Worker Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grand jury has added three felony
counts to the criminal charges facing the former skipper of the
Exxon Valdez.
   Meanwhile, a worker was killed Monday aboard a ship housing
workers involved in the cleanup of the massive oil spill caused by
the wreck of the tanker.
   In Anchorage, Joseph Hazelwood was charged with three counts of
second-degree criminal mischief, District Attorney Dwayne McConnell
said.
   The indictment accuses him of reckless actions before the
987-foot tanker ran aground on Bligh Reef. If convicted of all
three, Hazelwood could be sentenced to up to 15 years in prison and
fined $150,000, McConnell said.
   Hazelwood, 42, of Huntington, N.Y., was charged in Valdez in
late March with three misdemeanors: operating a boat while
intoxicated, reckless endangerment and negligent pollution.
   McConnell said the state will ask to have all the charges
consolidated into a single trial. Hazelwood is free on $50,000 bail
on the misdemeanor charges pending a June 20 trial. No date has
been set for his arraignment on the felony charges in Superior
Court.
   Hazelwood's blood alcohol content was illegally high nearly 11
hours after the accident, the Coast Guard said. He had turned over
control of the tanker to the third mate, who was not certified to
pilot the ship in Prince William Sound.
   Several crew members said at last week's National Transportation
Safety Board hearings in Anchorage that they drank with Hazelwood
before the ship left the Valdez terminal for the trans-Alaska
pipeline. Others testified they smelled alcohol on his breath, but
said he didn't seem to be impaired.
   On Monday, a food worker aboard one of the vessels housing
cleanup workers in Prince William Sound was crushed by a freight
elevator aboard the Coastal Star, a headquarters ship anchored
about 55 miles southwest of Valdez, Coast Guard Chief Mark Kennedy
said.
   The victim's identity was being withheld until relatives could
be notified.
   Exxon has several thousand workers cleaning beaches in the sound
and along the southern Alaska coast, most of them housed on ships
like the Coastal Star. Exxon has leased more than 600 vessels for
the cleanup.
   Meanwhile, Exxon and the U.S. Fish &amp; Wildlife Service announced
a special rehabilitation center will be opened in Anchorage for
bald eagles and other flesh-eating birds as the toll of wildlife
continues to mount.
   At least 43 birds of prey are among the more than 17,000 birds
confirmed dead as the result of the March 24 spill of nearly 11
million gallons of oil by the tanker.
   Exxon said it was giving an Anchorage veterinarian $100,000 for
the bird facility. The oil company said James Scott will be
assisted by Pat Redig, director of the raptor center at the
University of Minnesota.
   Exxon said last week it already had spent nearly $100 million
trying to clean up the oil that has stained Alaska's southern
coastline. The state Department of Environmental Conservation said
it has inventoried more than 700 miles of contaminated beach.
   The Alyeska Pipeline Service Co., the company which operates the
tanker terminal in Valdez and is responsible for initial spill
response, said the first of four tanker escort vessels has arrived.
   Alyeska spokesman Tom Brennan said the Liberty Service and three
other vessels on their way from Seattle will carry containment
booms and other equipment to deal with spills.
   Alyeska was criticized harshly after the Exxon Valdez spill
because its response vessel didn't reach the scene until nearly 11
hours after the tanker ran aground.
   Scientists plan to attack the spill by stimulating natural
bacteria to break down poisonous components, the first such
large-scale experimental attack, The New York Times reported in
today's editions.
   Scientists plan to apply powdered fertilizer to about 1,500 feet
of beach on Naked Island to stimulate bacteria, the Times said,
quoting U.S. Environmental Protection Administration officials.
   The experiment will not involve recombinant or selectively bred
organisms, and will rely wholly on common microbes alreadly present
in Alaskan waters, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
