<SECOND>PM-BRF--Britain-Gurkhas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0416,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gurkha Force To Be Cut By Half, Government Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT that five battalions, not divisions,
involved. Picks up 4th graf, `Britain first ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says it will halve the number of
Nepalese Gurkhas serving in the British army before the 1997
transfer of Hong Kong to China. Most of them serve as guards in the
British colony.
   The Gurkhas have fought alongside British troops since 1815,
including during the two world wars and the 1982 Falklands war with
Argentina, said Defense Secretary George Younger.
   He announced in the House of Commons on Monday that a
``progressive restructuring'' of the Gurkhas' five infantry
battalions will begin in 1992, reducing their number to 4,000
soldiers.
   Britain first encountered the Gurkhas when they fought British
attempts to establish trade routes from India to Tibet. Armed with
13{-inch Kukri fighting knives, their primary skill is jungle
warfare but they have evolved into a key ``fast reaction'' force
for the army.
   They have proved a vital source of funds for Nepal, one of the
world's poorest nations. In some years, as many as 80,000
applicants have sought only 225 places.
</TEXT>
