<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 0203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-US     05-23 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-US,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Calls Baker's Remarks ``Ironic''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With US-Mideast, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir today rejected
criticism leveled by Secretary of State James A. Baker III of
Israel's policy of continuing to support new Jewish settlements in
the occupied lands.
   ``Now is the time to lay aside, once and for all, the
unrealistic vision of a greater Israel,'' Baker said in a speech in
Washington on Monday.
   Shamir, interviewed by Israel radio, said, ``I don't know how
anyone could speak at all of a large Israel. Israel is a very small
country and all of us know that its territory is very limited. It
really rings ironic to speak of Israel as big.''
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens also dismissed Baker's call on
Israel to halt Jewish settlement in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip and give up aspirations of annexing the territories.
   ``These are our dreams. We are speaking about our country and we
have proven that we fulfill our dreams,'' Arens said on the radio,
interviewed from Brussels.
   Shamir, who was on a visit to London, said of his disagreement
with Baker over Jewish settlements in the territories: ``It is
clear there are differences of opinion between us and that isn't
new. I don't see any link between settlements and the subject of
the peace process.''
   He added that he had explained his views on the settlements
``fully and explicitly'' when he visited Washington last month.
   Israel has built more than 130 settlements in the occupied
territories since capturing them in the 1967 Middle East War.
Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc considers these lands to be integral
parts of historic Israel.
   About 70,000 Jews live in the settlements, which are scattered
among Arab towns, villages and refugee camps whose population
totals 1.7 million.
   The United States has long criticized Jewish settlement building
in these territories as an obstacle to peace. But Baker's comments
in a speech to an American Jewish lobby group on Monday were seen
as one of the sharpest American statements on the issue.
   Baker urged Israel to ``foreswear annexation. Stop settlement
activity. Allow schools to reopen,'' referring to Palestinian
schools shut by Israel in the West Bank and Gaza as part of a
crackdown on a 17-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli
rule.
   Israeli newspapers headlined Baker's criticism of Israel, giving
little attention to his calls to Palestinians to be more
conciliatory toward Israel and to abandon ``the illusion of control
over all of Palestine.''
   The Haaretz daily quoted unnamed diplomats in Washington as
saying they found Baker's speech to be ``very disappointing from
Israel's standpoint.'' The newspaper also said the speech was one
of the ``worst'' for Israel made by an American leader in the last
decade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890523-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 0232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Egypt-Arabs     05-23 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Arabs,0862</SECOND>
<HEAD>Egypt Returns to Arab League, But How?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Arab Summit ^AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By NEJLA SAMMAKIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The reactivation of Egypt's membership in
the Arab League seals President Hosni Mubarak's success in
returning to the fold without significant concessions.
   Few Egyptians, however, expect it to signal a return to the
heady days of the 1960s, when the magnetism of Gamal Abdel Nasser
put Egypt alone in the forefront of the Arab world.
   Magazine editor Makram Mohammed Ahmed, a Mubarak confidant,
said, ``Mubarak's Egypt has managed, with patience and perseverance
and consideration for Arab interests, to return to the Arab fabric.
   ``I don't think that Mubarak's Egypt wants a repeat of the role
(Egypt) played in the 1960s. The direction has changed.''
   All Arab League members except Libya approved of inviting Egypt
to the emergency summit today and Wednesday in Casablanca, Morocco.
   Even the Libyans did not directly attack Cairo's invitation but
professed to see no need for a summit. Syria, previously almost as
virulently anti-Egypt as Libya, welcomed the move.
   The summit was called to offer support to the Palestine
Liberation Organization in its campaign for acceptance in the
Arab-Israeli peace process and to discuss ways to stop Lebanon's
civil war.
   The Arab League suspended Egypt in 1979 to retaliate for the
peace treaty President Anwar Sadat signed that year with Israel.
All Arab states except Sudan, Somalia and Oman broke diplomatic
ties.
   Almost nine years later, in November 1987, with Iraq under
pressure from Iran in their long war, the league allowed its
members to resume ties with Egypt. All did except Libya, Syria and
Syria's client, Lebanon.
   Despite the realization at that summit that Egypt's strong
military was vital to counter threats from non-Arab Iran, the
league gave in to Syrian objections and did not reinstate Cairo.
   Its membership in the league reactivated, Egypt will achieve an
important victory _ ending 10 years' ostracism without touching
what still is the Arab world's only peace treaty with Israel.
   Until 1987, scrapping the treaty was an Arab condition for
restoring normalcy with the country that traditionally has served
as a political and military anchor for the Arabs.
   Despite Syria's apparent decision to ignore that condition, it
professes to expect Egypt to join Arab ranks against Israel. An
official statement said Damascus ``approves the return of Egypt to
its natural place in the (Arab) struggle,'' adding that Syria's
President Hafez Assad ``is aware that President Mubarak is not
Anwar Sadat.''
   If Mubarak is not Sadat, neither is he Nasser, Egypt's
charismatic president who called the first Arab League summit in
Cairo in January 1964 and inspired among Arab leaders a strong
sense of unity and identity.
   In the late 1950s, Nasser merged Egypt with Syria and, for a
while, North Yemen in a strongly anti-Western, pro-Moscow union
that dissolved in 1961. He sided with a new republican regime in
Iraq in 1961 and four years later sent 50,000 troops to help Yemeni
rebels overthrow their king.
   That move cost Egypt millions of dollars and the support of
Saudi Arabia, allied to Yemen's royal family. Military experts said
it also so weakened Egypt's military that Israel scored a stunning
victory in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Shunning such impulsive acts, Mubarak used careful, calculated
decision-making to shepherd Egypt back into the Arab fold.
   Mubarak has said repeatedly that the Arabs have learned to look
for mutual interest and economic welfare rather than emotional
rhetoric to deal with their friends. He said that is the attitude
that led to formation of a four-nation Arab Cooperation Council
with Jordan, Iraq and Yemen this year.
   ``Union cannot be achieved in an emotional venture by a
charismatic leader, or by a pioneering state, but ... by organized
work over a long time, based on the reality of differences and of
economic interests,'' Ahmed wrote in his column in last Thursday's
edition of his magazine Al-Mussawar.
   ``The power balance has changed. Egypt is not the greatest and
richest anymore. Egypt cannot assume the role or the responsibility
for the (Arab) community ... as in the '60s, because this has
exhausted it and created many problems.''
   Such talk would have been anathema to Nasser and is anathema to
Libya's Moammar Gadhafi, a devout follower of Nasser's ideas of one
borderless Arab nation from the Euphrates to the Atlantic.
   Since he took power in a 1969 coup that ended Libya's monarchy,
Gadhafi has been trying to merge his country with others in the
Arab world. The genesis of his quarrel with Egypt was Sadat's
rejection of a unity move in 1972.
   After Egypt disclosed that Mubarak would attend the Casablanca
summit, Libyan media announced a flurry of contacts between Tripoli
and the other Arab governments evidently designed to head off the
invitation or, failing that, the summit itself.
   No indication emerged that the others paid any attention.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR`S NOTE _ Nejla Sammakia has worked as a newswoman in the
Cairo bureau of The Associated Press since 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
