<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     05-23 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Sharply, Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended sharply higher against the
Japanese yen Tuesday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange fell.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
65.90 points Monday, shed 251.25 points, or 0.74 percent, to end
trading at 33,816.61.
   The dollar closed at 141.95 yen, up 1.50 yen from the previous
day's 140.45-yen finish. The currency started higher at 142.05 yen
and moved between 141.82 yen and 143.03 yen.
   The dollar, which opened sharply higher in Tokyo following a
similar upswing on overseas markets, was still bullish despite the
Bank of Japan's dollar-selling intervention, traders said.
   ``Even though a discount-rate hike is expected, it might not be
enough to make the yen attractive, unless the hike is far more than
0.5 percent,'' said an analyst with a commercial bank in Tokyo,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The central bank is expected to raise the official discount rate
by at least 0.5 percent from the current 2.5 percent. But the bank
has made no official announcement.
   Meanwhile, Japanese Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama said early
Tuesday that a decision on the discount rate could be based on
upcoming end-of-the month price data.
   He said, however, the dollar's current strength still does not
warrant a statement by Group-of-Seven nations at this time.
   ``It's not that kind of movement,'' he said.
   He also said that currency rates are only one factor in
formulating Japan's monetary policy, indirectly denying speculation
that the Bank of Japan would raise its discount rate solely on
foreign exchange considerations.
   Citing the White House's statement that the dollar's rise
against the yen is ``a matter of concern to the U.S.,'' Murayama
said the Bush administration is opposed to the stronger dollar but
noted that market movements are difficult to control.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the plunge was largely due
to the yen's sharp drop against the dollar.
   Kenji Ishizuka, a dealer with Daiwa Securities said share
prices, which were lower across the board, fell further following a
news report that the Bank of Japan and the Finance Ministry reached
an agreement to raise the official discount rate soon.
   ``It's been quite difficult for investors to determine the
direction of trading because of uncertainties over the exchange
rates,'' he said.
   The majority of market players remained cautious, trying to
watch the currency market movements, Ishizuka added.
   Higher interest rates usually discourage stock investment.
</TEXT>
