<FIRST>r i PM-IRA-Gibraltar     05-23 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IRA-Gibraltar,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Spanish Police Contradict Britain Over IRA Slayings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish police have flatly contradicted crucial
parts of the British government's justification for the slaying of
three unarmed IRA guerrillas in Gibraltar last year, a London
newspaper reported today.
   British authorities have always maintained that Special Air
Service commandos shot to death Mairead Farrell, Sean Savage and
Daniel McCann in the British colony on March 6, 1988 because they
feared the guerrillas were about to detonate a car bomb.
   But The Independent said in today's editions that five senior
Spanish police officers involved in the case have told the paper
that:
   _ British security forces were told the guerrillas' car was in
place in Gibraltar the day before the shootings, giving them at
least 15 hours to verify Spanish advice that it contained no bomb.
   _ The three guerrillas were not discovered by chance in
Gibraltar the day they were shot. Hours before they were killed,
they had been tracked by Spanish authorities to the border, which
they crossed on foot. The surveillance operation was then passed on
to the British.
   The paper did not name the Spanish police officers but reported:
``These claims undermine the British authorities' explanation...
   ``The (British) security forces claimed to have been taken by
surprise by the sudden arrival of the trio and the car and blamed
the Spanish police for sloppy surveillance work which allowed the
IRA members to slip undetected onto the Rock'' of Gibraltar.
   It quoted one senior Spanish police officer as saying: ``We told
the British we were 90 percent certain that the car contained no
bomb.''
   The paper commented in a separate editorial: ``The information
published today... makes it appear more likely that the three
terrorists were, in effect, executed.''
   A spokesman at the Ministry of Defense in London refused to
comment on the report. ``An inquest was held into these events and
that inquest came to its conclusions. There is nothing further we
would add,'' he said. The spokesman, in accordance with British
practice, declined to be named.
   The jury at a month-long inquest in Gibraltar that ended last
Sept. 30 ruled in a 9-2 vote that the three were lawfully killed.
   British authorities have said the guerrillas were preparing to
explode a car bomb during a parade by British soldiers. No bomb was
found in Gibraltar but two days after the shootings, Spanish police
found a car packed with explosives in Marbella that had been rented
by one of the three.
   The IRA said the three were on active service _ a euphemism for
a bombing or shooting mission _ when they were shot.
   The shootings raised a storm of protest among IRA supporters in
Northern Ireland and abroad, drew criticism from Prime Minister
Charles Haughey's government in the Republic of Ireland, and
triggered a wave of violence in Northern Ireland in which nine
people, including two British soldiers, died.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting British rule there. It
wants to unite the predominantly Protestant province with the 95
percent Catholic Republic of Ireland under socialist rule.
   The human rights group Amnesty International said last month
that the inquest jury acted on incomplete evidence and conflicting
testimony.
   Amnesty renewed its demand for a judicial inquiry and said the
inquest failed to allay suspicions of ``an official policy of
deliberate planned killings.''
   The Independent said ministers in Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's government remained adamant that the British version of
events given at the inquest was correct.
   The paper said some ministers dismissed the reported assertions
by Spanish police as part of a power struggle in Spain's socialist
government.
   It said both Spain and Britain were concerned that the
continuing dispute about the shootings could harm relations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
