<FIRST>r a PM-HUD-Pierce     05-23 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Pierce,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-HUD Secretary Accused of Choosing Subsidy Recipients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former HUD Secretary Samuel R. Pierce personally
decided which projects were subsidized under a program being
investigated as an improper source of Republican political funds, a
former HUD official said.
   The official, Thomas T. Demery, accused Pierce of improperly
promoting certain housing projects over others so that they would
receive millions of dollars in subsidies, The New York Times
reported in today's editions.
   Pierce headed the Department of Housing and Urban Development
throughout the Reagan administration.
   The program under fire provided an incentive for developers to
renovate housing by subsidizing rents for 15 years. An HUD audit
found widespread abuses in the program, including an absence of
competitive bidding.
   Demery told the Times that Pierce ordered allocations for some
projects as a result of requests from members of Congress and other
politicians.
   The HUD audit found that housing developers involved in the
subsidy program paid hundreds of thousands of dollars to prominent
Republican consultants who often had little or no experience in
housing.
   The audits suggested that the consultants were paid to make
contact with Pierce.
   The audit criticized Demery's role in the project, but Demery
blamed Pierce for ordering him to give the subsidies to certain
programs.
   The newspaper said Pierce did not return telephone calls. Pierce
is to testify before a House panel on Thursday.
</TEXT>
