<FIRST>r i PM-MissUniverse     05-23 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Miss Universe,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women From Around The World Compete For Miss Universe Title</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventy-six young women with diverse
backgrounds from around the world are competing for tonight's
crowning of Miss Universe 1989, $300,000 worth of prizes and the
prestige of worldwide visibility.
   The event, featuring ``Dynasty'' television program stars John
Forsythe and Emma Samms as hosts, is being beamed to more than 60
nations around the world, reaching a potential audience of 600
million viewers.
   Crowning the winner will be the woman who won the title last
year, Porntip Nakhirunkanok of Thailand.
   The contestants are judged in three categories: swimsuit,
evening gown and personality interview. Promoters say each
contestant is interviewed for five minutes with each judge before
the main event tonight.
   Rehearsals and taping began two weeks ago in this Caribbean
resort on the Yucatan Peninsula, which was ravaged last September
by Hurricane Gilbert.
   On their last day of rehearsals Monday, contestants danced, sang
and practiced their lines, getting ready for one of the biggest
events in their young lives.
   Between numbers, they wrote letters back home, chatted, buried
themselves in paperbacks or listened to coaching from advisers.
   During a break, Flavia Cavalcante Rebelo, Miss Brazil, said the
event was more than a simple beauty pageant.
   ``I need to represent my country well. People ask me about
Carnival, ecology in the Amazon. It's the lungs of the world.''
   Miss Haiti, Glaphyra Gregor Irma Jean-Louis, who is a physician,
said, ``All my life I've wanted to be in the Miss Universe
pageant.''
   ``No one expects to win,'' said Mike Clark, president of the
company producing the show. ``But each one hopes to win.''
   Although only one woman will wear the Miss Universe 1989 crown,
there have already been winners in several categories. Local judges
gave the best costume award to Miss Brazil for a colorful Carnival
outfit. Judged by her peers for the amity award was Miss Turks and
Caicos, Sharon Simons. The photographers gave Miss Australia, Karen
Wenden, the photogenic award.
   Clark describes all the contestants as winners.
   While organizers and participants are enthusiastic about the
beauty contest, some people consider this type of event demeaning
to women, saying it judges a woman's value on the basis of her
physical attractiveness.
   But Clark said the contestants don't feel degraded, adding that
physical beauty is not the only determining factor in who wins.
   ``Each girl has an equitable chance at winning,'' he said.
``When you talk to her, she's intelligent, she has a heart. I find
that in each of these women.''
   The judging process is ``an effort to get to know the girls
better,'' Clark said. ``They see there's a woman behind the body.''
   Pageant officials say the winner must devote her year-long reign
to charitable causes, as well as the promotional work for pageant
sponsors.
   For instance, Miss Universe 1988 has spoken at the United
Nations and with world leaders, including President Bush, about the
plight of underprivileged children.
</TEXT>
