<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-23 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Nikkei Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued to rise sharply against the
Japanese yen today, pushing down share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange, dealers said.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 65.90-point gainer Monday,
shed 251.25 points, or 0.74 percent, closing at 33,816.61.
   The dollar closed at 141.95 yen, up 1.50 yen from Monday's
140.45-yen finish. The dollar has climbed 7.51 yen since May 11,
and its closing today was the highest since 142.00 yen on Oct. 27,
1987.
   It opened at 142.05 yen and ranged between 141.82 yen and 143.03
yen in wide fluctuations that Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, a dealer with
Daiwa Bank, likened to ``a jet coaster.''
   Traders said the Bank of Japan intervened in the market in
efforts to check the dollar's rise.
   But continuing rumors that the central bank would soon raise its
discount rate, as well as feelings that the dollar would have
trouble staying above 143 yen, also helped bring the U.S. currency
down from today's highs, they said.
   ``The dollar's slip later in the afternoon was not because of
the Bank of Japan's dollar-selling effort but because of news that
the bank and the Finance Ministry agreed to raise the official
discount rate soon,'' Kinugasa said.
   Market players and analysts expect the central bank to raise the
key rate at least by 0.5 percentage point, from the current 2.5
percent. The rate affects interest charges by commercial banks and
higher interest rates tend to make the yen more attractive to
investors.
   ``When the authorities announce the decision, it could encourage
yen buying for a little while, but it will fade away by the time
the discount rate actually goes up,'' Kinugasa said.
   Another trader with a Japanese commercial bank in Tokyo,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said a discount rate increase
``might not be enough to make the yen attractive, unless the hike
is far more than 0.5 percent.''
   Japanese Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama, meanwhile, told Kyodo
News Service he had no knowledge of any decision to raise the rate.
   He said earlier today that a decision could be based on price
data compiled at the end of May.
   Noting a White House statement that the administration of
President Bush opposes a stronger dollar, Murayama said market
movements are difficult to control.
   Bank of Japan Gov. Satoshi Sumita said the central bank would
take appropriate measures when necessary to curb inflation.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said today's plunge was mainly
due to the yen's weakness against the dollar.
   ``The Nikkei was losing some 500 points at the beginning of the
afternoon session, but started to recover as short-term interest
rates stopped rising,'' said an analyst with Nomura Securities,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Higher interest rates discourage stock buying.
   Japanese investors are now watching moves on the foreign
exchange market, as well as the timing of any official discount
rate hike, the analyst said.
   ``But the discount rate hike might not be as discouraging as it
could be because it's been speculated for quite some time, so the
majority of market players have been well prepared for the hike,''
he said.
   Daiwa Securities dealer Kenji Ishizuka said, ``It's been quite
difficult for investors to determine the direction of trading
because of uncertainties over the exchange rates, which have become
very speculative.''
   The majority of market players remained on the sidelines
watching currency market movements, he said.
   Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 700
million shares, up from Monday's 550 million.
</TEXT>
