<FIRST>r i PM-UN-CentralAmerica     05-23 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Central America,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Says Honduras Blocking Deployment of U.N. Observers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras is blocking a U.N. plan to deploy
military observers who would try to stop cross-border attacks by
rebels fighting the Salvadoran and Nicaraguan governments, the U.N.
secretary-general said.
   Javier Perez de Cuellar made the comments in a letter last month
to five Central American countries. The correspondence, released
Monday, was part of an exchange of letters on the issue.
   U.N. officials have drawn up a plan to send about 100 military
observers and 60 pilots, drivers and administrators to monitor
Central American border areas, especially the Nicaragua-Honduras
and El Salvador-Honduras borders.
   Up to 11,000 Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras and receiving
support from the United States, operate from bases in Honduras.
   El Salvador says rebels fighting its government operate from
bases in Honduras _ without the Honduran government's permission _
and that Nicaragua supplies the Salvadoran insurgents.
   Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras of Honduras sent Perez
de Cuellar a handwritten note, also released Monday, that said his
country would agree to the border patrols only if Nicaragua drops a
case it has filed in the World Court against Honduras.
   Nicaragua made public a letter in which it said the World Court
ruled unanimously in December that Nicaragua has the right to
pursue its case, which accuses Honduras of cooperating with the
Contras.
   Nicaragua's foreign minister, Miguel d'Escoto, said in the
letter that Honduras has tried for two years to ``sabotage the
creation and establishment'' of a U.N. border patrol.
   Perez de Cuellar said in his letter that he could not send the
U.N. observers if Honduras links their deployment to ``conditions
over whose fulfillment I have no control.''
   The letter, sent to the foreign ministers of Honduras,
Nicaragua, Guatemala, El Salvador and Costa Rica, did not mention
Nicaragua's case in the World Court.
   Canada, Spain and West Germany have agreed to send personnel to
participate in the border patrol and the U.N. draft calls for at
least one Latin American contingent.
   Venezuela is ``under active consideration,'' said a U.N.
diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
