<FIRST>r i PM-China-Demands     05-23 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Demands,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Demands Broaden As Movement Expands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-China, Bjt ^By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's rebelling students at first asked only to
talk to the government as equals. Now they want the government to
fall.
   The turning point in China's student movement came Saturday,
when Premier Li Peng, charging that the students were being used by
malcontents determined to overthrow the Communist system, imposed
martial law on most of Beijing.
   During the first month of the students' drive for democratic
reform, their demands were modest. They wanted senior leaders to
meet them as equals, in a nationally telecast dialogue on how to
make China a freer and less corrupt society.
   The dialogue must also mean recognition of their newly formed
independent student unions, the activists said.
   In a more general sense, the students sought freedom of the
press, greater funding for education, public disclosures of the
incomes of high officials and a more sincere attempt to wipe out
the corruption that is endemic to the Communist Party and China's
bureaucracy.
   There were no deadlines or threats. Although some students put
up posters condemning the Communist system or calling for
multiparty elections, the majority stressed that they were willing
to work within the system.
   They said the marches, sit-ins, class boycotts and hunger
strikes would end if the government merely talked to them.
   Instead, the government declared martial law and ordered troops
to sweep the students from Tiananmen Square.
   That move has radicalized the student demands. Li, who a week
earlier visited hunger strikers in their hospitals, has taken on
the role of the villain, the military dictator who must be
overthrown.
   Students also are demanding the resignation of 84-year-old
senior leader Deng Xiaoping, the pragmatic author of China's reform
program. The students say he now is too old to grasp the needs of
changing China.
   Today, hundreds of thousands of students, workers and
intellectuals marched through Tiananmen Square to demand the
resignation of Li and Deng.
   ``Li Peng, step down, Deng Xiaoping, step down,'' the crowds
chanted.
   Dialogue, the students say, has no meaning when the opposing
party has resorted to military force to suppress them.
</TEXT>
