<FIRST>r i PM-Obit-deGroote     05-23 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-de Groote,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African Pianist Dead At Age 36</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African pianist Steven
de Groote, a Van Cliburn contest gold medal winner in 1977, has
died in a Johannesburg clinic of tuberculosis of the liver, the
hospital said today.
   De Groote, 36, died Monday at Brenthurst Clinic about 10 hours
after being transferred to the intensive care unit.
   A hospital spokesman, who did not want to be identified, said de
Groote had severe respiratory problems as well as the liver
problem. He was admitted to the clinic on May 8, suffering from
severe abdominal pains, the spokesman said.
   De Groote had recorded and played international concerts
extensively since winning the prestigious Van Cliburn piano
competition in Fort Worth, Texas in 1977. He was named artist in
residence at Texas Christian University, which plays host to the
preliminary rounds of the quadrennial competition.
   De Groote had come to South Africa to perform concerts with the
National Symphony Orchestra in Johannesburg, but that performance
last week and others were cancelled when he was admitted to the
clinic, according to the South African Broadcasting Corp.
   A Johannesburg newspaper, The Citizen, said De Groote's pianist
brother Andre had been at his bedside since Sunday.
   The paper said he is also survived by his father, former South
African Broadcasting Corp. orchestra leader Pierre de Groote, a
brother Oliver, a clarinetist, a brother Phillip, a cellist, a step
brother and step-sister.
   The Citizen said de Groote had been an associate professor of
music at Arizona State University from 1981 and a frequent visitor
to South Africa after leaving to study in the United States.
   De Groote's health had suffered since 1985 when he was in a bad
plane accident in Arizona.
</TEXT>
