<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-23 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mostly lower in early European
trading today. Gold prices rose.
   Foreign currency dealers said the market was rife with rumors
and speculation about higher interest rates or a new currency
stabilization initiative by the Group of Seven industrialized
nations.
   ``I see it (the dollar) move up a bit more, but then the central
banks will come in again,'' said a dealer at a Frankfurt bank.
   Others said recent concerted central bank intervention has been
weakened by the absence of the Deutsche Bundesbank.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.50 yen to a closing 141.95 yen despite
intervention by the Bank of Japan for the second day in a row.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 141.65 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday:
   _2.0075 West German marks, down from 2.0088
   _1.7825 Swiss francs, down from 1.7922
   _6.8020 French francs, up from 6.7990
   _2.2563 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2640
   _1,454.75 Italian lire, down from 1,455.75
   _1.1985 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1956
   In London, it cost $1.5805 to buy one pound, compared with
$1.5810 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $363.25 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $360.75. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $363.40.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $363.50 compared with $359.80 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.76 to close at a bid $363.97.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.18 a troy
ounce, up from Monday's $5.14.
</TEXT>
