<DOCNO> AP890523-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 0809EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CasinoRailroad     05-23 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Casino Railroad,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amtrak Inaugurates Service To Atlantic City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amtrak has restored train service
ferrying gamblers to the casinos from New York, Philadelphia and
Washington.
   The first Atlantic City Express carried 350 politicians and
other guests to the seaside resort Monday. It was the first
Atlantic City train since 1982.
   The trains make four round-trips a day from Philadelphia. A
fifth train originates in Washington and passes through
Philadelphia. Another route carries passengers once a day to and
from New York.
   Amtrak expects to attract 1.4 million riders a year and collect
$30 million in revenue. The project to restore the Atlantic City
line cost $101 million.
   The six-car, diesel-powered inaugural train was about 20 minutes
late getting to Philadelphia because of signal problems in
Baltimore, said Ira Silverman, Amtrak director of route marketing.
   ``It happens once out of a thousand times,'' he said, ``but of
course on an inaugural run, the gremlins come out.''
   The 67-mile trip from Philadelphia takes about 80 minutes and
costs $25 round trip.
   Atlantic City's beaches and casinos last year drew more than 33
million visitors.
</TEXT>
