<FIRST>r a PM-TelevisedManhunt     05-23 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Televised Manhunt,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medicaid Thief Begins Serving Prison Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who fled to Arizona before his sentencing
has begun serving a 7- to 21-year prison term for the biggest
Medicaid fraud in history, thanks to a tipster who turned him in
after seeing the case on a TV show.
   Sheldon Weinberg, convicted of stealing $16 million, was
imprisoned Monday after five months as a fugitive.
   Officials received hundreds of leads on his whereabouts after
his case was featured on NBC's ``Unsolved Mysteries.'' One call led
FBI agents to Scottsdale, Ariz., where Weinberg and his wife were
living under assumed names.
   Weinberg, 69, was returned to New York on Friday and brought to
court Monday. He was deeply tanned and made no statement during the
proceeding before Justice Ruth Moskowitz, who had sentenced him in
absentia.
   ``I do not consider this a white-collar crime,'' Moskowitz said.
``It is a crime of violence to all the people of New York City. It
is a crime of violence to the Medicaid recipients who should be
receiving the best medical care.''
   Weinberg and his two sons were convicted Nov. 30 of defrauding
Medicaid by submitting phony reimbursement claims from the health
clinic they operated.
   Deputy state Attorney General Edward J. Kuriansky said Weinberg
used the money to finance an $18,000-a-month New York apartment, a
$5 million lakefront mansion in Boca Raton, Fla., yachts and a
fleet of custom cars.
</TEXT>
