<SECOND>PM-Vernon Savings,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Thrift Executive Agrees To Plead Guilty in Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former savings and loan executive has agreed to
plead guilty to federal charges he took part in a scheme to donate
thrift funds to House Speaker Jim Wright and other politicians,
court records show.
   Federal law forbids corporate contributions to politicians.
   Pat L. Malone, former executive vice president of Vernon
Savings, admitted setting up a system that used thrift funds to
reimburse Vernon employees for making $55,000 in political
contributions in 1986, according to a criminal information filed in
federal court.
   The documents show Malone agreed to plead guilty to bank fraud
charges.
   Court records show donations included unspecified contributions
to Wright and $2,000 to 1986 Texas Tribute, a political committee
set up to seek donations for the Texas Democrat.
   Court records show other contributions included $2,000 to Sen.
Jake Garn, R-Utah; $1,000 to Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; $3,000
to the gubernatorial campaign of former Rep. Tom Loeffler of Texas,
and unspecified contributions to Rep. Bill Lowrey, D-Calif., and
former Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y.
   Federal regulators closed Vernon in 1987. It reopened as
Montfort Savings Association, then was sold in December and renamed
First Gibraltar Federal Savings Bank.
   There was no answer today at a Dallas telephone listing in the
name of a Pat Malone.
   The criminal information accused Malone of soliciting political
contributions from Vernon officers and having them file false
expense vouchers to reimburse themselves for the donations.
   A criminal information is filed in place of an indictment to
show charges to which a defendant has agreed to plead guilty.
</TEXT>
