<FIRST>r i PM-France-SovietProtest     05-23 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Soviet Protest,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Confirm Toxic Gas Killed Soviet Demonstrators</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French doctors working with American and Soviet
colleagues in Soviet Georgia confirmed today that some
demonstrators who died in a clash with police last month were
killed by toxic gases.
   On the basis of 16 autopsy results, doctors identified
Chloropicrine as responsible for some deaths, according to Medecins
sans Frontiers, a Paris-based medical humanitarian group.
   Chloropicrine was approved in the Soviet Union as a tear gas
until 1981, when it was reclassified as a ``suffocant'' or
asphyxiating gas for combat use, said Dr. Marc Gastellu Etchegorry
of the group.
   No details were immediately available and Etchegorry said
further questions would be addressed by the four-member team upon
their return to Paris on Wednesday.
   Violent clashes between police and Georgian nationalists in
Tbilisi, the republic's capital, left 19 people dead. Another
person was shot to death by police enforcing a curfew.
   Moscow officials admitted soldiers used a toxic gas to disperse
demonstrators but said they used a chemical agent similar to but
stronger than tear gas.
   In a statement, the French doctors said several hundred people
were admitted to hospitals more than a week later believing they
suffered secondary effects from the toxic gases. But the
international team concluded they suffered, instead, from panic
caused by psychological trauma.
   The French doctors worked with American colleagues from
Physicians for Human Rights, with Georgian doctors and with
representatives from the Georgian Health Ministry, according to the
statement.
   The investigators, invited by the local government and Soviet
human rights activist, Andrei Sakharov, examined and questioned
about 100 hospitalized patients, the statement said.
</TEXT>
