<HEAD>Former Associated Press Editor Dies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS one graf with where donations can be sent.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coleman Mobley, a free-lance writer and former
editor with The Associated Press, has died of respiratory
complications. He was 52.
   Mobley died early Monday at Bellevue Hospital Center, where he
was admitted April 18, said Peter Schectman, duty officer at the
Manhattan hospital.
   Mobley, a graduate of Georgetown University, joined the Decatur
(Ill.) Herald, now the Herald and Review, in 1965 and became its
urban affairs reporter two years later.
   In 1969, he was appointed to the editorial staff of the
Lindsay-Schaub newspaper group and covered the 1970 Illinois
Constitutional Convention for the group.
   After working as public information officer for the Illinois
Arts Council, he joined The Associated Press in Chicago in 1972. He
transferred to the AP General Desk in New York in 1978, leaving in
1984 to pursue free-lance assignments, concentrating on cultural
and legal issues.
   He is survived by his mother, Sarah McFarland of Oak Park, Ill.;
two sons, David of New York and Gregory of Springfield, Ill.; two
brothers and three sisters.
   The family asked that donations be made in Mobley's name to
God's Love We Deliver, a group that delivers meals to AIDS
patients. Its address is P.O. Box 1776, Old Chelsea Station, New
York, N.Y. 10113.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
