<FIRST>r i PM-China-Television     05-23 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Television,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Resume Satellite Transmissions For Foreign TV Networks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American and other foreign television networks
scrambled for satellite time today after Chinese authorities lifted
a martial law ban on transmissions.
   Major American networks, Japanese television and two Hong Kong
stations rushed to get their videotape out after China Central
Television announced that satellite services had been resumed.
   ``It was a zoo. There was only one path out,'' said John
Sheahan, CBS bureau chief in Beijing.
   The Chinese cut off transmissions and the military dismantled
satellite earth stations after the government declared martial law
in Beijing on Saturday to put down growing student-led unrest.
   Today one earth station was restored and the Chinese state-run
station began providing transmission facilities once more, Sheahan
said. All videotape was transmitted through London, with the
various networks taking turns sending in five- and 10-minute blocks.
   ``It was like going through a subway turnstile,'' Sheahan said.
``There was an enormous amount of goodwill among competitors.''
   Martial law regulations banned nearly all reporting activities
by foreign reporters in Beijing.
   Despite the ban, however, there has been little government
interference in foreign coverage of the more than month-old
student-led demonstrations for greater democracy.
</TEXT>
