<FIRST>r a PM-TeachersContract     05-23 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teachers Contract,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contract Would Give Boston Teachers Greater Say in Classroom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston's teachers would get a 7 percent raise
three years in a row and more power in their classrooms but would
be held more responsible for their students' performance under
terms of a tentative contract.
   School Superintendent Laval S. Wilson and teachers union
President Edward Doherty announced the pact Monday and called it a
``landmark agreement on education reform.''
   But city officials warned that because of a state budget crisis,
the city might not be able to afford the raises for the union's
6,000 members.
   ``I do not see, at this time, how a contract of this magnitude
can be funded, given the fiscal uncertainties facing the
commonwealth,'' Mayor Raymond Flynn said.
   The contract must be ratified by the School Committee and then
is expected to be approved by the union in June.
   Teachers would have more of a say in choosing staff and would
have a role in setting curriculum and budget priorities through
school councils. In return, teachers would be subjected to more
detailed reviews of their performance.
   Union and school officials say the pact is modeled on teachers'
contracts in Dade County, Fla., and Rochester, N.Y.
</TEXT>
