<DOCNO> AP890523-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     05-23 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Hold 237 People in Troubled Province</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have jailed 237 ethnic
Albanians without charge in the volatile province of Kosovo, a
regional official said today.
   Those detained ``are people who acted in the interests of
Albanian nationalism and separatism and who in Kosovo exposed their
hostile positions,'' said Jusuf Karakusi, the province's interior
minister, the state Tanjug news agency said.
   Kosovo was the scene in February and March of mass
demonstrations and violent clashes between ethnic Albanians and
Yugoslav security forces. The battles killed at least 25 people,
including two policemen.
   Ethnic Albanians, who comprise about 85 percent of Kosovo's
population of 1.8 million, were protesting constitutional changes
that limited the wide autonomy the province had previously enjoyed.
The new rules gave Serbia, of which the region is an administrative
part, a greater say Kosovo's affairs.
   The imposition of a state of emergency was followed by a
crackdown in which more than 800 people were arrested on charges
stemming from the unrest.
   An additional ``237 have been detained under isolation
measures,'' which are permitted under emergency law, said Karakusi.
   Among those jailed without charges or trial are prominent ethnic
Albanian politicians, intellectuals and other community leaders who
opposed the constitutional amendments, press reports said.
   Among them is Azem Vllasi, the former local Communist party
chief and a leading opponent of Serbian strongman Slobodan
Milosevic.
   The detentions without trial ``represent a flagrant violation
not only of (the prisoners') civil rights but also of universal
human rights,'' said a commentary in the latest issue of Danas,
Yugoslavia's leading newsmagazine.
   ``The legal status of the detainees is undefined and unclear
--they are not supposed to be in jail but have spent months behind
bars,'' Danas said.
</TEXT>
