<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China 3rdLd-Writethru a0513 05-23 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0513,0879</SECOND>
<HEAD>One Million Protest Against Martial Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with protest, report that Li stripped
of duties, other details; no pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One million people defied martial law for a fifth
straight straight day today and streamed into the streets to demand
the resignation of Premier Li Peng.
   The demonstration, led by students, teachers, government
employees and intellectuals, was the largest show of public wrath
toward Li since he imposed martial law on Saturday to quell a
student-led campaign for democratic reforms.
   ``Li Peng step down,'' the crowds chanted as they marched past
Tiananmen Square where tens of thousands of students have
maintained a 10-day vigil for a freer and less corrupt society.
   ``People unite and break the militaristic coup,'' read one
poster. ``Bury the cult of the individual. End old people's
politics,'' said one in reference to senior leader Deng Xiaoping,
another target of the marchers.
   Hundreds of thousands also turned out in Shanghai, China's
second-largest city. They also turned out in Hong Kong and Macao,
colonies which revert to Chinese control in the late 1990s.
   Authorities today lifted a martial law ban on foreign network
coverage of the Beijing protests and satellite feeds resumed.
   The march came amid increasing speculation that the beleaguered
Li would be forced from office for refusing to hold talks with the
students and resorting instead to military force to end their
movement. Rumor and innuendo filled Beijing about battles for
control between liberal and conservative wings of the ruling
Communist Party.
   Hong Kong commercial radio reported that the Politburo, the
Communist Party's top decision-making body, decided today to strip
Li, a 60-year-old former electrical engineer, of both his
government and party posts.
   It said Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang, whose position was
jeopardized when he advocated compromise with the students and
opposed Li's hardline stance, will resume his duties.
   The report could not be immediately confirmed.
   One indication that Li might be in trouble was the first
official acknowledgement that the premier was the primary object of
demonstrators' anger.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said 1 million people took to
the streets and ``the overwhelming majority of the slogans of the
parade were directed against the chief leader of the State
Council,'' namely Li.
   It said other slogans were ``withdraw the troops and lift
martial law'' and ``safeguard the constitution and guarantee human
rights.'' Leading intellectuals from China's most famous
think-tank, the Chinese Academy of Sciences, led the protest. They
accused Li of staging a military coup in his struggle against Zhao.
   Tens of thousands of students and workers also marched through
the streets of Shanghai today to demand that Li step down,
according to Jason Hurtado, a professor at the city's Fudan
university. Throughout the day, about 200,000 city residents milled
around expectantly.
   Overnight, student leaders printed and distributed thousands of
posters and pamphlets calling for workers to support students and
people gathered around to read the inscriptions.
   In Macao today, 120,000 people poured into the narrow streets in
the Portugese colony's largest march to support the pro-democratic
movements in Beijing. They urged Premier Li Peng to step down and
criticized Beijing's press censorship in a march that paralyzed
traffic for two hours.
   In Hong Kong, protests continued for a fourth straight day. In
all, about 10,000 students marched through the city and 2,000
boycotted classes.
   Workers used a large crane to replace a portrait of
revolutionary leader Mao Tse-tung on the gate of the Forbidden City
across from Tiananmen Square. Earlier today, two men splattered
paint on the famed portrait of the founder of Communist China.
   A witness said the two men, wearing the white headbands of
student protesters, were jumped on by students and taken to
Tiananmen Square. Student leaders later insisted the men were not
students.
   Thousands stopped to watch the 90-minute operation of lifting
the new portrait into place. They cheered and clapped when the work
was completed.
   As in the previous three nights under martial law, a constant
stream of supporters walked, bicycled and motorcycled around the
square, occupied by tens of thousands of students.
   Most of the troops that moved into city outskirts Friday night
had withdrawn to points further away from the city, and residents
had removed many of the barricades they had set up to block a troop
advance into the city.
   The students decided earlier in the day to continue their
occupation of the square even though thousands of demonstrators had
returned to their schools. More than half of the protesters on the
square hail from outside Beijing.
   ``I voted that we should go back because many of the Beijing
students are alrady leaving,'' said Gua Haifeng, a student leader
from Beijing University. ``But the student union insists on
struggling until the end. They want to see the government fall.''
   ``We just couldn't leave,'' said a student from Lanzhou, a
western city about 750 miles from Beijing. ``Tiananmen Square is
the center of our student movement. If it died, the movement in
Lanzhou and all around China would die, too.''
</TEXT>
