<FIRST>r i PM-Bulgaria-Turks     05-23 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bulgaria-Turks,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Say Ethnic Turks Die In Clashes With Security Forces</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic Turks were reported killed and
injured when security forces in Bulgaria opened fire during weekend
protests, emigres and diplomats said today.
   They said the confrontations were the most violent outbursts
since a campaign in the early 1980s by Bulgaria's communist
authorities to get ethnic Turks to adopt Bulgarian-sounding names,
restrict their Moslem religious rites and to bar the Turkish
language in public.
   A diplomat reached in Sofia said he has heard reports of
fatalities but did not know how many casualties there were when
4,000 to 5,000 protesters clashed with troops in Razgrad, 160 miles
east of Sofia. About 200 people were arrested, he said.
   The area in northeastern Bulgaria is home to many of the 900,000
ethnic Turks in the Balkan country.
   Tanks, helicopters and a heavy security force presence were
deployed around Razgrad and Shumen, where demonstrations also took
place, and communications to Razgrad were cut, the diplomat said.
The area is home to many of the 900,000 ethnic Turks in the Balkan
state.
   Emigre sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said troops
opened fire on thousands of people who walked from nearby villages
to protest in northeastern Kaolinovo on Saturday, demanding more
rights for ethnic Turks.
   Troops and police let the protesters into the town, but later
opened fire on the crowd, the source said.
   Another emigre said thousands of ethnic Turks also took to the
streets near the ethnic Turkish cities of Kurdzhali and Dzebel, in
southern Bulgaria.
   A spokeswoman of the Committee of the Rights of Man, a
government-approved group in Bulgaria, told The Associated Press by
telephone from Sofia that she could not confirm the reported
protests or killings.
   There is a long history of conflict between the Turks and
Bulgarians, who were under Turkish rule for 500 years before 1863.
</TEXT>
