<FIRST>u a PM-RobberyTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0492 05-23 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Robbery Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0492,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Starts Today for Two Accused in Bank Robbery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with jury selection under way.
PICKS UP 11th graf a0449, `Earlier this ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jury selection began under tight
security today for the bank robbery trial of two men, one of whom
is also accused of murdering a member of the gang to keep him from
testifying.
   The trial in federal court is the culmination of a case in which
another witness died of unknown causes and some suspects have been
accused of plotting to break out of jail, kill other witnesses and
flee to the Cayman Islands.
   Because of the alleged threats, courtroom halls were lined with
a metal detector, an X-ray machine and a handful of federal agents.
   John P. McCoy, 43, of Slater's Branch, Ky., and Doyle David
Moore, 27, of Lovely, Ky., are accused of conspiracy to commit bank
robbery and intimidating witnesses.
   McCoy is also charged with shooting to death Russell M. Davis of
Martin County, Ky., who was part of the robbery gang.
   The prosecutor said it was a chore coming up with an opening
statement.
   ``These people are just too zany,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Ben Bryant. ``They've been watching too much television.''
   Authorities say McCoy masterminded the 1987 robbery of $286,000
from the Matewan National Bank in Kermit, 40 miles from Huntington,
and was joined by Moore, Davis and Harold D. ``Boonie'' Runyon, 39,
of Forest Hills, Ky.
   Davis met with Secret Service agents in Jacksonville, Fla.,
shortly after the robbery and agreed to become a witness. Days
later, authorities say, Runyon and McCoy took him to the top of a
Kentucky mountain and shot him in the head.
   ``He was a threat to us,'' Runyon said Friday in pleading guilty
to the slahing and conspiracy to commit robbery. ``There was no
reasoning with him. We took him to a hill and shot him.''
   Earlier this month, Timothy Lynn Sammons, 30, of Beauty, Ky.,
who reportedly was to be called as a witness in the trial, was
found dead in his car. Sammons, a friend of Davis, appeared before
the grand jury that indicted the alleged bank robbers.
   Martin County Coroner Jay Hinkle said Monday the cause of death
still has not been determined but said foul play is not suspected.
   And McCoy, Runyon and four others _ including McCoy's son _ were
charged May 6 in an alleged plot to break McCoy, Runyon and another
man out of jail, kill five witnesses and help the prisoners flee to
the Cayman Islands.
</TEXT>
