<FIRST>r i AM-Lyubimov     05-23 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lyubimov,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Citizenship Restored to Theater Director Yuri Lyubimov</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has restored the citizenship of
avant-garde director Yuri Lyubimov, founder of the Taganka Theater
who moved abroad in 1984 after being fired and ousted from the
Communist Party, Tass said Tuesday.
   Lyubimov, 71, returned briefly to the Soviet Union a year ago at
the invitation of the government, which said it was acting in the
spirit of reforms by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev. He came back
to stage another production in January.
   The official news agency said Lyubimov was stripped of his
citizenship ``at the height of the stagnation period'' _ the
current leadership's reference to the era of the late Soviet leader
Leonid I. Brezhnev.
   ``But in the years of perestroika, which has dramatically
changed things in every field of life in Soviet society, including
art, it became possible for Lyubimov to begin working with the
Taganka troupe again,'' Tass said.
   According to Tass, the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet restored
Lyubimov's citizenship at the director's request.
   Since leaving the country in 1984, Lyubimov has been living and
working mostly in Europe, but spent some time in the United States,
staging Dostoyevsky's ``Crime and Punishment'' in 1987.
   He is working in Moscow on a play about village life, titled
``Alive,'' a play banned 20 years ago, Tass said.
</TEXT>
