<FIRST>u a PM-SwindallTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0531-487 05-23 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Swindall Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0531-487,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Juror Questioning Begins in Former Congressman's Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with jury questioning under way,
judge's comment; PICKS UP 5th graf a0487, `In one ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers began questioning 70 potential jurors
today for the perjury trial of former U.S. Rep. Pat Swindall on
charges of lying to a grand jury about a loan deal.
   Defense attorneys asked the judge to strike one of the first
people interviewed after he admitted having ``subliminal'' feelings
against Swindall.
   But the juror later said he would be able to follow the doctrine
that a defendant is innocent until proven guilty, and U.S. District
Judge Richard Freeman allowed him to remain. ``You can't get a
perfect jury,'' Freeman said.
   The judge has said he wants to see if an impartial jury can be
seated before ruling on Swindall's request to move the trial out of
town because of publicity.
   On Monday, Freeman said Swindall's attorneys want the court to
exclude from evidence secretly recorded talks among Swindall,
money-launderer Charles LeChasney and an undercover agent. Freeman
did not immediately rule on the request.
   The former two-term Republican congressman was indicted Oct. 17
on 10 counts of perjury. Each charge carries 10 months to five
years in prison.
   The 38-year-old conservative evangelical is accused of lying
under oath to a federal grand jury in 1988 about his dealings with
LeChasney and with Mike Mullaney, a federal agent posing as a money
broker, possibly for drug dealers.
   Swindall lost his seat representing Atlanta's eastern suburbs to
Democrat Ben Jones in November's election.
   Prosecution briefs unsealed earlier showed the government
building a claim that Swindall plotted to lie publicly about a
shady loan deal, then did lie about it.
   In one brief unsealed in the court, prosecutors argued that
public statements Swindall made after his allegedly false grand
jury testimony are relevant to the case because they point to ``a
continuation of Swindall's attempts to limit his own potential
criminal exposure.''
   Swindall's attorneys want the tapes thrown out, on the grounds
that they have no bearing on whether he perjured himself earlier.
   In one conversation that prosecutors want to enter as evidence,
Mullaney, posing as a broker funneling Swindall money through
LeChasney as middleman, asked Swindall what he would say if anyone
started asking questions.
   ``What's wrong if I say I sold the note to someone Charles
LeChasney introduced me to and I don't know what his name is and I
really didn't care.'' the congressman replied.
   ``There's no question in this transaction that I am basically
using Charles as my buffer,'' Swindall said in another conversation
related in the prosecution document.
  
</TEXT>
