<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Acupuncture-Addicts     05-23 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Acupuncture-Addicts,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acupuncture Used to Treat Addicts In Special Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drugs addicts at the Dade County Stockade got the
point today _ 10 points to be exact _ as part of a treatment
program using acupuncture.
   The new program will treat 1,500 inmates at a cost of about
$600,000 a year, said Circuit Judge Herbert Klein, the county's
anti-drug coordinator.
   ``I don't feel there's any other way I could be helped. This is
the last way,'' said Terry Henderson, 20. He described the
insertion of 10 two-inch needles in his ears as feeling ``like a
mosquito bite.''
   Henderson is serving a one-year sentence for cocaine sale and
possession. He said he smoked crack daily before his arrest.
   The program is aimed at helping addicts relax and reducing their
craving for drugs. But some doctors say there haven't been enough
scientific studies to determine if acupuncture actually eases
withdrawal symptoms.
   Acupuncturist Bill Berlin, who has been pushing for the program
for four years, said he has an 80 percent success rate in private
practice. But he said the jail program would be more difficult.
   ``Part of the recovery is rebuilding their lives as well as
eliminating the need for drugs,'' he said. ``Counseling is the
other half of the drug treatment.''
   Developed more than 2,500 years ago by the Chinese, acupuncture
is a technique to relieve pain and stress by inserting needles into
specific points on the body that are believed to affect organs and
bodily functions.
   Klein endorsed the program, which originated at a New York City
hospital, after finding at least three-quarters of the defendants
entering the Miami courts are on drugs.
   In the acupuncture program that started Monday, 224 inmates will
undergo daily ``needling,'' as Klein called it, and intensive
therapy for four weeks.
   For the next 12 weeks, prisoners will receiveless-frequent
acupuncture treatments while attending educational and vocational
programs and joining work details.
   In the final 30 days of treatment, inmates will be moved to a
detention center, assigned to kitchen duty and continue drug abuse
treatment.
</TEXT>
