<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Yeltsin     05-23 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin, Now a Parliamentarian, Relieved of Government Job</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party maverick Boris N. Yeltsin was
relieved of his government job Tuesday at his request following his
landslide election to the new Soviet parliament, Tass reported.
   Yeltsin, 58, was named first deputy chairman of the State
Construction Committee after being fired as Moscow party boss in
November 1987. He lost the important party post after lashing out
at the slow pace of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms.
   Yeltsin had vowed to quit his government job if he were elected
to the new Soviet parliament, the Congress of People's Deputies. He
ran on an anti-establishment ticket challenging the powers of party
and state bureaucrats, and Moscow voters gave him almost 90 percent
of the vote in elections held in March.
   The congress holds its first session Thursday. Yeltsin was
discharged from his State Construction Committee job by the
Presidium, the nation's top executive body, on Tuesday, the
official news agency said.
