<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-NewZealand-Quake 1stLd-Writethru a0520 05-23 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Zealand-Quake, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0520,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Big Quake Shakes Seabed Off New Zealand</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details and Nepal quake; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A massive undersea earthquake was
recorded today north of Australia's Macquarie Island near New
Zealand, officials said.
   Kevin McCue, senior research scientist at the Australian
Seismological Centre, said the quake occurred at 6:54 a.m. EDT and
measured about 7.2 on the Richter scale.
   The U.S. Geological Survey reported the quake measured 8.2 on
the Richter Scale and said it was the strongest temblor this year
anywhere in the world. It was the strongest since one measuring 8.1
on October 20, 1986, in the Kermadec Islands in the Pacific, the
survey said.
   McCue said a stretch of seabed apparently was ruptured in a
large movement at the junction of the Australian and Pacific
plates, about 850 miles east of Christchurch, New Zealand,
according to the Australian Associated Press.
   Alison Clifton, Australia's Macquarie Island station leader,
said by telephone that a ``fairly severe'' quake rattled buildings
at the base but did no damage, the Australian news agency reported.
   ``It was pretty noisy,'' she said. ``It was certainly sizeable.''
   In Nepal, an earth tremor measuring 5 on the Richter scale
rocked Manebhanjyang, 175 miles east of Katmandu, at 4:25 p.m. EDT
Monday, according to the department of mines and geology.
   It said there were no reports of casualties or property damage.
   The open-ended Richter scale is a measure of the energy released
by an earthquake, as measured by ground motion recorded on a
seisomograph.
   Each increase of one number, as in a jump from magnitude 5.5 to
6.5, means the ground motion is 10 times greater. A quake of 3.5
can cause slight damage in populated areas, while a quake of 6.0
can cause severe damage. In March 1964 an earthquake in Alaska hit
8.5 on the Richter scale, killing 114 people.
</TEXT>
