<FIRST>u i PM-Poland-Students 1stLd-Writethru a0519 05-23 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Students, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0519,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses To Register Student Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with reason for judge's decision;
picks up 3rd pvs: Students said...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The provincial court refused today to
register the pro-Solidarity Independent Students Association,
causing howls of surprised anger and chants of ``Down with
Communism!'' from a packed courtroom.
   Warsaw Provincial Judge Danuta Widawska was unable to explain
the decision in the tumult that followed it.
   Provincial court chairman, Edward Sadkowski, later said the
decision stemmed from the student group's claim of the right to
strike. Polish law does not specifically grant students that right,
he said.
   Students said they may boycott June 4 parliamentary elections
because of the decision. Some accused the court of trying to
confuse and divide the opposition before the elections.
   Before the decision, a lawyer for the student association, known
by its Polish initials NZS, argued that registering the group would
fulfill the promises that communist authorities made during talks
with the Solidarity-led opposition.
   Lawyer Piotr Andrzejewski noted authorities objected to the
association's statute permitting strikes. But he told the court
such strikes have a long tradition in Poland and are not forbidden.
   About 200 students angered by the rejection marched for about a
half mile from the court chanting, ``Down With Communism!'' and
``We will make a second China!'' referring to huge student
demonstrations in Beijing.
   Scuffles broke out with police when they reached a main square,
and several protesters were arrested.
   Piotr Czerwiec, a student leader, said the association would
appeal the court's decision to the Supreme Court this week, but it
appeared unlikely a decision could be made before the June voting.
   Students have played an active role in helping Solidarity
candidates in elections bringing the first democratic voting in
Poland since World War II. Registration of the students'
assocation, like the legalization of the independent workers union
Solidarity and the farmers union Rural Solidarity, was a condition
for the opposition agreeing to participate in the elections.
   All three organizations were banned when martial law was imposed
in Poland in December 1981. The other two were legalized during the
talks earlier this year with communist authorities on enacting
reforms.
   Solidarity is waging a spirited campaign for candidates to a new
100-member Senate, the first fully democratic legislative chamber
in the East bloc. The opposition also is contesting 161 seats in
the existing 460-member parliament. The rest are reserved for the
ruling Communist Party and its allies.
   Some student leaders blamed older Solidarity leaders for not
fighting more for their association.
   ``Solidarity ... did not press hard enough,'' said Andrzej
Jesionowski, a member of the student association's National
Commission.
   Earlier, about 300 students packed the courtroom with a handful
of older Solidarity advisers. The rejection came as a shock.
   ``Down with Communism!'' someone shouted as soon as Mrs.
Widawska announced the rejection. Then the whole room erupted in
the angry chants and stamping feet.
   ``Do you want to hear the justification?'' the judge said
through her microphone.
   ``No!'' students shouted back, and Mrs. Widawska and two
assistant judges hurriedly left the bench.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
