<FIRST>r p PM-NYCMayor     05-23 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Mayor,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Goldin Announces for Mayor: `I Can Make NYC Work'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin entered the
mayor's race today, saying New Yorkers want a change after 12 years
under Ed Koch.
   The 53-year-old Democrat, who has held the elective
comptroller's post nearly 16 years, said he has the honesty,
toughness, compassion and experience to run the city.
   He said he senses ``a tremendous feeling among the people of New
York. They want a change.''
   Goldin said he would start a Department of Children, expand the
student dropout program, use more pension funds for housing and
``take the handcuffs off the cops.''
   Also running on the Democratic side besides Koch is Manhattan
Borough President David Dinkins. Among the Republicans, former U.S.
Attorney Rudolph Giuliani faces cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder.
   Prior to his announcement of candidacy today, Goldin today
declared the city ``can be livable.''
   ``One of the reasons I'm running for mayor ... is that I have
the experience and knowledge ... to make it work and to make it
function,'' he said.
