<HEAD>120,000 People March in Macao to Support Beijing Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 120,000 people poured into Macao's narrow
streets Tuesday in the Portuguese colony's largest march to support
the pro-democracy movement in Beijing.
   Students, workers, teachers, civil servants, businessmen and
native Portuguese joined the march, which paralyzed the colony's
traffic for two hours.
   The marchers handed an open letter to the Macao branch of the
Xinhua News Agency, China's unofficial representative in the
colony, which is to revert to Chinese rule in 1999.
   They urged Chinese Premier Li Peng to step down, protested
Beijing's press restrictions and vowed support for the students.
   Marches continued for the fourth consecutive day in Hong Kong,
while about 100 singers recorded a song in support of the students.
   About 8,000 technical institute students marched on Hong Kong
Island while 2,000 students from the City Polytechnic of Hong Kong
boycotted class and marched in downtown areas of the Kowloon
peninsula across the harbor.
   The British colony of Hong Kong is to revert to Chinese rule in
1997.
