<FIRST>r i AM-China-Mao     05-23 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Mao,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three From Mao's Birthplace in Custody For Vandalizing His Portrait</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEJ7,8,9</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Student activists Tuesday turned over to police
three young men whose zeal for the democracy movement led them to
vandalize the famed portrait of Mao Tse-tung that looks out over
Tiananmen Square.
   The three were hustled off by students occupying Tiananmen
Square soon after they threw black and red paint on the nearly
30-foot-high portrait of communist China's founding father.
   The official Xinhua News Agency later identified them as a
middle school teacher, a newspaper arts editor and a factory
worker, all from southern Hunan province, Mao's birthplace. All
were in their 20s.
   Xinhua said they arrived in Beijing on May 19 to participate in
the student movement for democratic reforms.
   Splotches of paint were scattered on Mao's neck, collar and one
eyebrow, and one long line of paint dripped down the side of his
mouth and nose.
   Workers later covered the portrait with green canvas, and
Tuesday evening a large crane appeared to hoist a new portrait into
place over the gate to the Forbidden City.
   Thousands of spectators, many who had come to the square to see
or support the student demonstrators, stopped to watch. The crowds
cheered and clapped when the job was completed. The old Mao was
driven off in a flatbed truck.
   Mao is regarded by most Chinese as a flawed figure who caused
great suffering with his purges of intellectuals, the economic
disaster of the Great Leap Forward and the catastrophic 1966-76
Cultural Revolution.
   However, he is still revered by Chinese as the father of the
nation.
   Some demonstrators in recent weeks have carried portraits of Mao
to show they preferred the high principles of a revolutionary such
as Mao to the corruption and self-interest they believe is
characteristic of many of today's leaders.
</TEXT>
