<FIRST>r w AM-GovernmentExecutives     05-23 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Government Executives,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Less Than Half Say They Would Take Federal Jobs Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than half the federal senior-level
managers and executives responding to a survey said they were sure
they would go to work for the government again if they could
retrace their careers.
   And 71 percent said they felt their agency was experiencing a
``brain drain'' _ the departure of bright people for better
opportunities. They pointed to federal pay and benefits that have
failed to keep pace with non-government work, to better jobs
outside government and to a negative public image of federal
employees.
   Those who said they would not work for the government if they
were starting out again cited those same factors, plus the quality
of their leaders and the degree of bureaucractic control over their
jobs.
   The survey, made public Tuesday, was conducted by the alumni
association of the Federal Executive Institute, which offers a
four-week training course for senior people in government.
   Questionnaires mailed to 2,231 members last October drew
responses from 1,937 _ 80 percent of them still with the government.
   Forty-six percent of those who responded said they would choose
government work again while 24 percent would not and 28 percent
were unsure. The remaining 2 percent did not answer that question.
   Consistent with that result, 48 percent said they would not
encourage young people to have a federal career while only 41
percent would encourage them.
   Those who said they would chose government jobs if they had to
do it over again cited the challenging nature of the work, their
commitment to public service, personal satisfaction, the chance of
professional growth or advancement, the ability to have an
influence on public affairs, the pay and benefits, the degree of
management authority they exercise and job security.
   Even though less than half said they would do it again, far more
_ 69 percent _ expressed satisfaction with their jobs. Only 15
percent expressed disatisfaction.
   Fifty-four percent said they think the quality of newly employed
government people is lower than it was 10 years ago.
</TEXT>
