<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BlackEducation     05-23 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Education,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scholars Say Steps Would Help Black Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A committee of prominent black scholars called
Tuesday for smaller, more personal schools, significant parental
involvement and other steps they said would help black children
achieve greater academic success.
   ``We believe it is the school's responsibility to overcome
social barriers that limit academic progress,'' said Sara Lawrence
Lightfoot, a Harvard University education professor and member of
the Committee on Policy for Racial Justice.
   ``What we demand is this: that the schools shift their focus
from the supposed deficiencies of the black child and the alleged
inadequacies of black family life to the elimination of the
barriers that stand in the way of academic success,'' Lightfoot
said.
   She spoke at a news conference to release the committee's
publication, ``Visions of a Better Way: A Black Appraisal of Public
Schooling.''
   Such a shift is essential if the United States is to have the
highly trained and educated work force it needs in the near future,
the publication said.
   ``All of our fates, all of our skins are wrapped up in better
education for black students,'' Lightfoot said. Unlike in earlier
times, she said, ``people have to stay in school to become
functioning members of the work force.''
   The publication cites barriers to black academic achievement,
among them deep-rooted social and economic inequities, mistaken
notions and stereotypes about lower-income people, misuse of
standardized testing and rigid tracking systems.
   Lightfoot, the lead author, said the most important way to
improve education for black children is to make schools more human
and personal. She said schools should be smaller or large schools
should be divided into schools-within-schools to combat the
invisibility that minority students often feel.
   Parents must be at the heart of the effort, she said, playing
significant roles in decisions ranging from curriculum to
disciplinary techniques.
   Lightfoot said the committee does not recommend abolishing
standardized testing or tracking systems that often put black
children on vocational rather than academic paths at very early
ages.
   But she said tests should never be used as the sole measure of a
student's achievements or intelligence and children should be
re-evaluated frequently so that they aren't permanently consigned
to ``a single box or category or track.''
   ``The whole system needs to be made much more subtle, much more
flexible, much more discerning,'' she said.
   The essay calls on the black community to make improving the
public schools its principal objective in the next decade. It says
the black middle class and black institutions such as churches and
fraternal organizations have a special responsibility to set
expectations and support academic development among black youth.
   Roger Wilkins, a history professor at George Mason University in
Fairfax, Va., said black institutions are trying to meet the new
needs confronting them. ``We're trying to encourage more
institutions to adapt more rapidly,'' he said.
   But Wilkins added that ``we are not at all saying that our
community alone can combat the street culture. ... We are not here
to let the larger community off the hook'' when it comes to dealing
with drugs, crime, job opportunities, medical care and other needs.
   The committee recommends expanded funding for Head Start and
Chapter 1, the federal government's major programs for at-risk and
disadvantaged students. It also suggests closer ties between
schools and social services, recruitment of more black teachers and
an expanded curriculum that recognizes the realities of black
children's lives.
</TEXT>
