<FIRST>r a AM-InmateReleased     05-23 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inmate Released,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long-Sought Burglary Suspect Released From Crowded Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A burglary suspect eluded police for months
then was released two days after his capture under a federal court
order aimed at reducing jail overcrowding.
   ``It's very frustrating,'' said police Lt. James Dickerson. ``We
spend money and time looking for people and then they're right back
out.''
   Frank Washington, 32, of Pittsburgh, had been sought by city
police since January in a series of burglaries.
   Detectives arrested him May 15 after tracking him to a bar, and
he was released from Allegheny County Jail two days later. Because
of overcrowding, Washington did not have to post his $20,000 bond.
   Police Cmdr. Ronald Freeman complained that the court order on
jail population, issued by U.S. District Judge Maurice Cohill,
allows criminals to return to the streets.
   ``I certainly believe Judge Cohill has contributed greatly to
our crime statistics,'' Freeman said.
   The judge consistently refuses to comment on the issue.
   Warden Charles Kozakiewicz said he had no choice but to free
Washington under the judge's order _ he was among the prisoners
with the lowest bonds and was not accused of any of 14 serious
crimes that warrant keeping inmates in jail despite their bonds.
   ``It's distasteful to me and certainly not to my liking to
release anybody from jail,'' he said.
</TEXT>
