<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1355EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-FusionFrustration 1stLd-Writethru a0485 05-23 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion Frustration, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0792</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemists Hole Up in Lab After Stinging Criticism</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to UPDATE with conference under way; PICKS
UP 3rd graf pvs, `They also ...'; INSERTS 6 grafs after 11th graf pvs,
`However, many ...' to UPDATE with findings by scientists in Texas and
Sweden.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stung by sharp criticism from fellow
scientists, chemists Stanley Pons and Martin Fleischmann shun
friend and foe alike these days to concentrate on a new round of
cold-fusion experiments.
   The pair have ignored an invitation to defend their work at a
conference sponsored by the Los Alamos National Laboratory that
opened today in Santa Fe, N.M.
   They also turned down a meeting with the state panel that will
allocate a $5 million appropriation for fusion research at the
University of Utah.
   Pons and Fleischmann hope that two papers they are preparing for
submission to scientific journals will flesh out the sketchy data
they have provided so far, said James Brophy, the university's vice
president for research.
   ``They feel their time is more valuably spent in the lab getting
some of the details people have criticized them for not having,''
said Brophy, who planned to attend the sessions in Santa Fe.
   Pons and Fleischmann sent physicists around the world scurrying
to their laboratories when they announced in a March 23 news
conference they had sustained fusion in a bottle by running an
electrical current between platinum and palladium electrodes
immersed in ``heavy'' water containing deuterium, a variety of
hydrogen.
   But at subsequent scientific gatherings, Pons and Fleischmann
were accused of shoddy research and criticized for not publishing
enough information to enable others to duplicate their results.
   Scores of scientists have attempted to reproduce their
experiment, but few researchers have matched their results.
   The Workshop on Cold Fusion Phenomena, sponsored by Los Alamos
National Laboratory, could begin to clarify the many conflicting
claims and counterclaims still pouring out of university, national
and private laboratories.
   In abstracts of papers scheduled to be presented this week,
researchers largely dismissed the sensational claims of Pons and
Fleischmann, who works with Pons but is affiliated with the
University of Southampton, England.
   However, many of the presenters, from Los Alamos to New Jersey,
suggest enough low-level fusion is occurring to justify more
research into the territory.
   Today, Texas A&amp;M University physicists John Appleby and Kevin
Wolf offered qualified support for the chemists' claims at the
Santa Fe conference.
   Appleby said he found evidence of ``anomalous heat.'' Wolf said
separate tests turned up evidence that a small number of neutrons
and larger amounts of tritium had been released in experiments
similar to Pons and Fleischmann's.
   Wolf said the number of neutrons produced was up to seven times
the number expected in nature. ``Convincing?'' he asked
rhetorically. ``You be the judge.''
   About 500 physicists, chemists and other scientists from around
the world were expected at the conference.
   In Stockholm, Swedish physicists said today they produced a
burst of neutron radiation in an experiment similar to the those
conducted by the Utah chemists.
   ``The results indicate fusion reactions can occur at low
temperatures in the electrode material palladium. This gives
certain support to Fleischmann and Pons ideas,'' said scientists at
the Manne Siegbahn Institute for Physics.
   In an interview this week, Pons said his research was ``going
fantastic.'' Of the critics, he said, ``People are going to have to
eat a lot of crow, I'd say.''
   Originally, Pons and Fleischmann cited patent concerns for their
refusal to share specifics of their research. But six pending
patents now protect the basic experiment, and lack of time is the
only thing preventing the chemists from producing more detailed
accounts, Brophy said.
   Brophy said the new papers will include far more information
than the first Pons-Fleischmann article, published by the Journal
of Electroanalytical Chemistry, including details on heat
measurements.
   He said the pair now believe their experiment produces 100 times
more energy in the form of heat than it burns. Originally they
claimed a four-to-one ratio.
   The chemists contend that laboratories such as Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, Yale and others have failed to reproduce
their results because they have not set up the experiments properly.
   If that is true, they should provide more information, said
Steven Koonin, a California Institute of Technology physicist.
   ``I'm not a patent lawyer, but I don't see why they are holding
back. The fact that they are makes me very suspicious,'' said
Koonin. ``If they're worried about patenting and processes, I would
think that's all locked up. If there's something there, they'll get
the credit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
