<FIRST>r a AM-BearVisitor     05-23 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bear Visitor,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>200-Pound Bear Pays Quick Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTAGE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cozette Griffin and her husband had just
finished dinner when an unexpected visitor crashed through the
front door, tore though the house and left through a kitchen window.
   ``I heard ungodly crashes. The next thing I heard was my husband
say `Run,''' she said. ``I left for the nearest exit ... the
basement steps.
   ``About six feet ahead of me was undeniably a great big black
bear. It was so totally unreal.''
   Authorities estimated the bear weighed 200 to 275 pounds. Wild
bears are more common to the north than in the Portage area of
south-central Wisconsin.
   ``It will be indelibly etched in my memory,'' Mrs. Griffin said
Monday.
   Mrs. Griffin, 62, said she and her husband, LaVerne, 60, had
finished eating Sunday evening when they heard the noise at the
front door.
   She said she fled across the street to Divine Savior Hospital.
Her husband found refuge in the bathroom while the bear made its
visit that lasted only about 10 to 15 seconds.
   The bear apparently wasn't searching for food.
   ``Everything I left on the counter was there when it was all
over. Apparently a shrimp salad didn't tempt him in the least
bit,'' she said.
   Police Officer Tom Moore said the department had received a call
of a bear in the Griffins' neighborhood. He said he and a colleague
chased the bear from the Griffin home to the bottomland of the
nearby Wisconsin River, the last place he saw the animal.
</TEXT>
