<HEAD>School Board Rejects Dress Code For Graduation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOPKINTON, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rather than peek under graduation gowns
to enforce a dress code, the school board voted to let Chariho
Regional High School seniors wear what they want to commencement.
   The dress code, which would have required shirts with collars
and would have banned sneakers, blue jeans and shorts, was voted
down Monday night despite arguments that everyday clothing was not
appropriate for graduation.
   ``Are you going to look up everyone's cap and gown?'' committee
member Arthur Bernasconi asked. ``I'm not.''
   Betsy Conway said some students at last year's ceremony wore
T-shirts, jeans, tank tops or sandals, which she thought
inappropriate.
   ``Why should graduation be the same as a day on the beach
playing volleyball?'' Conway asked.
   Seniors who spoke at the meeting said their class had rejected
the dress code proposal by a 149-45 vote. They also said audience
members were more disruptive at last year's ceremonies than the
seniors.
