<FIRST>r i AM-China-TV     05-23 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-TV,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Allowing Networks Satellite Time</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and other foreign television networks
competed for satellite time Tuesday after Chinese authorities
lifted a martial law ban on transmitting.
   The major U.S. networks, Japanese TV stations and two Hong Kong
stations rushed to transmit their videotape after China Central
Television announced that satellite services had been resumed.
   ``It was a zoo. There was only one path out,'' said John
Sheahan, CBS bureau chief in Beijing.
   CCTV was ordered not to allow further television transmissions
and the military dismantled satellite earth stations after the
government declared martial law in Beijing on Saturday to put down
growing student-led unrest.
   After martial law was declared, Chinese authorities shut down
the satellite transmissions of CBS and Cable News Networks, which
had been broadcasting live from Beijing during the Sino-Soviet
summit but continued their reports after the high-level meeting was
over to show the student demonstrations. The Chinese authorities
said the networks had permission only to broadcast live while
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev was in China.
   Despite arguments from CBS and CNN, the government pulled the
plug on the networks. The satellite shutdown forced CBS, CNN and
the other U.S. networks to carry their videotape to other
countries, where it was transmitted back to the United States.
   On Tuesday, however, Sheahan said he was told that one earth
station was restored and CCTV received a call from military
authorities at 5 p.m. (4 a.m. EDT) informing the state-run station
that it could decide on its own whether to provide transmitting
facilities.
   Thirty minutes later, CBS was notified the satellite service was
restored.
   All videotape had to be transmitted by way of London, with the
various networks taking turns sending in five- and 10-minute blocks.
   ``It was like going through a subway turnstile,'' Sheahan said.
``There was an enormous amount of good will among competitors.''
   CCTV's decision to resume satellite transmissions came amid
martial law regulations that banned nearly all reporting activities
by foreign reporters in Beijing.
   Despite the ban, there has been little government interference
in foreign coverage of the demonstrations.
</TEXT>
