<DOCNO> AP890523-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1425EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DurableGoods     05-23 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Durable Goods,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surge Undercuts Recession Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods surged
2.9 percent in April, the biggest advance since December, the
government said Tuesday in a report that further eased fears of a
recession this year.
   The Commerce Department said orders for manufactured goods
expected to last three years or more rose to a seasonally adjusted
$129.1 billion last month after a 1 percent increase in March.
   Those gains followed declines in January and February that had
raised concerns economic growth might be in danger of slowing so
much that the country could topple into a recession brought on by a
credit squeeze engineered by the Federal Reserve Board.
   But analysts said the back-to-back gains of the last two months
were a good indication that demand in the manufacturing sector will
be enough to keep the economy expanding this year, although at a
slower pace than 1988.
   David Wyss, an analyst with Data Resources Inc., said that while
he still believed economic growth was slowing, the
bigger-than-expected increase in orders in April showed the economy
is ``not softening quite as fast as a lot of people thought.''
   Priscilla Trumble, an economist for the WEFA Group of Bala
Cynwyd, Pa., said she believed the central bank was successfully
engineering a ``soft landing,'' in which economic growth slows
enough to dampen inflation but not enough to cause a slump.
   The April durable goods report, she said, ``does, in fact, make
me feel a little more comfortable that ... the bottom is not going
to fall out this year.''
   The report, added Robert Dederick, chief economist at the
Northern Trust Co., in Chicago, says that ``the manufacturing
sector is in no way showing a systemic weakness.''
   The Commerce Department said the April increase, the largest
since a 7.4 percent rise in December, was spread across all major
industrial categories.
   Excluding the volatile defense category, the April advance was
an even stronger 4.7 percent. The hike in non-defense orders was
the first since a 6.2 increase last December.
   Defense orders, which had jumped 28.5 percent in March and 19.7
percent in February, declined 16.3 percent last month.
   Manufacturing sectors sharing the overall increase last month
were electrical machinery, led by communications equipment, up 9.4
percent to $20.0 billion; primary metals, such as steel, up 5.6
percent to $12.5 billion, and nonelectrical machinery, up 1.4
percent to $22.6 percent.
   Higher demand for cars and car parts boosted transportation
orders 0.6 percent to $37.3 billion in April. Demand for aircraft
and aircraft parts continued to remain high.
   Non-transportation orders rose 3.9 percent, the first increase
since a 2.2 percent hike last December and the broadest jump in
this area since a 4.8 percent leap in April 1987.
   Non-defense capital goods, watched as a sign of business
investment plans, also posted a 5.5 percent hike in April, up from
2.6 percent in March. It was the best showing since a 10.2 percent
increase in December.
   The Commerce Department said durable goods shipments last month
rose 2.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted $123.1 billion following
three monthly declines. Shipments had reached their high of $124.2
billion in December.
</TEXT>
