<FIRST>r w AM-SubmarineProblem     05-23 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Submarine Problem,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sub Cuts Short Its Mission After Mechanical Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear-powered attack submarine on a
routine patrol in the Pacific Ocean had to surface unexpectedly
last week and cut short its mission after experiencing a mechanical
problem with its propulsion system, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
   The USS Helena, a so-called Los Angeles-class attack submarine,
is now on the surface and heading back to its home port of Pearl
Harbor, Hawaii, using an auxiliary propulsion system, said Peter
Williams, the Pentagon's chief spokesman.
   No one aboard the vessel was injured and the sub's nuclear
reactor was not involved in any way, he added.
   The Helena surfaced on May 17 ``as a precaution'' when it was
about 500 nautical miles west of the island of Midway, and has been
moving slowly toward Pearl Harbor ever since with another Navy ship
serving as escort, Williams said.
   Initial reports indicate the sub experienced a problem with the
reduction gear in its main propulsion system. The spokesman
declined to estimate when the Helena would arrive in Hawaii.
