<FIRST>r w AM-Warnke-Arms     05-23 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warnke-Arms,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warnke Urges Administration to Take Advantage of Soviet Proposals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former arms control negotiator Paul Warnke
urged the Bush administration Tuesday to take advantage of Soviet
proposals and to ease pressure on NATO to agree to modernize
short-range nuclear weapons in West Germany.
   ``The best reaction we could have would be one of restraint,''
said Warnke, who was chief arms negotiator under President Carter.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has announced a cut of
500,000 in the Soviet armed forces, including withdrawal of 50,000
troops and 5,000 tanks from Central Europe, and has offered to
reduce the Warsaw Pact forces to levels below those of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   President Bush has been cool to Gorbachev's proposals, and has
asked NATO leaders to approve at a meeting next week a plan to
modernize the Lance missile system in Europe. The plan envisions a
tripling of the Lance range to more than 200 miles, and expanding
the number of launchers from 88 to 997.
   West Germany has been pushing for talks on reducing short-range
nuclear forces in Europe, but Bush has balked, citing Soviet
superiority.
   The Soviet Union has 1,400 short-range nuclear missiles in
Europe, and according to NATO figures, has 6,260 nuclear artillery
systems compared with 2,700 for the Atlantic Alliance.
   Warnke said Gorbachev's proposals opened the way toward ``a very
significant military stand-down in Europe.''
   ``It would be very difficult for us at this point to make a
matching response that involved very significant reductions in
American troops. The net result of that would be to paralyze
NATO,'' Warnke told a news conference.
   ``One sensible response would be to say in response to Mr.
Gorbachev, OK, if you are willing to eliminate the offensive
invasion threat, we do not have to decide to deploy new short-range
nuclear missiles, the sole function of which would be to respond to
that invasion.''
   Warnke also denied administration assertions that the Soviets
have modernized their short-range nuclear missile force, noting
that the newest such system, the SS-23, was required to be
destroyed under the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces Treaty signed
in 1987. Most Soviet short-range missiles are SCUDs, which were
deployed 25 years ago, he said.
   Warnke, at his news conference, presented a report by the
British American Security Information Council, which largely
reflected his views on disarmament.
</TEXT>
