<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1459EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HealthInsurance     05-23 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Health Insurance,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Employers Will Require Workers to Pay Some of Costs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A growing number of companies intend to
require their employees to pay a greater share of their health care
costs in response to soaring medical expenses, the chairman of the
National Association of Manufacturers said Tuesday.
   Richard E. Heckert, in releasing a survey of the association's
members on health insurance issues, said increased cost-sharing is
``a positive development'' because it encourages workers to become
more educated health-care consumers.
   The survey of 2,029 manufacturers earlier this year found that
the cost of providing health insurance represented an average 37
percent of the companies' net profits.
   ``They're looking for some way to cut their expenses,'' Heckert
said.
   The cost of health care for U.S. businesses has tripled over the
last eight years and rose an average 30 percent last year for the
companies surveyed, he said.
   The survey found 84 percent of the manufacturers surveyed
opposed any attempt to require companies to provide benefits to
workers, as a bill introduced in the Senate by Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., would do.
   Requiring coverage by employers would further escalate medical
costs and ``it doesn't make sense to raise costs further in a
system that needs major repair,'' Heckert said.
   Among the manufacturers surveyed, 99.3 percent offer group
health care benefits to employees and nearly all of them extend
coverage to the families of their workers.
   Nearly 56 percent of those surveyed pay the entire cost of
premiums for coverage and most of the rest share the cost with
employees. For dependent coverage, nearly 32 percent pay the entire
cost of coverage premiums, while about 54 percent share the cost
with the worker and nearly 15 percent require the worker to pay all
of the cost of such coverage.
   The manufacturers did not propose radical changes in the current
health-care system, but suggested ways to reduce costs, including
reform of the medical liability system to limit damage awards and
elimination of costly administrative burdens on employers offering
health insurance to workers.
</TEXT>
