<FIRST>r a AM-GraduationPrayer     05-23 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Graduation Prayer,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Principal Knew Of Graduation Prayer Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Niichel is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ONAWA, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school principal encouraged a student
to recite the Lord's Prayer as part of his commencement speech
after a federal judge rejected a minister's request to lead the
prayer, the student says.
   Iowa Civil Liberties Union officials criticized West Monona High
School Principal Gary Niichel for his action.
   ``It shows a complete lack of respect for our court system,''
said Mark Lambert, a legislative lobbyist for the ICLU.
   Senior class President Alan Langenfeld recited the prayer Sunday
to about 1,000 people. Langenfeld said he first consulted with his
father and Niichel.
   ``I had a little prompting from my father and Mr. Niichel,'' he
said.
   ``I need to make a distinction here,'' Langenfeld added. ``Mr.
Niichel has a son in our graduating class and any advice he gave he
gave as the father of a graduating senior, not as a principal.''
   Niichel acknowledged Monday that he knew of Langenfeld's plans
minutes before the commencement. He declined to comment further
``because of my position as an administrator.''
   U.S. District Judge Donald E. O'Brien last week rejected a
request by the Rev. Duane Lundberg to lead a prayer at the
graduation, citing constitutional restrictions on religious
practices at public facilities.
   Lambert said the ICLU had not decided whether to pursue legal
action in the case. A secretary in O'Brien's office said the judge
was out of town and unavailable for comment Tuesday.
   School Superintendent Donald Southwick said no action will be
taken against Langenfeld and said he was unsure whether the
district will take steps to prevent similar incidents.
   Langenfeld said he polled classmates before the ceremony, and no
one objected to the prayer.
   ``The whole class was kind of jittery,'' he said. ``They were
joking around that the feds were going to come get us and we'd have
our diplomas to read while we were sitting in jail.''
</TEXT>
