<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1517EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-JailersSue     05-23 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jailers Sue,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prison Guards' Lawsuit Charges Overcrowding Is Hazardous</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten prison guards have filed a class-action
lawsuit against the state, charging prison overcrowding is so
severe that guards are in danger.
   ``Inmates are not the only people affected by conditions that
judges sometimes call cruel and inhuman punishment,'' said Thomas
J. Brophy, a spokesman for American Federation of State County and
Municipal Employees Council 93, the union representing 3,000 state
prison guards.
   Numerous lawsuits have been filed by inmates seeking to reduce
prison overcrowding, but Brophy and others said Tuesday they
believe this is the first legal action by guards.
   As of May 17, there were 7,145 inmates jammed into state prisons
designed to hold 3,824, Department of Correction spokesman Deodato
Arruda said.
   The lawsuit, filed May 12 in Suffolk Superior Court, charges
that inmates in the Concord prison are shoehorned into the paint
shop, day rooms, telephone rooms, hospital ward and hallways.
   The crowding has made some areas impossible to secure and led to
an increase in inmate violence and attacks against guards, the
lawsuit alleges.
   The 10 correctional officers, all of whom are union officials,
charge the conditions violate their contract as well as state laws
mandating a safe workplace. They want the court to bar the state
from locking up more prisoners than the jails were built to hold.
   ``Most often, officers' injuries are suffered when they are
breaking up inmate-on-inmate violence,'' Brophy said. Neither
Brophy nor Arruda could provide statistics on assaults against
guards, but Brophy said they had increased.
   State attorneys met Tuesday to decide how to respond to the
lawsuit, Arruda said.
   Massschusetts has embarked on a jail-building program, with 225
new prison beds to be completed at Concord by October and 1,185
statewide by 1990, he said.
   Although several inmate lawsuits are pending on the crowding
issue, the state is not under court order to reduce prison
overcrowding. Two county jails are under such orders, and a
court-appointed master has been granting early releases to convicts
at the Dedham jail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
