<FIRST>u i AM-Cannes     05-23 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cannes,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>New American Director Takes Top Award at Cannes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lower case ``sex, lies and videotape'' is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANNES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Steven Soderbergh's first feature
film, ``sex, lies and videotape,'' won the Golden Palm award
Tuesday night at the 42nd Cannes film festival.
   One of the movie's four stars, James Spader, took the best actor
award, while Meryl Streep was selected best actress for her
performance in ``A Cry in the Dark,'' directed by Fred Schepisi.
   ``Well, I guess it's all downhill from here,'' said Soderbergh,
26, as he accepted the festival's top prize. ``I don't know what to
say. I was in great company here.''
   The Jury's Special Prize went to two films: French director
Bertrand Blier's ``Trop Belle Pour Toi'' (``Too Beautiful for
You'') and Italian director Giuseppe Tornatore's ``Nuovo Cinema
Paradiso'' (``Paradise Cinema'').
   West German director Wim Wenders, president of the jury,
presented the award to Soderbergh, of Baton Rouge, La. Wenders said
the film brought the jury both joy and ``confidence in the future
of the cinema.''
   Emir Kusturica of Yugoslavia received the best director award
for his movie ``Dom Za Vesanje'' (``Time of the Gypsies'').
   American Jim Jarmusch's ``Mystery Train,'' three sketches
unified by a train, took the prize for best artistic contribution.
   The Jury Prize went to ``Jesus de Montreal'' (``Jesus of
Montreal'') by Canadian director Denys Arcand. The film had been
among those rumored for the Golden Palm.
   Shot on a $1.2 million budget, ``sex, lies and videotape'' tells
the story of a seemingly happily married, prosperous couple whose
lives are disrupted when a troubled friend returns to town,
triggering revelations of sexual and personal betrayal.
   Spader, named best actor, portrays the returning friend who
precipitates the disaster, which ultimately leads to
self-knowledge. Impotent, he videotapes interviews with women about
their sex lies as a substitute for real intimacy.
   Blier's ``Trop Belle Pour Toi,'' starring Gerard Depardieu,
tells the story of a garage owner who betrays his beautiful wife
following a sudden, unexplained attraction to his less attractive
temporary secretary. ``Nuovo Cinema Paradiso'' was one of two
Italian entries focusing on the cinema and its demise. Ettore
Scola's ``Splendor'' was not honored with a prize.
   The 13-day festival also made a special bow to Gregory Peck,
whose film ``Old Gringo,'' also starring Jane Fonda, officially
closed the festival.
   Both he and Ms. Fonda received standing ovations from the black
tie crowd at the Palais des Festivals.
</TEXT>
