<SECOND>AM-Vet Slaying,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran Arrested At Mental Hospital In New Hampshire Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTHAMPTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who told police and two
newspapers that he killed a man who tried to prevent him from
committing suicide was ordered jailed Tuesday pending his return to
New Hampshire to face murder charges.
   ``I wish it had been me instead of him,'' said Richard Papineau,
who has been in and out of mental hospitals since torching a
Buddhist shrine in the Berkshire Hills six years ago while on a
weekend pass from a Veterans Administration hospital.
   He and two other men said they set the fire to draw attention to
a lack of treatment programs for Vietnam veterans.
   Papineau was arrested late Monday at Northampton State Hospital,
a psychiatric facility where he had been held for observation to
determine if he could stand trial on charges of assaulting his wife
and girlfriend.
   Papineau pleaded innocent Tuesday in Northampton District Court
to a warrant charging him with being a fugitive from justice in New
Hampshire.
   Cynthia White, an assistant New Hampshire attorney general, said
Tuesday that authorities have obtained a warrant charging him with
the murder of a man whose body was found Monday in woods off a
highway in Winchester, N.H.
   Papineau, 40, reportedly told the Union-News in Springfield and
The Recorder in Greenfield during interviews at the hospital that
he shot and killed the man. He identified the victim as a patient
at the VA Hospital in Northampton and alleged the killing occurred
after the two men drove to New Hampshire on April 24, the papers
said.
   ``When I went out there, I was going to take myself out,'' he
said. ``I still wish it had been me instead of him, just like I
wish it had been me instead of the guys in Vietnam. I've been
living with them for 22 years. Now there is one more name on that
list and I will live with them until I check out.''
   In Vietnam, Papineau received the Bronze Star for carrying a
wounded fellow Marine to safety, despite being wounded in the face
and head when his unit was trapped on a hill in the Ah Shau Valley
on June 4, 1967. Within 12 hours, 85 percent of his company was
killed or wounded and Papineau was found 18 days after the battle
wandering aimlessly through the countryside, his lawyer said in a
1984 court session.
   Papineau, who said he also told his story to police here, said
he had been distraught over a restraining order that kept him away
from the Greenfield apartment shared by his girlfriend and his
former wife.
   He said he stopped his car, walked into the woods and pointed a
.38-caliber revolver at his own head.
   ``I had the barrel in my face. I was sitting on a rock,''
Papineau said. His alleged victim, he said, ``came up behind me and
said, `I'm not going to let you do this,' and grabbed me. I kind of
freaked. The gun went off and he went down.''
   ``The next thing I knew, the gun was empty and I was just
standing there,'' Papineau said.
   He described the victim, whom he said he had known a few days,
as ``just like me, a loner.''
   His troubles here began New Year's Eve 1983 when Papineau said
that he and two other VA Hospital patients torched the small
Buddhist temple in Hawley. Veterans from across the country later
helped the small Tibetan congregation rebuild the temple.
   All three men were placed on probation and ordered to continue
treatment, but Papineau entered and left hospitals in several New
England states until a judge threatened to jail him. King said he
had recently returned to western Massachusetts, said Michael King,
director of the Veterans Outreach Center in Greenfield.
</TEXT>
