<HEAD>West Must Stop Bid to Reduce Navies in Arms Talks: Jane's Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release 4 p.m. EDT _ Time Set By Source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West must head off any attempt by the Soviets
to reduce naval forces during superpower arms talks, the editor of
``Jane's Fighting Ships'' said Tuesday.
   Capt. Richard Sharpe wrote in the introduction to the respected
military guide that the West's whole defensive strategy rests on
its naval strength.
   Sharpe also said that as the risk of superpower confrontation
recedes, regional instabilitse, threatening the
economic interests of industrialized nations and breeding
ies could increainternational terrorism.
   He said the health of the U.S. Navy in the next few years
depends on its ability to attract and keep qualified recruits.
   He also said India's goal of becoming a dominant regional
maritime power ``is beginning to cause concern around the whole
oceanic rim.''
   Sharpe said there is ``no doubt'' a key Soviet objective is to
reduce Western naval strength. Because of its traditional
reluctance to throw anything away, the Soviet navy has thousands of
tons of ancient ships and submarines that it could unilaterally
scrap with little impact on overall effectiveness, he said.
   ``It is devoutly to be hoped that the West will not once again
be wrong-footed in the propaganda battle and that listment rates running
at the lowest level in five years.
   Much of the problem, he said, is because of the disparity
between military and civilian pay rates.
   Sharpe said most regional naval growth in the last year has been
in the Indian Ocean and in the China Seas, which has 12 of the
world's 15 maritime disputes.
   Indian naval strength has continued to grow, and Sharpe said
there is little doubt that India intends to be the dominant
regional maritime force from the Suez to Malacca.
   ``However benign the stated intentions ... with its gigantic and
growing population, its close ties to the Soviet Union, its nuclear
research activity, its building up of bases ... and its attention
to build new strike attack aircraft carriers and modern submarines,
India is beginning to appear to nations on the oceanic rim as a
potentially belligerent state.''
