<FIRST>r a AM-GunImports     05-23 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gun Imports,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Hears Challenge to Assault Weapon Import Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Tuesday urged a federal appeals
court to uphold the Bush administration's ban on imported assault
rifles in a case that could affect 640,000 of the weapons in the
first quarter of this year alone.
   ``We do not want the American public to suffer the
consequences,'' said Mark Stern of the Justice Department's civil
division. ``It's for their safety.''
   But a lawyer for an Alabama gun shop owner argued that the
government had already issued permits and should release 1,250
semiautomatic rifles that were impounded at the Birmingham, Ala.,
airport by the U.S. Customs Service.
   The three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
based in Atlanta, sat in Miami for an expedited hearing on whether
to release the rifles to Don Wood, owner of Gun South Inc. in
Trussville, Ala. The judges took the case under advisement after
the one-hour session.
   On April 26, U.S. District Judge William Acker Jr. had ruled
that Wood was entitled to delivery of Steyr AUG-SA Austrian-made
rifles, which sell for $900 to $1,000 each.
   But the government appealed the decision, and Stern argued
Monday that the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms needs more
time to re-examine the permits it gave Gun South and other arms
importers.
   The court's decision could affect the fate of about 640,000
similar weapons already held up this year by the presidential ban
instituted after a man with an assault rifle killed five children
at a school in Stockton, Calif.
   Wood's attorney, James C. Barton, dismissed the confiscation of
his client's rifles as hysteria against a weapon already approved
by ATF as a sports rifle.
   Stern ``has used the term `assault weapon' 95 times in the face
of testimony of his own experts,'' Barton said. ``This is a libel
on my client's product, and we now have Congress using the same
term in the Assault Weapon Control Act of 1989.''
   Barton said the confiscation threatened his client's livelihood
and Gun South's 700 employees. The company has a total of 4,700
imported semiautomatic rifles on order.
</TEXT>
