<FIRST>r w AM-EmploymentStudy     05-23 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Employment Study,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Study Says Adjustment of Employment Test Scores Needed for Minorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scores of minorities on a test used to
screen job applicants must be adjusted to assure that blacks and
Hispanics are given equal consideration with whites, experts on a
National Research Council committee said Tuesday.
   Adjustments that boost the scores of minorities on the General
Aptitude Test Battery, a widely used employment screening exam, are
necessary to make sure that blacks and Hispanics are not
``disproportionately excluded'' from job referrals, a council
committee said.
   ``With no score adjustments, very low fractions of
minority-group members will be referred for employment,'' it said.
This could result in what the committee called ``a severe adverse
impact on the employment opportunities of those demographic
groups.''
   The study was conducted by the council at the request of the
Department of Labor. One element of the study was to analyze a plan
to use the General Aptitude Test Battery to screen applicants for
all of the 12,000 job categories in the U.S. economy.
   The test, now used to screen job applicants for several hundred
thousand jobs annually, was first developed in the 1940s by the
U.S. Employment Service, a division of the Department of Labor. In
recent times, the USES has encouraged state employment offices to
use the test to select applicants who are referred to employers to
fill job vacancies.
   As part of the test program, the NRC committee said the Labor
Department adopted a system to adjust upward the scores of minority
applicants. This policy has been challenged by the Department of
Justice. Labor officials asked the council to examine the policy
from a technical perspective.
   The committee concluded that score adjustments are necessary to
assure equal job opportunities for minorities.
   ``In the absence of score adjustments, minority applicants who
could preform successfully on the job will be screened out of the
referral group in greater proportions than are equivalent
majority-group applicants,'' the study said.
   The committee said the GATB examinations were only of ``modest''
use in predicting how well a specific applicant would perform a
specific job. The study also called ``unfounded'' a Labor
Department claim that universally applying the GATB would save
employers $80 billion annually through an increase in job
productivity.
   GATB examinations have at least two flaws, the council committee
said. The study said that there are limited forms of the test,
which means that advance copies could become available to
applicants, thus giving them an unfair advantage.
   The second flaw is what the committee called ``speededness.''
The study said that a test that must be completed within a short
period of time can give distorted scores if applicants are coached
to randomly select answers in the final minute of the allowed time.
   GATB examinations test verbal, numerical, perceptual and
psychomotor skills, but the committee said that no test is
available to give a precise prediction of how well a person will
perform on a job.
   The National Research Council is the principal operating agency
of the National Academy of Sciences, a private organization
chartered by Congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
