<FIRST>r i AM-Germany     05-23 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German President Re-Elected to Second Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Richard von Weizsaecker,
West Germany's eloquent and respected elder statesman, was
re-elected to a second, five-year term Tuesday.
   A special assembly of legislators and appointed electors that
convenes once every five years re-elected the 69-year-old Christian
Democrat with 881 votes of the 1,022 cast, or 86.2 percent.
Weizsaecker was unopposed.
   During his first term, Weizsaecker transformed the largely
ceremonial office into an influential post.
   Weizsaecker won praise for his effort to bring fellow Germans to
terms with the Holocaust in a 1985 address marking the 40th
anniversary of the German capitulation in World War II.
   But Weizsaecker also called for a fair assessment of the
accomplishments of a nation built on the ruins of Nazi Germany.
   The president planned another major address Wednesday to mark
the 40th anniversary of West Germany's statehood.
   ``These are serious responsibilities and I wish for us the
strength to bear them successfully,'' Weizsaecker said in an
acceptance speech.
   Parliament President Rita Suessmuth opened the convention in
Bonn's sprawling Beethoven Hall with words of praise for
Weizsaecker, the sixth man to serve as West German president since
the nation was founded on May 24, 1949.
   Each of the five political parties represented in the federal
parliament may nominate a candidate for the presidency. But for the
first time in the nation's history, the vote was uncontested,
reflecting the respect Weizsaecker has won across the political
spectrum.
   Weizsaecker drew the endorsement of all but the left-leaning
Greens Party, which nonetheless decided not to run their own
candidate.
   In a recent nationwide poll, Weizsaecker drew an approval rating
of more than 85 percent and the Institute for Opinion Research
determined that he is the public figure most often chosen as an
appropriate example for young West Germans.
</TEXT>
