<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-23 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orange County collected 4,000 ideas for
improving traffic and now plans to bury the top 100.
   The winning entries _ ranging from hydrofoil commutes and
freeway shoulder map racks to collision avoidance radar _ will be
buried in a time capsule as part of the county's centennial
celebration.
   The top 100 ideas were unveiled during a county Transportation
Commission meeting Monday.
   Included among the suggestions were these winners:
   High-speed cameras to record license plates of motorists who run
red lights, double-deck freeways, hydrofoil commuting along the
Pacific, smaller cars and a monorail system along freeway medians.
   The winning suggestions were bound in a slick, 16-page booklet
and will be buried in the centennial time capsule.
   Ideas aren't cheap. It cost the commission $41,000 to advertise,
buy postage, print brochures and hire consultants to sift through
the ideas.
   Next year, the panel plans to spend $50,000 for a consultant to
try and work some of the ideas into reality.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PASS CHRISTIAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fuzzy, 75-gram baby screech owl
has received the appropriate moniker of ``High Tide'' after heavy
rains flooded him from his nest in the hollow of a tall water oak
tree.
   High Tide, believed to be less than a dozen days old, was found
Saturday on the grounds of a Christmas Tree Farm in a communitie in his
arms said
Tuesday he would do it again to end his family's anguish.
   ``Absolutely, there's no doubt in my mind,'' Rudy Linares, 23,
of suburban Cicero, Ill., said on the CBS-TV This Morning program.
``Today, tomorrow, I'd do the same thing again.
   ``I didn't want him there to begin with,'' he said of his
15-month-old son, Samuel, who died April 26. ``There was no other
alternative. I couldn't see my family be torn apart any more.''
   A grand jury refused to indict Linares after he disconnected
Samuel's respirator and held a gun to keep away employees of
Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical Center in Chicago.
   The Cook County state's attorney's office charged Linares with
murder, but opted against pursuing the charge following the grand
jury's action. The county's medical examiner ruled the death an
accident.
   Samuel was in a coma for nine months after choking on a balloon.
   Last week, Linares pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor weapons
charge and was released on condition that he receive a
psychological evaluation and get counseling if recommended by
authorities.
   During the nine months Samuel was in a coma, it became
increasingly difficult to visit him, Linares said in Tuesday's
interview.
   ``Tubes out of his nose, his mouth, tubes out of his throat; it
was just getting harder and harder to see him that way,'' Linares
said. He said it was ``just tearing apart the whole family.''
   His wife, Tamara, who also appeared on the television program,
which originated in New York, said the family's mail since the
incident has all been supportive, and included prayers.
</TEXT>
