<FIRST>r p AM-NYCMayor     05-23 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYC Mayor,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Goldin Says He Wants to Change `Calcutta on the Hudson' _ As Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York has begun to look like ``Calcutta on
the Hudson,'' the city's chief financial officer for the last 16
years said Tuesday in formally launching his campaign for mayor.
   Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin said he has the experience to
``make New York livable again.''
   He said he would develop programs to combat housing shortages,
drugs and high school dropout rates; establish a Department for
Children; rebuild bridges and streets; and ``take the handcuffs off
the cops.''
   Goldin, 53, will run in the Democratic primary against incumbent
Edward I. Koch, who is in his 12th year as mayor, Manhattan Borough
President David Dinkins, and former Charter Review Commission
Chairman Richard Ravitch. Among the Republicans, former U.S.
Attorney Rudolph Giuliani faces cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder.
   Goldin said he would devote more funds to rehabilitate vacant
apartment buildings the city has seized for back taxes so that more
of the homeless could be put into permanent housing.
   ``This is a sensible program for a city that's beginning to look
like Calcutta on the Hudson,'' he said.
