<FIRST>r w AM-Weather-Crops     05-23 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weather-Crops,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Improves Plains' Soil Moisture, Slows Field Work in Corn Belt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain has improved soil moisture conditions in
the central and southern Great Plains and has slowed field work in
the eastern Corn Belt and the Delta region, a government report
said Tuesday.
   Despite the rainfall in parts of the plains, the outlook for
winter wheat in much of the region continues to be poor. Harvest is
under way in several states, including Texas and Oklahoma.
   Nationally, corn planting was 84 percent complete by the end of
the May 15-21 survey week, lagging the normal pace by only two
percentage points, said the Joint Agricultural Weather Facility.
However, in the wetter areas of the eastern Corn Belt, planting of
the new crop lagged far behind.
   ``Planting was complete in Texas and nearly complete in Georgia,
Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Missouri and Nebraska,'' the report said.
   But in Ohio, where 85 percent of the corn acreage is usually
planted by now, only 24 percent was seeded, the report said. In
Pennsylvania, 19 percent of the corn was planted by May 21,
compared with 62 percent usually.
   The facility, which is operated by the Agriculture and Commerce
departments, said the 1989 soybean crop was about 39 percent
planted, only two percentage points behind the normal pace.
However, plantings lagged sharply in some areas, including Ohio,
where only 6 percent of the estimated soybean acreage had been
planted, compared with a normal 56 percent.
   Cotton plantings, at 60 percent, were reported nine points
behind the usual rate for this time of the season. Although
planting was complete in California, it lagged in the Delta and
Southeast.
   A related report by the USDA's 1989 drought task force headed by
Undersecretary Richard Crowder said that ``timely rains in the Corn
Belt are promoting rapid germination and establishment of this
year's crop.''
   But the report added that the impact of recent rain in winter
wheat areas will depend, in part, on weather conditions in the
coming days.
   ``If another (weather) front brings more rain as predicted,
moderate improvement in crop conditions could occur,'' the task
force said.
   The National Weather Service calls for ``moderate to heavy rain
in the Great Plains and Corn Belt in the next 5 to 10 days,'' it
added. ``The outlook through mid-June still calls for cool, wet
weather in the South and East, and warm, dry weather from the
eastern Dakotas into the central Corn Belt.''
   A new 30- and 90-day weather outlook is scheduled to be issued
by the Weather Service next week.
</TEXT>
