<FIRST>r a AM-LadleDeaths     05-23 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ladle Deaths,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Father who Killed Two Sons Sentenced to Life Without Parole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSKEGON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of killing his two sons
in a 1,300-degree foundry ladle was sentenced Tuesday to two life
sentences without chance of parole.
   Bartley James Dobben, 28, was given the mandatory sentence by
Muskegon County Circuit Judge James Graves Jr. a week after a jury
found him guilty but mentally ill on two counts of first-degree
murder.
   Dobben admitted killing 15-month-old Peter David and 2-year-old
Bartley Joel on Thanksgiving Day 1987 in a furnace at the
Cannon-Muskegon Corp. foundry where he worked. His attorneys
contended Dobben was insane at the time.
   Dobben, diagnosed as a paranoid schizophrenic two years before
the slayings, is guaranteed treatment for his mental illness while
incarcerated.
   Dobben was to be taken Wednesday from the Muskegon County Jail
to the State Prison of Southern Michigan at Jackson, where he will
be psychologically evaluated for a decision on where to imprison
him, authorities said.
   Dobben's defense attorneys have said they will appeal the
verdict.
