<FIRST>r w AM-DroughtAssistance     05-23 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought Assistance,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Agrees to `Fast Track' For Drought Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the House Agriculture Committee
agreed Tuesday to push through a broad package of federal
assistance this week for farmers suffering crop losses from
continuing drought.
   The full committee, under an agreement worked out by Democrats
and Republicans, will act on the legislation Thursday. The
drought-relief package will be brought before the House at an
undetermined date after lawmakers return from a Memorial Day recess.
   ``I think the chances that a bill will be passed and signed into
law by the president ... have dramatically improved,'' Rep. Pat
Roberts, R-Kan., said after the meeting of committee leaders,
including the panel chairman, Rep. Kika de la Garza, D-Texas.
   The assistance package will mirror relief programs enacted by
Congress last year to aid producers in the Midwest and northern
Great Plains.
   In general, federal payments would be made to farmers who suffer
losses of more than 35 percent of their crops.
   The relief would be available for all crops _ not just specific
hard-hit ones like wheat _ because of damage from drought, freezing
temperatures, hail and excessive moisture, said Scott Swenson, a
spokesman for Rep. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., chairman of the
Agriculture subcomittee on wheat, soybeans and feed grains.
   Lawmakers are considering another drought package this year
because the Agriculture Department has said the 1989 winter wheat
crop doesn't qualify for any of the $3.9 billion in assistance
approved in 1988.
   Last week, a bipartisan group of senators introduced
drought-relief legislation that would extend last year's assistance
programs to the winter wheat crop.
   Roberts said that House committee leaders decided to go with a
``generic bill'' as a way of broadening support as well as ensuring
that adequate aid is available to spring-planted crops if the
drought worsens or spreads to other regions.
   Last year's dry weather has persisted in some areas, with winter
wheat states like Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas particularly hard hit.
   The Agriculture Department estimated this month that
drought-related damage will cut this year's expected crop of winter
wheat to 1.43 billion bushels, the lowest since 1978.
</TEXT>
