<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-BlackCaucus 1stLd-Writethru a0661 05-23 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Black Caucus, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0661,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Meets With Congressional Black Caucus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with comments by Conyers, Rangel, edits throughout to
tighten, including trimming two grafs at end</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black members of Congress who met with
President Bush on Tuesday said he has agreed to consult them on
contentious issues and they also said they hope to participate in
shaping administration policy.
   While they disagreed with Bush's views on various domestic and
foreign policy issues, they said they are withholding judgment on
his administration until he more fully develops his policies.
   ``We saw this as an important beginning,'' said Rep. Ron
Dellums, D-Calif., after the White House meeting of the
Congressional Black Caucus with Bush and Secretary of State James
A. Baker III.
   But some members expressed serious doubts about Bush's
commitment to many issues they raised during their hour-long
meeting.
   ``We're dealing with a thousand lights without any batteries,''
said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., in reference to Bush's often
stated urging for all sectors of society to help make life better
since the government can't afford to do it all.
   Rangel, chairman of the House select committeee on narcotics,
said he has refrained from early criticism of Bush.
   ``I've been very restrained because anything is better than the
last eight years'' under President Reagan, he said. ``But how long
can you wait?'' Rangel said Bush lacks a specific strategy for
helping poor persons fight crime and drug abuse, but that he ``was
willing to work with us to develop one.''
   ``I don't think there was any question about the president's
sincerity. But where does all this go?'' he asked.
   During the meeting, Bush brought up budgetary constraints in
talking about domestic issues, the participants said.
   Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., said Bush has proposed a ``do nothing''
budget. ``Right now they haven't put forth an agenda,'' he said.
But he added that he is willing to give Bush more time.
   Participants said that in regard to crime, Bush appeared open to
expanding his policy from a heavy focus on law enforcement and
punishment to include other factors such as education, housing and
health care.
   But on South Africa, the caucus members said he held out no hope
he would come around to their view that more sanctions are needed
to pressure the white minority government to negotiate with
representatives of the black majority.
   Dellums said Bush agreed to meet with the group again and to
have Cabinet members meet with them to discuss other issues.
   By contrast, during the Reagan administration, Black Caucus
members went to the White House at the beginning of 1981 and were
never invited back, Dellums said.
   Despite the differences, some caucus members shied away from
criticism of Bush.
   ``We recognize the president is evolving his policies,'' said
Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas.
   ``We want to be significant players in that policy,'' Dellums
said.
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., said that while ``it's totally
unclear where we're going,'' at least the administration is willing
to set up a mechanism to hear ideas from legislators who disagree
with the Republican administration.
   Caucus members think Bush is not looking at what they say are
the root causes of drug abuse and crime _ unemployment, poverty,
lack of housing, and poor education.
   ``We were concerned about his priorities there,'' Leland said.
   Dellums said Bush indicated ``he was prepared to expand his
analysis to include an appreciation for the fact that there are
other systemic problems that have to be dealt with and that the
issue of drugs is not going to be eradicated simply by law
enforcement.''
   But Conyers called Bush's anti-crime plan ``strictly draconian
and supply-side oriented.''
</TEXT>
