<FIRST>r i AM-ToxicGas     05-23 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toxic Gas,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Doctors Say Toxic Gas Killed People in Soviet Georgia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French humanitarian organization said Tuesday its
doctors concluded through investigations in the Soviet republic of
Georgia that toxic gases killed some demonstrators who died in a
clash there with police last month.
   Medecins sans Frontiers (Doctors without Borders) said in a
statement that Chloropicrine was identified as one of the gases
responsible on the basis of autopsy results in 16 cases.
   The statement said the four-member French team worked with
American colleagues from the group Physicians for Human Rights,
with Georgian doctors and with representatives from the Georgian
Health Ministry. It said the team would address further questions
upon returning to Paris on Wednesday.
   The organization's Dr. Marc Gastellu Etchegorry said
Chloropicrine had been approved in the Soviet Union for use as a
tear gas until 1981, when it was reclassified as a ``suffocant'' or
asphyxiating gas for combat use.
   Nineteen people died in clashes between police and Georgian
nationalists on April 9 in Tbilisi, the republic's capital. Police
shot and killed a 20th person later as a curfew violator.
   The foreign medical investigators were invited by the Georgian
government and by Andrei Sakharov, prominent Soviet dissident,
human rights campaigner, nuclear physicist and Nobel Peace laureate.
   The doctors examined and questioned about 100 hospitalized
patients.
   They said hundreds of people were admitted to hospitals
beginning on April 17, more than a week after the clash, believing
they suffered secondary effects from the toxic gases.
   The statement said the doctors concluded these people were
suffering from a panic syndrome caused by psychological trauma, and
not from chemical effects from gases.
   The French doctors' group says it understands Chloropicrine is
made in the United States as well as the Soviet Union. The doctors
assume, but do not know for a fact, that the gas is part of
military stockpile rather than used as tear gas in riot control.
   The army general in command of Soviet forces in Georgia, Gen.
Igor Rodionov, denied on April 30 that his troops used toxic gas
but said Interior Ministry units had tear gas. He did not say that
they used it.
</TEXT>
