<SECOND>AM-Mutilation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0722,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>System, Family Stymied by Inability to Keep Violent Criminal Locked
Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 12-13, `Shriner's criminal ...,' with 2 grafs to
ADD definition of ``defective delinquent,'' CORRECT Shriner was not sent
to reform school; picks up 14th graf, `In 1976 ...; INSERTS 1 graf after
19th graf, `The sentences ...,' to ADD background on Shriner; picks up
20th graf, `Shriner had ...' Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man with a long history of assaults on
children has been charged with raping and sexually mutilating a
7-year-old boy, a tragedy officials and relatives say they were
stymied from preventing.
   ``He's my brother and I love him, but God, he's driven the whole
family nuts for 20 years,'' John Shriner said after older brother
Earl Kenneth Shriner's arraignment Monday.
   Police said an assailant lured the boy into the woods and
repeatedly and violently raped him, choked him, stabbed him in the
back and cut off his penis.
   Shriner, 39, pleaded innocent in Pierce County Superior Court to
attempted murder, rape and assault in the attack on the boy, who
was found Saturday wandering in shock in a South Tacoma woods,
naked, bloody, and with a noose wrapped around his neck. He was in
satisfactory condition at a hospital Tuesday.
   Bail for Shriner was set at $1 million pending a trial July 17.
   About 50 people crowded into the courtroom and about a dozen
placard-waving demonstrators protested outside the County-City
Building against the crime. The boy's doctor, Dr. John Coombs,
called it ``the most outrageous thing I've ever seen.''
   State Sen. Phil Talmadge of Seattle, ranking Democrat on the
Senate Law and Justice Committee, said he will write the state
Department of Corrections and Department of Social and Health
Services asking why Shriner was free.
   ``I want to see their explanation,'' Talmadge said Tuesday.
``This guy by all accounts had no business being out on the
street.''
   Spokesmen for Corrections and for the state's Indeterminate
Sentence Review Board said they kept Shriner locked up as long as
they could.
   ``I totally understand the frustration,'' said Dennis Marsh, the
board's executive secretary. ``I guess from our perspective, the
parole board's perspective, there was nothing we could do.
   ``I guess the next guestion is, who needs to do what and when?''
   Shriner's criminal history dates to 1965, when he was declared a
``defective delinquent'' after choking a 7-year-old girl. The
now-outdated term was used to designate delinquents considered to
have mental or emotional reasons for committing violent acts.
   In 1966, he was sent to a school for people with developmental
disabilities after he led authorities to the body of Lorretta Marie
Sturtz, a 15-year-old classmate at a school for the mentally
retarded. She had been strangled and left tied to a tree.
Considered too dangerous by school officials, Shriner was committed
to Western State Hospital from 1968 to 1973.
   In 1976, he was acquitted in two separate assault cases, but
pleaded guilty in May 1977 to assaulting two 16-year-old female
hitchhikers. The judge ordered him committed to the sexual
psychopath program at Eastern State Hospital, but officials there
refused to accept him. He spent his entire 10-year sentence at the
Shelton Correctional Center.
   In the final months of his prison term, Shriner was found with
lists of things he would need to maim or kill youngsters, said
Kathryn S. Bail, Indeterminate Sentence Review Board chairwoman.
   ``We did everything legally possible to keep him in custody,''
Ms. Bail said.
   At a hearing to commit Shriner to a state hospital, he was freed
by a judge, said Frank Mendizabal, Department of Social and Health
Services spokesman.
   In November 1987, Shriner pleaded guilty to assault in the
stabbing of a 16-year-old boy. He served 66 days of a 90-day
sentence. In October 1988, Shriner pleaded guilty to attempted
unlawful imprisonment in an attack on a 10-year-old boy who was
tied to a post and beaten. He was sentenced to 67 days in jail.
   The sentences were not longer because both cases involved the
relatively minor charge of simple assault, authorities said.
   Reports on Shriner up to 1977 described Shriner as mentally
retarded, but in 1987 psychiatrists and psychologists at a state
hospital concluded he had a learning disability and other
disorders, including pedophilia and an anti-social personality.
   Shriner had been living with his mother before his arrest
Sunday. She said Monday that she loved her son, but if he was
guilty, ``he should be put somewhere where he's safe and where
people are safe from him.''
   Tacoma police Sgt. Stan Mowre said police had warned residents
in Shriner's neighborhood, but couldn't specifically tell them
about Shriner and his record.
   ``He had served every day of his sentence,'' Mowre said. ``You
can't go out and stigmatize someone and take out a billboard on
them.''
</TEXT>
