<FIRST>r w AM-JapanFighter     05-23 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan Fighter,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Votes For FSX Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Foreign Affairs Committee voted
22-12 on Tuesday to moderate Senate-passed legislation which
includes conditions on the transfer U.S. aerospace technology to
Japan for the co-production of the FSX jet fighter.
   But Republican members said the legislation remains ``veto
bait'' because President Bush opposes any restrictions on his
ability to negotiate the agreement with the Japanese government.
   Rep. William Broomfield, R-Mich., ranking Republican on the
panel, said he has been told by Secretary of State James A. Baker
III that any restrictions on the FSX deal ``will be vetoed.''
   William Clark, assistant secretary of state-designate for East
Asian affairs, said the administration believes that any changes
``would require us as good-faith negotiators to reapproach the
Japanese.''
   The House panel refined legislation drafted by Sen. Robert C.
Byrd, D-W.Va., after that body narrowly defeated, 52-47, a
resolution to disapprove the co-development deal.
   The Byrd legislation, imposing restrictions on the president in
hammering out future co-production arrangements, was adopted by the
Senate 72-27.
   The House panel adopted a substitute drafted by Rep, Stephen J.
Solarz, D-N.Y. which makes two major changes in Byrd's proposal.
   The Byrd amendment would impose a flat prohibition on the
transfer of critical U.S. engine technology to Japan during
co-production.
   Solarz changed that to an expression of congressional sentiment
that such technology should not be transferred and giving the House
and Senate a chance at vetoing the arrangement if a transfer was
approved.
   The Byrd legislation also flatly bars Japan from selling or
transferring the FSX or its technology to a third country.
   The Solarz version sets up a mechanism for Congress to
disapprove such a sale if the president were to approve it, but
does not ban it outright.
   The Solarz-drafted legislation retained provisions requiring a
General Accounting Office study of the effects of the FSX
arrangement on the American aircraft and aerospace industry as well
as a provision calling on the president to seek at least a 40
percent share of the benefits of the deal for U.S. industry.
   ``This sense of the Congress statement is motherhood and apple
pie,'' Solarz said of the latter provision. It does not require
renegotiation. If the president does not get 40 percent, so be it.
But now he can say to the Japanese, Congress wants us to get no
less than 40 percent.''
   If the House were to pass the legislation as approved by the
committee, differences with the Senate-passed provision would be
ironed out by a Senate-House conference.
   The agreement calls for U.S.-based General Dynamics and
Mitsubuishi Heavy Industries of Japan to jointly develop and build
the FSX, which would be an advanced version of General Dynamics'
F-16, for use in the Japanese air force starting late in the next
decade.
</TEXT>
