<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0660 05-23 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses To Register Student Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with TV Solidarity banned. Picks
up 4th graf, ``Students, we...' ADDS 3 grafs with TV details.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students shouted ``Down with communism!''
when a provincial court refused Tuesday to register their
pro-Solidarity association, and they declared a sit-in strike at
Warsaw University.
   Some students threatened to boycott Poland's first democratic
elections since World War II. They accused the court of trying to
divide the opposition before the June 4 parliamentary elections.
   Communist authorities also banned a scheduled
Solidarity-produced election show from state TV Tuesday night,
saying it violated ``limits which may not be crossed.'' The TV
announcement was made at 10:35 p.m., the time the program was to go
on the air on Poland's second channel. A television announcer
instead read an official communique explaining why the Solidarity
show was blocked.
   Solidarity spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said earlier the
student association ruling was ``legally unjustified, politically
damaging'' and violated the agreement on reforms reached last month
between the government and the opposition.
   ``Students, we were and still are in solidarity with you,'' said
a statement from the independent union movement's Warsaw regional
chapter. It backed student strikes and asked Solidarity factory
committees ``to extend immediate help.''
   Judge Danuta Widawska of Warsaw Provincial Court told about 300
students and a handful of older Solidarity activists packing the
courtroom that the registration request was rejected.
   Students shouted ``No!'' and angrily chanted and stamped their
feet when she offered to explain it, and she hurriedly left the
courtroom.
   Sympathizers and students later marched through the city and
scuffled with police. Students said 15 demonstrators were arrested.
   Leaders of the student association at the 16,000-student Warsaw
University said they are taking over the campus and boycotting
classes to demand legalization. They hoisted a huge banner
announcing the action at the main campus gate.
   Edward Sadkowski, the Provincial Court chairman, said in a
telephone interview that the decision stemmed from the group's
claim of the right to strike.
   Student association lawyer Piotr Andrzejewski had argued that
student strikes have a long tradition in Poland and are not
expressly forbidden, so they should be considered legal.
   Student leader Piotr Czerwiec said the association would appeal
to the Supreme Court this week, but it was unlikely the decision
could be reversed before the elections.
   Andrzejewski told the court it was required to register the
association because of promises made by communist authorities at
``round-table'' talks on reform with the Solidarity-led opposition
that ended April 5.
   ``This, today, was a clear attack on the whole round table and
its decisions,'' he said. ``I see a threat directed above all
against the election campaign of Solidarity.
   ``Part of the students will turn back from the elections,'' he
said of students who have been helping Solidarity candidates
campaign. ``With the great mass of undecideds, and with the
communists tearing down our posters, there will not be anybody to
put them back up. ... It may all end very badly.''
   Solidarity is waging a spirited campaign for candidates to a new
100-member Senate and for 161 seats in the existing 460-member
parliament. The rest are reserved for the ruling Communist Party
and its allies.
   Registration of the students' assocation, like the legalization
of the independent workers union Solidarity and the farmers union
Rural Solidarity, was a condition for the opposition agreeing to
participate in the elections.
   All three organizations were banned after martial law was
imposed in Poland in December 1981. The other two were legalized
soon after the talks ended last month.
   Some student leaders blamed older Solidarity leaders for not
fighting more for their association.
   ``Solidarity ... did not press hard enough,'' said Andrzej
Jesionowski of the student association's National Commission.
   Solidarity was promised access to state TV and radio in the
round-table talks, and Tuesday's canceled broadcast was to have
been the third such Solidarity-produced TV show. The first
45-minute program was May 9.
   A management communique, put out by the state's PAP news agency,
said the program will be referred to an arbitration committee
composed of authorities and Solidarity activists ``for viewing and
mutual assessment.''
   It said the program's contents ``aim against the round-table
agreements,'' but gave no particulars.
</TEXT>
