<SECOND>AM-Navigational Satellite,0141</SECOND>
<HEAD>Satellite Launch Postponed for the Third Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bad weather forced the Air Force to
postpone the launch of an advanced navigational satellite for the
third time Tuesday.
   Winds above the launch pad were too strong and there was a
forecast that thunderstorms would move into the area, said an Air
Force statement.
   The effort was called off nearly two hours before the planned
7:43 p.m. EDT launch. Another attempt was set for Wednesday at 7:39
p.m.
   The launch of the Delta 2 rocket was scrubbed Saturday by
high-altitude winds and on Sunday by a thunderstorm.
   The rocket carries a $65 million Navstar satellite that will
enable U.S. and allied military units such as planes, ships,
submarines and tanks to determine their location within 50 feet
anywhere around the globe.
