<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 2051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-B-1Bomber     05-23 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-B-1 Bomber,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Oppose Spending on B-1B While B-2 Funding is Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers complained Tuesday about an Air
Force request to spend about $1.5 billion to fix the B-1B bomber's
defensive system while funds for the B-2 stealth bomber are being
cut.
   Lt. Gen. Ronald W. Yates, the Air Force's principal deputy
assistant secretary for acquisition, told a House panel that the
current fleet of 97 B-1B bombers has problems with its electronic
countermeasure system, or ECM, which includes its jamming
capability and its ability to identify and avoid threats.
   The service is asking for $1.454 billion to repair the
electronic system. That would push the Air Force past the $20.5
billion cap placed on spending for the program in 1981.
   The problems stem from the original contract the Air Force
signed with Eaton AIL, a Massachusetts company, for the B-1B
bomber. The service agreed on a development and production pact on
the same day, and since then has faced cost overruns and problems
with the electronic system.
   ``What you're telling us is the ECM is less good by 10 percent
than the original promise nine years later. That is the sum,'' said
Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., the House Armed Services Committee chairman
who also heads the subcommittee on procurement.
   ``Yes, that is the sum,'' responded Yates.
   The Air Force official said the service could not defend what
had happened nine years ago, but needs the additional money to
improve the bombers' ability to identify threats.
   Rep. Ike Skelton, D-Mo., taking Yates through basic questions
about the B-1B, asked how many B-1Bs existed and whether they were
``flyable, more or less.''
   ``More or less,'' responded Yates.
   The Air Force official than explained that the bombers have
deficiencies in the ``ability to detect and avoid threats, and
jamming capability is limited.''
   ``You misjudged the problems in the original specs,'' Skelton
said.
   ``We didn't misjudge. ... What we did was fail technically in
the ECM,'' Yates said.
   Aspin expressed concerns about spending money on the B-1B while
funds for the B-2 stealth bomber will be cut $884.6 million in the
fiscal 1990 budget.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, faced with a budget agreement
between the White House and Congress, was forced to slash $10
billion from the defense budget. The B-2 program was among the
programs that were scaled back.
   The Wisconsin Democrat said he was unsure how the problem would
be resolved, but added, ``I think we got programs in competition
here. If we fully fund the B-1, it may come back to haunt the B-2.''
</TEXT>
