<FIRST>u i AM-ArabSummit 3rdLd-Writethru   05-23 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arab Summit, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0690,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moroccan King Welcomes Egypt Back to Arab League</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Hassan, Mubarak speeches. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASABLANCA, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hassan II on Tuesday welcomed
Egypt back to the Arab League after 10 years of ostracism as he
opened a summit conference focusing on sharp divisions over Lebanon
and the Palestinians.
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak urged greater solidarity among
the league's 22 member nations and said the Arab world hopes this
conference will mark a ``new dawn.''
   Hassan said he was happy to see the Egyptian leader ``here among
us, representing his people, the people of Arab Egypt who have
fought and struggled for a half-century ... in support of Arab
rights.''
   Twenty-one Arab leaders are attending the two-day summit,
including Col. Moammar Gadhafi of Libya, who had threatened to
boycott the meeting in protest over Egypt's readmission.
   Only Lebanon, ruled by rival Christian and Moslem governments,
was not represented for the first time since the Arab League was
formed in 1945.
   Hassan greeted his guests at the entrance to the palace as they
began arriving separately at 6 p.m. in bulletproof limousines. The
king did not embrace Gadhafi, as he had the other leaders.
   The leaders held a two-hour informal session and convened again
behind closed doors after speeches by Hassan and Mubarak.
Conference sources said the main topic was Lebanon.
   Mubarak, reading from a prepared text, called the gathering ``an
historical conference, convening in an atmosphere of brotherhood.''
He warned against ``wasting time and opportunities.''
   Inter-Arab difference, Mubarak said, are ``inevitable,'' but
``disagreement should not lead to quarrel.''
   He called for a wider Arab role in international efforts for
global peace and for closer cooperation with the 12-nation European
Economic Community.
   Mubarak said the crisis in Lebanon ``has truly become an immense
problem, exhausting us and exhausting our consciences.''
   ``We must all work for the one aim of overcoming this crisis
before the fire burns us all,'' he said.
   He said Arabs should start by backing a six-man Arab panel that
has been trying to defuse the crisis so it could ``arrange national
reconciliation, ensure the withdrawal of all foreign forces and
revive the constitutional bodies so they can carry out their
duties.''
   Lebanon's seat remained vacant after a preparatory meeting of
foreign ministers failed to agree on which leader should represent
the country, torn by 14 years of civil war.
   On the Palestinian question, Mubarak openly supported
anti-Israeli rioting that has raged in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip since December 1987.
   Egypt's membership in the Arab League was suspended after the
late President Anwar Sadat signed the Camp David peace treaty with
Israel in 1979, making Egypt the only Arab nation to have made
peace with Israel.
   ``We support the Palestinian people in its resistance of
occupation and Israeli hegemony,'' he said.
   He said Egypt would back ``whatever road the Palestinians find
suitable to realize their aspirations.''
   The Palestine Liberation Organization and Syria had presented
rival documents to the preparatory meeting of ministers.
   The first dealt mainly with PLO chief Yasser Arafat's peace
moves and a demand that Arabs meet their pledge of more than $600
million to finance the 17-month-old uprising in the
Israeli-occupied territories.
   Syria's paper spoke of combining Arab resources to achieve
``strategic parity'' with Israel, indicating it still opposes a
negotiated settlement.
   An Egyptian compromise was adopted but its contents have not
been revealed.
   Some delegates said they feared the summit would break down over
Lebanon.
   Iraq and Egypt have said they would seek a resolution demanding
withdrawal of all foreign forces from the country.
   That would includes 40,000 Syrian soldiers deployed under a 1976
peacekeeping mandate from the league and Israeli troopers who
occupy a ``security zone'' in south Lebanon.
   After four years of relative quiet, the Lebanese civil war
revived March 8 when artillery duels began between Christian army
units commanded by Aoun and an alliance of Syrian forces and Druse
militiamen. Hundreds of people have been killed and nearly 1,400
wounded, nearly all of them civilians.
   Seating one or both of Lebanon's rival leaders at the summit,
Christian Gen. Michel Aoun and Moslem Premier Salim Hoss, would
have perpetuated the division and might have caused a walkout by
Syria or Iraq, which are enemies of long standing. Syrian supports
Hoss and Iraq is Aoun's only outpoken supporter in the Arab world.
</TEXT>
