<HEAD>Battle of the Blades Moves to Federal Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0747 to fix category code.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The giant Gillete Co. was in a lather Tuesday,
charging in federal court that tiny competitor Wilkinson Sword Inc.
has falsely advertised its new razor blades.
   In a lawsuit filed in U.S. District Court, Gillette said
Wilkinson's new Ultra Glide razor doesn't really provide the
``smoothest, most comfortable shave known to man,'' as Wilkinson
claims.
   Gillette, which sued to stop Wilkinson's advertising campaign
and is seeking undetermined monetary damages, said consumer tests
showed men preferred its Atra Plus razors to others on the market.
   Norman R. Proulx, president of Atlanta-based Wilkinson,
dismissed Gillette's claims. He said that in blind consumer tests,
men perferred his company's product.
   ``We have ample proof for the claims we have made ... otherwise
we wouldn't have made them,'' he said.
   With annual sales of more than $1 billion and about 60 percent
of the market, Boston-based Gillette is the leader in the wet razor
market. Wilkinson claims about a 4 percent share.
