<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-23 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Spreads Across East and Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms drenched parts of Virginia and southern New
Jersey on Tuesday, and showers in the Northwest changed to snow in
the mountains.
   A cold front pushing eastward across the Appalachian region
brought rain and widespread thunderstorms from the Ohio Valley to
the mid-Atlantic Coast states and the Gulf Coast.
   Atlantic City, N.J., had a third of an inch of rain in an hour.
Severe thunderstorms swept Virginia and southeastern North
Carolina, and a tornado was reported about 30 miles north of
Wilmington, N.C.
   Thunderstorms caused showers and some brief, heavy rain and
small hail from central Mississippi to central and southern Alabama
and the Florida Panhandle. Nearly an inch and a half of rain fell
in one hour in Montgomery, Ala.
   Thunderstorms dropped three-quarter inch hail on Bayfield, Wis.
   A cold front moved across Nevada, western Utah and the high
country northwest of the central Rockies, producing showers and a
few thunderstorms along the northern and central Pacific Coast and
snow in the Cascades in Oregon and Washington.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
over 2} inches at Maxwell Air Force Base near Montgomery and 1}
inches at Mansfield, Ohio.
   Record high temperatures for the date included 89 degrees in
Colorado Springs, Colo.; 94 in Pueblo, Colo., and a record-tying 95
in San Antonio.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees in South Lake Tahoe, Calif., to 102 degrees in
Midland-Odessa, Texas. The nation's low Tuesday morning was 26
degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   The Wednesday forecast was for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the northern Plains and upper Mississippi Valley
to the lower Missouri Valley, rain showers across the Pacific
Northwest and showers and thundershowers scattered from New England
into the mid-Atlantic Coast region.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 80s or 90s across much
of the nation; in the 60s and 70s from the California coast to
Nevada, western Utah and the northern high Plains; in the 70s
across the northern Plains and northern Great Lakes into the upper
Ohio Valley, mid-Atlantic region and New England; 50s across the
Pacific Northwest; and 100 to 105 degrees from the southern Rockies
into the upper and middle Rio Grande Valley of Texas.
</TEXT>
