<FIRST>r a AM-MissileTest     05-23 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missile Test,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Radar Missile Successful in Second Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHINA LAKE NAVAL WEAPONS CENTER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A missile
designed to guide itself in and destroy enemy radar posts underwent
its second successful test, the Air Force announced Tuesday.
   The AGM-136A missile, code named Tacit Rainbow, flew May 17 at
this high desert test base, but the test wasn't previously
revealed. It was the second of 25 planned tests, the Air Force said.
   The missile was launched from a B-52 bomber and homed in on its
target, even though the radar it tracks was shut off once during
the flight, the Air Force said.
   The joint Navy-Air Force project is administered by the
Aeronautical Systems Division of the Air Force Systems Command at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base near Dayton, Ohio. The missile is
built by Northrop Corp. of Los Angeles, which also makes the B-2
stealth bomber and other military hardware.
   The AGM-136A is similar to present anti-radar missiles, which
follow enemy radar waves to their source and destroy the
installation. However, the new missile is designed to ``loiter,''
or go into a holding pattern if the radar is turned off, thus
countering a defense that can be used against such missiles.
</TEXT>
