<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 2119EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-VoiceCancer 1stLd-Writethru a0643 05-23 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Voice Cancer, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0643,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Treatment Preserves Voice in Victims of Throat Cancer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 2-3, `Until now ...,' to fix spelling of `larynx.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A combination of chemotherapy and radiation
shows promise of helping doctors avoid mutilating surgery and
preserve the voices of victims of advanced neck cancer, researchers
said Tuesday.
   Until now, the standard therapy for people with advanced cancer
of the larynx has been to remove the voicebox. While this approach
frequently cures the disease, it destroys patients' ability to talk.
   About 11,000 new cases of cancer of the larynx are diagnosed
annually, and 4,000 to 5,000 of these people have advanced disease
that requires surgical removal of the larynx followed by radiation
therapy.
   In the new approach, doctors shrink the tumors first with
chemotherapy drugs. Then they destroy the remaining cancer with
radiation.
   ``They can talk normally, by and large,'' said Dr. Gregory Wolf
of the University of Michigan.
   Wolf described the experimental therapy, conducted with Dr. Waun
Hong of M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in Houston, at the annual
meeting of the American Society of Clinical Oncology.
   ``It's extremely unsatisfactory for most patients to lose their
voicebox,'' commented Dr. Richard Hoppe of Stanford University.
``It has been necessary in the past, because that's the only
possible way they could be cured. This will have a major impact,
because people have preservation of the voicebox.''
   In treatment so far, 332 patients have been randomly assigned to
have surgery or chemotherapy. About 65 percent of patients in both
groups are still free of cancer after two years of followup.
   The researchers said that when this form of cancer relapses, it
usually comes back within the first two years.
   In some cases, the chemotherapy could not reduce the cancer
enough for radiation to clear up what was left, and these people
required surgery. However, 68 percent of those treated with the new
approach have preserved their voiceboxes.
   ``The results are quite encouraging,'' said Wolf. ``We hope this
can be applied to other parts of the head where mutilating surgery
is performed.''
   In all, 30,000 to 40,000 new cases of cancer of the head and
neck are diagnosed in the United States each year, according to Dr.
Hardinder Garewal of the Veterans Administration Medical Center in
Tucson, Ariz.
   One common variety is cancer of the mouth, which, like the
others, often results from smoking and alcohol abuse.
   Recent studies have found that vitamin A can reverse
pre-cancerous white patches in the mouth known as oral leukoplakia.
However, this vitamin is too toxic to the liver to be used in high
enough doses to be a practical treatment.
   In other research presented at the meeting, Garewal reported
that a natural nutrient called beta carotene can clear up
leukoplakia. This substance, found in many vegetables, is converted
into vitamin A in the body.
   Garewal treated 25 people for three to six months. The white
spots went away in three-quarters of them, and they suffered no
serious side effects.
   They took daily 30 milligram capsules of beta carotene, which he
said is the equivalent of six carrots. He said that if the findings
hold up to further study, it may be possible to find ways of
treating the condition by changing people's diets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890523-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 2132EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-WrightProbe 3rdLd-Writethru a0741 05-23 1048</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright Probe, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0741,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright Lawyer Decries ``Lynch'' Atmosphere; Opponent Sees ``Legalisms''</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS top 7 grafs to put Wright quote in 2nd graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for House Speaker Jim Wright and the
ethics committee clashed Tuesday over whether the panel had
stretched the rules when it charged the nation's highest elected
Democrat with 69 ethics violations.
   And Wright, who watched the proceedings on television, appeared
less than confident that he could survive as speaker regardless of
the outcome of Tuesday's hearing. ``That remains to be seen,'' he
said. ``If I can't be not just a respectable speaker, but an
effective speaker, then I wouldn't want to be speaker.''
   Wright's Houston lawyer, Stephen Susman, pleaded with the
committee to ``stand in the way of a lynch mob'' seeking to oust
Wright and asked that the panel reject what he termed the speaker's
persecution by the panel's special outside counsel, Richard J.
Phelan.
   ``To say Jim Wright should be condemned because he went close to
the line ... is not fair,'' Susman said in arguing that the panel
should dismiss the most serious charges against his client.
   But Phelan, a Chicago attorney, declared that Wright is resting
his case on ``legalisms,'' and he said ethics rules should be
interpreted broadly, not treated like tax laws where searching for
loopholes is an accepted practice.
   ``We are dealing with the confidence of the American public,''
Phelan said. ``Are we to look at the rules through the prism of the
most nearsighted, myopic person that we can?''
   The unusual trial-like proceeding was held in a House hearing
room before TV cameras, with Wright's counsel and the ethics
committee's team, led by Phelan, on opposite sides. Although Wright
watched on television, his wife, Betty, sat in the front row.
   A decision on the motion was expected as early as Wednesday.
   Leaving the Capitol after the day-long hearing, Wright said he
hoped the ruling would go his way, but added that if not he would
take his case before the nation at a disciplinary hearing.
   ``I'm not going to let people down. I'm not going to leave any
implication that I've done anything bad,'' he said. ``I certainly
abided by the rules as I understand them.''
   
   Asked whether he believed he could survive as speaker, he said,
   
   It was just the first open skirmish in the nearly year-long
ethics probe of Wright which has thrown his political survival into
doubt. The speaker is still likely to face a disciplinary hearing
before the ethics panel to determine whether charges against him
have been clearly and convincingly proven, and possible punishment
by the full House.
   Another member of Wright's legal team, William C. Oldaker, had
conceded in advance of Tuesday's hearing that motions to dismiss
charges are routinely denied, and that chances that the committee
would rule in Wright's favor when it meets Wednesday were less than
even. Wright's motion essentially asks the panel to reverse an
interpretation of the rules it made last month.
   But Susman, pleading for the panel to reconsider, read a passage
from Wright's book, which is the basis for some of the charges, and
asked each member of the committee to ``doubt a little of his own
infallibility.''
   Another member of Wright's eight-lawyer defense team, Rep.
Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., said Wright ``needs a victory. That's
clear.''
   Whatever the legal outcome, some in the House were already
writing Wright's political obituary, saying he had been so tainted
by the charges that he could no longer serve effectively as the
Democrats' most visible national spokesman. A group of moderate
Wright supporters met last week and discussed ways for the speaker
to ease gracefully out of his leadership post.
   One fellow Democrat, Rep. Jim Slattery of Kansas, said in a
statement Tuesday, ``If the speaker is not exonerated by the ethics
panel and if the ethics committee concludes that Speaker Wright has
violated House rules, then I think he should resign.''
   Slattery, who is considering a race for the Kansas governor's
office, has come under attack from Republicans portraying him as a
close ally of Wright.
   Susman tried to minimize the charges against Wright, which
include accepting $145,000 in gifts from a Fort Worth businessman
with a direct interest in legislation and evading House income
limits through bulk sales of Wright's book.
   ``To any fair person, that hardly sounds like much of a
scheme,'' he said at one point in a reference to sales of the book,
``Reflections of a Public Man.''
   And Susman suggested that Wright is being pilloried in political
retribution for Democratic rejection of the nomination of John
Tower as secretary of defense, or for his handling of the
controversial congressional pay raise issue earlier this year.
   ``Why worry about due process for a dead man?'' the lawyer asked
rhetorically. ``Why should this committee stand in the way of a
lynch mob or a conviction based upon guilt by association?''
   Because, he said in answer to his own question to the six
Democrats and six Republicans on the panel, ``if a member of
Congress, indeed the most powerful member of Congress, cannot get a
fair trial, no American can.''
   Wright's case for dismissal rested on a contention that the
ethics committee, formally called the Committee on Standards of
Official Conduct, is holding him to a new and higher standard not
envisioned by the authors of the rules.
   Susman accused Phelan, who has led the panel's investigation of
Wright since last July, of picking out the speaker as a target,
``then searching the law books ... to pin some offense on him.''
   On Wright's book deals, in which he sold bulk quantities of the
slim volume to groups to which he had made speeches, Phelan argued
that the facts were clear. ``Look at what happened. Did he make a
speech or did he sell a book?'' he said.
   And on Wright's relationship with Fort Worth developer George
Mallick, who gave Betty Wright a salary and use of a car and
condominium valued at $145,000 over 10 years, Phelan suggested
Mallick wanted something in return from the powerful congressman
who was his friend.
   ``Does that stand the test of credibility?'' he asked. ``What is
the average American supposed to think?''
</TEXT>
