<FIRST>r a AM-LukensTrial     05-23 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lukens Trial,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Opens Case Against Congressman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a teen-ager who claims she
had sex with U.S. Rep. Donald Lukens testified Tuesday that the
congressman offered her a government job after she told him her
daughter was 16.
   ``I didn't think he would stoop that low, but he did,'' Anna
Coffman said. ``I took it as a bribe.''
   Attorneys for Lukens disputed the charges in opening arguments
before the prosecution began its case against the 58-year-old
conservative Republican in county Domestic Relations Court.
   Lukens is charged with contributing to the unruliness or
delinquency of Rosie Coffman, now 17. She says she and
then-19-year-old Michelle Foster went to Lukens' Columbus apartment
in November to have sex with him, and the prosecution says money
was exchanged.
   Lukens contends the charges are part of an attempt by Mrs.
Coffman to extort money from him. If convicted of the misdemeanor,
Lukens faces a maximum sentence of 180 days in jail and a $1,000
fine.
   Mrs. Coffman testified that the relationship between Lukens and
her daughter began in 1985, when Rosie Coffman was 13.
   She said she called Lukens that year to discuss ``him
contributing to her delinquency by getting her intoxicated'' and
told him the girl was 13.
   Three years later, she said she again confronted him during a
meeting secretly videotaped by a television station at Mrs.
Coffman's initiative.
   ``I told him how old she was,'' Mrs. Coffman said, adding she
showed him pictures of the girl. ``It didn't bother him a bit
because apparently he's been doing that all along.''
   She said Lukens told her he thought her daughter was 18. The
younger Coffman turned 17 on Nov. 7, the day after the alleged
encounter.
   Mrs. Coffman said that after she learned of the relationship by
overhearing a conversation between her daughter and Ms. Foster, her
first reaction was ``to contact someone to let them know about it.
I knew if I would call the police, I would get the runaround.''
   She said she contacted Franklin County Children Services, then
called WSYX-TV, which arranged the videotaping. The 50-minute tape,
in which Lukens is barely audible, was shown to the jury Tuesday.
   Mrs. Coffman said she contacted the television station because
she was afraid of Lukens and ``I wanted to get him exposed for what
he did.''
   Defense attorney Thomas Tyack attacked a part of Mrs. Coffman's
testimony in which she said she called Lukens' Hamilton office
using a number on a business card he gave her daughter in 1985 that
identified him as a congressman.
   ``Can I ask you how you did that when Mr. Lukens didn't become a
member of Congress until 1987?'' he said.
   ``I didn't know what he was,'' Mrs. Coffman said. Lukens was in
Congress for two terms in the 1960s, then ran unsuccessfully for
governor and served in the state Legislature.
   Mrs. Coffman also admitted under Tyack's questioning that WSYX
paid for Mrs. Coffman and her daughter to stay at a Columbus hotel
earlier this year and that she was paid $1,500 by local television
show ``Evening Magazine'' for an interview.
   In opening arguments, Assistant Prosecutor Rita Mangini said
Lukens, when questioned by police, denied having sex with the girl
but later admitted to a private detective that he did have sex with
her.
   Tyack told jurors that Lukens admits the girl visited his
apartment on the night in question but that ``what happened inside
is a matter of dispute.''
</TEXT>
