<HEAD>Thai Train Derailment Kills Five</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with five killed, denial cars plunged
into ravine. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bangkok-bound passenger train
derailed in northern Thailand, killing at least five people and
seriously injuring 20, officials said Wednesday. They said 200
other people were slightly hurt.
   The derailment occurred Tuesday night at a curve in Phrae
province, about 300 miles north of Bangkok, said an official of the
State Railways of Thailand.
   He said the train was traveling from the major northern city of
Chiang Mai when 13 of its 15 cars went off the track at Phrae about
80 miles to the southeast.
   The official, who requested anonymity, disputed another
official's claim that the cars plunged into a ravine.
   He said the cause of the accident was not immediately known but
that the locomotive engineer did not appear to be at fault.
   Soldiers are assisting in the rescue operation, he said.
