<DOCNO> AP890523-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 2250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SovietPullout     05-23 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Pullout,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Troops and Tanks Leave Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ONDREJ HEJMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOHOSUDOV, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trainload of Red Army T-72
tanks pulled out of Czechoslovakia Tuesday after a modest ceremony
featuring a Soviet military brass band playing Russian folksongs
and mothers appealing for peace.
   A banner in Russian reading, ``Have a nice journey'' fluttered
in the breeze.
   No speeches were made.
   Soviet troops first came permanently to Czechoslovakia after
they led a Warsaw Pact invasion in August 1968 to crush liberal
reforms known as the ``Prague Spring'' under former Communist Party
leader Alexander Dubcek.
   A woman resident, who refused to give her name, told reporters,
``We want peace, and if the guys up there want to fight it out
among themselves, let them. We don't need armies for that.''
   Other women who said they had sons about to do their compulsory
military service echoed her call for peace.
   The first stage of the present pullout was completed March 17,
when an airborne battalion left the Slovak city of Zvolen, 240
miles east of Prague.
   That departure went unpublicized in Czechoslovakia's state-run
media. Another battalion was withdrawn with slightly more fanfare
from the Moravian city of Olomouc near the Polish border 10 days
ago, but Czechoslovak authorities have not trumpeted the
withdrawals as much as Communist leaders in neighboring Hungary.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has announced plans to
withdraw 50,000 Soviet troops from East Europe by 1991.
   According to Soviet Lt. Gen. Yuri Shchepin, the Red Army chief
of staff, 264 vehicles and 887 soldiers have left Czechoslovakia to
date.
   On Tuesday, 23 tanks pulled out of the small village of Krupka,
near Bohosudov, about 60 miles from Prague.
   Altogether, 1,500 men, 192 tanks and 20 fighter planes are
scheduled to leave Czechoslovakia in 1989, Shchepin told reporters
at Bohosudov Tuesday.
   He said the tanks withdrawn Tuesday would be taken to the Black
Sea port of Novorossiysk, some to be scrapped and others used for
unspecified non-military purposes.
   ``You can see with your own eyes that we are not only talking
about wanting peace, but taking concrete steps,'' Shchepin said.
``We would welcome a similar initiative from NATO countries too.''
</TEXT>
