<DOCNO> AP890523-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 2307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-AlohaPlane 4thLd-Writethru a0728 05-23 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aloha Plane, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0728,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>NTSB Says Airline to Blame for Fatal Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf on penalties after 9th graf pvs, Board member</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Transportation Safety Board said
Tuesday that Aloha Airlines had itself to blame for last year's
accident over the Pacific Ocean in which an attendant was sucked to
her death after the plane's fuselage peeled open.
   The board voted 4-1 to assess as the accident's ``probable
cause'' the failure of Aloha's maintenance workers ``to detect the
presence of significant disbonding and fatigue damage'' along the
skin of the 19-year-old Boeing 737.
   As contributing causes, the NTSB cited the Federal Aviation
Administration for improperly assessing the airline's inspection
program and for issuing inadequate orders to ensure the safety of
older airliners.
   Specifically, the NTSB said the FAA had erred by not ordering
that rivets along joints in the 737's outer skin be replaced much
earlier than they were.
   It was the April 28, 1988, accident that heightened concerns
about aging airlines. The Aloha plane had made more than 90,000
takeoffs and had been one of the first 12 built by Boeing.
   The board, issuing safety recommendations, urged the FAA to
closely watch airlines with unusually high numbers of heavily used,
older planes; modernize training requirements for airline
mechanics; step up inspections of Boeing 737s for additional
fatigue problems, and develop a program to monitor aircraft
corrosion.
   But the NTSB rejected a recommendation drawn up by its staff
that would have criticized the cockpit crew of Aloha Flight 243 for
landing the damaged plane in a way that added stress to what was
left of the Boeing 737.
   Board members said that proposed conclusion was unfair because
it ignored the heroic actions of pilots and flight attendants.
   Board member Joseph Nall dissented from the NTSB vote to assess
probable cause, saying he wanted to blame the aviation system
generally for not dealing sooner with the problem of aging
airliners.
   The NTSB has no authority to impose penalties and can only make
recommendations to government agencies, transportation companies
and others.
   Earlier in the day, NTSB investigator James Wildey told the
board that an examination of the plane's fuselage showed it had
either been repaired improperly by Aloha _ or not repaired at all.
   ``The piece that they repaired contained additional fatigue
cracks that were underneath the repair patches, between the repair
patches and on either side of the repair patches,'' Wildey, a
metallurgist, said.
   Airline President A. Maurice Myers later took exception to that
analysis, saying there is ``substantial evidence that those
multiple cracks were not detectable.''
   He said the accident represents a ``system failure'' on the part
of the manufacturer, the FAA and his airline.
   ``The system should have found the problems before it got to
this stage,'' he commented.
   Wildey also told the board that an unnamed passenger reported
noticing a crack in the fuselage near the door as she boarded the
plane. Wildey said airline inspectors had missed the crack.
   Investigators said that rivets had been installed in such a way
as to concentrate stress that led to tiny cracks in several areas
of the fuselages of the first 291 737s built by Boeing. An FAA
order to replace the rivets became final two weeks ago but airlines
still have several months to do the work.
   Newer 737s do not have the problem because a different method
was used to bind together sections of the fuselage skin,
investigators said.
   Board member Jim Burnett said there are indications the FAA had
not followed recommendations from the plane's manufacturer in
issuing maintenance directives to airlines.
   He noted that one Boeing service bulletin directed airlines to
replace rivets along the fuselage where the Aloha 737 split open.
But an FAA airworthiness directive was vague in its requirements,
he said.
   ``The real issue is that (the FAA) didn't follow through on
Boeing alert service bulletins,'' Burnett maintained.
   The airline has said it followed all required procedures for
inspecting and maintaining its planes.
   Chief NTSB investigator Barry Trotter said Aloha has improved
its maintenance program since the April 28, 1988, accident.
   Myers said the airline was ``in full compliance with FAA
requirements and industry standards at the time'' of the accident
and has since made many changes.
   Myers said Aloha has scrapped three of its 737s including the
one that ripped open, and purchased several new planes, giving its
fleet an average age of 10 years compared with 15 at the time of
the accident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
