<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Tolliver Adv26   05-23 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Tolliver, Adv 26,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri PMs, May 26 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Canvases That Paint Themselves</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Tolliver looks at life through a
different brush stroke.
   He can't explain how he does it, but art dealers and collectors
from around the nation grab his works, forcing him to turn down
offers to go on show in galleries because he can't paint fast
enough to keep up with the demand for his creations.
   ``I put a stroke there, two strokes here and let the strokes
dictate what I'm doing,'' Tolliver says. ``I might start out with a
cotton field and end up with a mother and child. It may be in
abstract or impressionism. In some instances, they paint
themselves. It's just a feeling.''
   The feeling is everything for Tolliver, who learned to paint
from a paint-by-numbers set when he was 14 and not busy carrying
water to fellow cotton pickers in the Mississippi Delta country.
   ``I could draw anything I could see by the time I was 9,'' he
said. ``It was like playing music by ear. But painting is
different. The man who invented that paint-by-number thing was
great. I learned the principles of blending colors, everything.''
   Tolliver, a high school dropout, then began reading every book
he could find on art and the masters. Most of his works feature
people _ mostly cotton pickers, or landscapes of shanties and lazy
streams.
   ``That's my background, and what I paint is the nostalgia I
feel. But I've only been doing this professionally for seven years.
As I grow and see new things, I'll paint from a new background,''
the artist said.
   The old background does just fine for Tolliver, who has painted
1,000 pieces, selling all but a few that are on display in his
studio in downtown Lafayette. He now commands a minimum of $1,000 a
painting.
   His works hang in the Zigler Museum in Jennings, La., a few feet
away from a Rembrandt and a Van Dyke, and in the New Orleans Museum
of Art. His work also has been displayed at African American Art's
``The Heartland'' in Los Angeles, and displayed in the rotunda of
the U.S. Senate Building in Washington. Hampton University in
Virginia has purchased several of his paintings.
   ``Now, some universities don't want my paintings because they
say I'm commercial because my work sells,'' Tolliver said. ``It
doesn't make sense to me. I don't know a painter anywhere who don't
want to sell his work.
   ``They say I paint what people like. That's funny. I paint what
I like from impressionism to modern art. Whatever I feel. I can't
help it because people like it.''
   The 37-year-old native of Vicksburg, Miss., lied about his age
when he was 14 and joined the Jobs Corps to learn carpentry. He
finally moved to Lafayette to take advantage of the brief oil boom.
   He never thought about painting for a living until 1983 when he
was laid off as a carpenter, one of the thousands of victims of the
oil patch crash in Louisiana.
   ``Painting was a hobby, nothing to make a living at,'' he said.
``But there was nothing else to do. A lady I had worked for
enrolled me in the Lafayette Art Association and paid my dues.''
   Tolliver then sent his wife to the association with two
paintings to display but she went to the wrong place instead. She
wound up at the University of Southwestern Louisiana Museum, which
gave her $150 for her husband's work.
   Frances Love, then the museum director, purchased the paintings,
told Tolliver about a local art gallery and the money began rolling
in.
   ``One of the paintings was absolutely beautiful,'' Love said.
``It looked like the rare kind of fine impressionistic landscape
that you might find in galleries in southern France.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Fri May 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890523-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 0811EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Temple Adv29   05-23 0838</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Temple, Adv 29,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, May 29 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>From Easy Earth Girls to a Gloomy Weegee</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Earth Girls Are Easy'' had a limited release May 12 and is
opening progressively across the country through May</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Julien Temple might be a shrewd cinematic
jester who can make audiences laugh with the wacky ``Earth Girls
Are Easy,'' but he's also a solemn filmmaker who can weave dark
tales about a celebrated crime photographer.
   After the success of ``Earth Girls Are Easy,'' his newest
project is a gloomy study of Weegee, the New York crime
photographer of the 1930s and '40s.
   ``Weegee was a repulsive, fat, bug-eyed photo-rapist _ not
necessarily your Hollywood leading man. But the back side of the
character is vulnerable, lonely and extremely talented,'' the
filmmaker said.
   ``I really would like to do a dark and mysterious story now.''
   In ``Earth Girls Are Easy,'' Geena Davis, who won an Academy
Award as supporting actress for her role of a dog trainer in ``The
Accidental Tourist,'' stars as a San Fernando Valley manicurist
whose comatose suburban life is revived when a spaceship carrying
three furry space aliens splashes into her swimming pool. Husband
Jeff Goldblum, Damon Wayans and Jim Carrey co-star.
   The movie musical overflows with kitschy production numbers as
it honors the bizarre arrangement of life in Southern California,
including a celebration of hair tint in the ``'Cause I'm a Blond''
song-and-dance sequence.
   ``I was playing with a culture that is only really been seen
through the cliche of the total Valley girl,'' Temple said. ``But
it's actually a very powerful form of society. It's not a city in a
traditional sense. It's just strange things thrown down in the
mid-'50s, like instant cake mix.
   ``It's seeped through with pop culture. The obsession with
beauty and fingernails and tans and fast food. ... It is like its
own little planet. And I like making films about places as well as
people.''
   The British filmmaker looked at life in the Valley through the
eyes of the aliens themselves.
   ``It's as extraordinary as going up the Amazon,'' he said of
prowling around the local urban sprawl, ``and that is thrilling, as
well as sometimes depressing and sometimes revolting.''
   Colorful and kinetic, ``Earth Girls Are Easy'' is distinguished
by Temple's unusual visual style and attention to particulars. One
crowded seduction scene is littered with everything from a book
called ``How to Drive a Man Crazy'' to a jug of Wesson oil.
   ``I like the details _ just the little visual things that say
how people think and feel emotionally,'' he said.
   ``The beauty parlor _ the line of work Geena's character is in _
deals with crazy-colored nails. But her fiance is a kind of yuppie
_ silvers and blacks and whites. And these aliens are like three
technicolor dream men who come down and make her think about her
life.''
   He has combined vibrant visuals, music and narrative before,
directing music videos for the Rolling Stones, Janet Jackson, Boy
George, Billy Idol and David Bowie. He has also made commercials
for a supermarket chain and Elizabeth Taylor's Passion for Men
perfume.
   ``Music videos are the freest form. You get your own cut,''
Temple said. ``I've never had a video changed on me by an artist.
And you don't have to go through the whole script development
process. It is a real laboratory of putting new ideas together.''
   Temple's video for Rogers' ``Planet Texas'' is an elaborate
account, filled with special effects, of otherworldly cowboys
transporting Rogers to a living sci-fi novel in the sky. Produced
for $600,000, it is among the most expensive videos ever.
   ``The process (Music Television) is very interesting _ that
(audiences) can understand imagery that fast,'' he said. ``The
challenge is to use it to create a new way of seeing.
   ``I agree there are certain basic story lines. But there are a
million ways to play around with those storylines and then there
are a million ways of differently shooting them. ... `Earth Girls'
is a fairly traditional love story. It's `Beauty and the Beast,'
with a little `Wizard of Oz' thrown in.''
   For now, Temple has had enough of tradition. ``Earth Girls,'' he
said, ``is not the ultimate kind of film that I would make. ...
It's a part of getting to a point where I can do something darker.
You can only make movies if you deliver an audience. And I'm aware
of that and I'm trying to position myself.''
   While realizing that Hollywood discourages experimentation,
Temple's profile of Weegee, whose real name was Arthur Fellig,
promises to be offbeat.
   ``I think there's a great charge in reaching an audience and
treating that audience with some respect, and giving them something
that really entertains but also plants certain ideas and questions
in there.
   ``I just wish cinema could be more responsive to real life.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Mon March 29</NOTE>
