<DOCNO> AP890523-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Warhol Adv28   05-23 1011</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Warhol, Adv 28,1051</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 28 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Andy Warhol: Ghost of Pop Icon Everywhere These Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ghost of Andy Warhol is everywhere these
days.
   This month alone a retrospective of the artist's work ended a
record-breaking run at the Museum of Modern Art; his Interview
magazine has been put on the market; his ``Shot Red Marilyn''
fetched $4 million at Christie's; and his infamous, dishy diaries
were published.
   More than two years after Warhol died at age 58 following gall
bladder surgery, the pop icon continues to hog the limelight in the
contemporary art market. Even in death he has easily outlived his
own saw that, ``In the future, everybody will be world famous for
15 minutes.''
   In the book ``Andy Warhol: A Retrospective,'' art historian
Robert Rosenblum wrote that Warhol's ``own fame has far outlasted
the 15 minutes he allotted to everyone else.''
   As ARTnews magazine has said, it's ``Andy Inc.'' time.
   Last year, Sotheby's sold $25.3 million of items from the Warhol
estate, including cookie jars in the shape of pigs and puppies and
early 19th century Baltimore furniture. Warhol was on the cover of
Newsweek, ABC's ``20-20'' did a feature on him and Business Week
and Forbes wrote about the 10-day auction.
   Andy-mania, as some art critics call it, featured equal parts
Warhol the media superstar and Warhol the artist, the man credited
with wedding fine art to popular culture. After all, silk-screened
Brillo boxes and Campbell's soup cans weren't exactly considered
art before Warhol.
   So who was this Andy Warhol?
   ``If Andy Warhol is not the American Dream, then there is no
American Dream,'' art critic Edward W. Hayes said.
   Born Andrew Warhola in 1928 to an immigrant family in
Pittsburgh, he collected autographed photos of movie stars as a
youngster. After graduating in 1949 from the Carnegie Institute of
Technology, he changed his name to Andy Warhol and moved to New
York seeking fame, wealth and status.
   As the late writer Truman Capote once said, ``Andy Warhol wanted
to be anyone but Andy Warhol.''
   Infatuated with Capote after seeing the author's photo on a book
jacket, Warhol repeatedly wrote and called the writer, ceasing only
when Capote's mother asked him to stop, art historian Marjorie
Frankel Nathanson said.
   By his mid-20s, Warhol had become a successful commercial
artist, doing inventive window displays at Bergdorf Goodman and
Bonwit Teller, and works for Glamour, Vogue and Seventeen magazines.
   He began dabbling in art, making a 1956 ``shoe portrait'' of
Elvis Presley. In 1960, he painted canvases depicting comic-strip
characters such as Batman, Nancy and Dick Tracy.
   His Campbell's Soup Cans appeared in 1962, as did drawings of
corns on toes for Dr. Scholl, and his initial repetition pieces,
``Five Coke bottles,'' ``192 One-Dollar Bills'' and ``S&amp;H Green
Stamps.''
   Next came his famous Liz Taylor and Marilyn series (``Blue Liz
as Cleopatra'' and ``Turquoise Marilyn''), in which he accented
their lips and eyes in neon-bright colors. Paintings of Elvis, Troy
Donahue and Warren Beatty were other early efforts of celebrity
portraits.
   Sixteen panels of Jacqueline Kennedy in 1963 show her grieving
over her husband's assassination. A similar period of darkness that
year had Warhol doing works on race riots, the electric chair, auto
accidents and dismembered victims.
   His ``Thirteen Most Wanted Men,'' commissioned by the New York
State Pavillion for its building at the 1964 World's Fair, was so
politically charged sponsors asked him to paint it over.
   Kenneth Silver, an associate professor of fine arts at New York
University, told a Warhol symposium last month at the MoMA that
``Thirteen Most Wanted,'' with its male pinups of the most
sought-after criminals in the United States, showed the ``two
issues of Warhol's art: class and gender identification.''
   ``Obviously,'' Silver said, ``Warhol was determined to introduce
elements of his gay identity into his art.''
   After that, Warhol began five years of shooting voyeuristic
films of his Factory studio followers. Then he was shot and
seriously wounded in 1968 by Valerie Solanis, the sole member of
SCUM, the Society for Cutting Up Men.
   He recovered, and by 1970 had an exhibit at the Pasadena
(Calif.) Art Museum that toured Chicago, Canada and much of Europe.
What followed were the famous Mao portraits beginning in 1972 that
used dashes of synthetic polymer paint and silkscreen ink on canvas.
   Vivid lips and eyes popped up again in similar paintings of Liza
Minnelli in 1978 and of Rolling Stones singer Mick Jagger.
   Factory follower Ultra Violet in her 1988 book, ``Famous for 15
Minutes: My Years With Andy Warhol,'' described him as a ``shy,
near blind, bald, gay albino from ethnic Pittsburgh.''
   But his art is another matter. MoMA curator Kynaston McShine,
who selected Warhol's 300-piece retrospective, put together a show
that is surprisingly moving. The Maos and Marilyns are likely to
endure as classics of our time.
   The exhibit, too, has a sense of humor, with Warhol poking fun
at his own penchant for publicity.
   His 1981 ``Myths'' had panels showing Superman, Santa Claus,
Howdy Doody, Mickey Mouse, Uncle Sam, Dracula, the Wicked Witch of
the East and ... Andy Warhol.
   Warhol once said, ``If you want to know all about Andy Warhol,
just look at the surface of my paintings and films and me, and
there I am. There's nothing behind it.''
   Wrong, critics say.
   Trevor Fairbrother, associate curator of contemporary arts at
the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston, told a symposium last month that
Warhol was ``an artist of consequence. Andy Warhol had brains.''
   But could he paint? the audience pressed Walter Hopps, director
of the Menil Collection in Houston and moderator of the symposium.
   ``Yes, he could really paint,'' said Walter Hopps, director of
the Menil Collection in Houston, in an understatement.
   The show, sponsored by Kroll International, moves next month to
the Art Institute of Chicago, then to London, Cologne, West
Germany, Milan, Italy, and finishes next year in Paris.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 28</NOTE>
