<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 0108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Argentina-Crisis Bjt   05-23 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina-Crisis, Bjt,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banks, Exchange Houses Closed Again Amid Political Logjam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks and foreign exchange houses
are being closed as the two main political parties try to agree on
ways to stabilize a foundering economy and speed inauguration of a
new president.
   The bank holiday scheduled for today was the fifth and the
exchange holiday the seventh since Feb. 5, when the Central Bank
disclosed it no longer would sell U.S. dollars to prop up the
austral.
   It was the second straight day the financial institutions were
ordered closed.
   Argentina's national currency has plunged in value by 90 percent
in four months, falling to 180 per dollar last Friday.
   Devaluation is one aspect of an economic crisis that is forcing
President Raul Alfonsin to consider stepping down early in favor of
President-elect Carlos Menem.
   Inflation is projected at near 50 percent this month, interest
rates have topped 200 percent, wages are shrinking, unemployment
and public anger are rising, the national budget is in deficit,
Central Bank reserves are low and no payments are being made on the
foreign debt.
   The General Labor Confederation has demanded a 125 percent
increase in the monthly minimum wage, provinces are requesting
federal funds to meet overdue payrolls and banks would be hard
pressed to pay the $2 billion in bonds that fall due this week.
   Economy Minister Juan Carlos Pugliese blamed the crisis on
financial speculation, political uncertainty and the government's
lack of credibility.
   ``We can't hang on until Dec. 10 with a policy in which we can't
do anything,'' he said.
   Menem and the Peronist Party won national elections May 14.
Inauguration was scheduled for Dec. 10, the final day of Alfonsin's
six-year term, but he may take office within weeks.
   Alfonsin indicated last weekend he is willing to step down early
if he can without violating the constitution, and if an agreement
is made with Menem on economic policy during the transition.
   On Sunday, Pugliese said exchange controls that had been lifted
will be reimposed, as will export taxes of 30 percent on grain,
beef and farm products, and 15 percent on industrial goods.
   After meeting with Pugliese, Jorge Matzkin, an economic
counselor to Menem, said the national minimum wage would be
increased, as would utility rates. He did not specify amounts.
   All-day meetings Monday failed to achieve agreement on an
overall economic policy or a way to legally move up the transition.
   ``We're blocked. We are waiting for an answer,'' said Cesar
Jaroslavsky, leader of Alfonsin's Radical Civic Union in the
Chamber of Deputies.
   ``If we don't get an answer, we'll keep governing by
ourselves,'' said Federico Storani, a Radical national deputy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890523-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 0108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GasolinePrices     05-23 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gasoline Prices,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>AAA Says Gasoline Prices Up 17.4 Percent Since Easter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists can expect to pay 17 cents a gallon
more to fill up their tanks for the Memorial Day holiday than they
did just nine weeks earlier at Easter, the American Automobile
Association says.
   It's the steepest price increase between holidays in nine years,
AAA said Monday. The last bigger increase recorded by the auto club
was a 19.1-cent-a-gallon jump between Christmas 1979 and Easter
1980.
   The average price of gasoline has risen to $1.254 a gallon, 16
percent higher than at Easter, when an average gallon of gasoline
cost $1.08, AAA said. Last Memorial Day, gasoline averaged $1.088.
   At self-serve retail pumps across the nation, unleaded gasoline
averages $1.13 a gallon, regular is $1.115 and premium unleaded is
$1.268, AAA said.
   At full-service stations, unleaded averages $1.306, regular
$1.257 and premium $1.449 a gallon.
   Diesel fuel is $1.085 at self-serve pumps and $1.219 at
full-serve.
   New Jersey has the lowest statewide prices, averaging $1.124 a
gallon, while motorists traveling in Nevada will face the costliest
fuel, at an average of $1.374 a gallon.
   AAA's Fuel Gauge Report is based on a survey of nearly 5,400
stations along major U.S. travel routes.
   Despite the sharp gasoline increase, the auto club said it
expects 24 million motorists to take to the roads and highways over
the Memorial Day weekend for a trip of 100 miles or more.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
