<FIRST>r f PM-McCall'sMagazine     05-23 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-McCall's Magazine,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Times Co. Agrees to Buy McCall's Magazine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Times Co., which publishes Family
Circle magazine, has agreed in principle to acquire McCall's
magazine.
   Terms were not disclosed, but the sale agreement followed recent
published reports that the U.S. subsidiary of France's Hachette SA
had broken off an informal agreement to buy McCalls.
   The agreement is subject to approval by the boards of the
companies, regulatory approval and signing of a definitive
agreement.
   Both Family Circle and McCall's are part of a group known within
the publishing industry as the ``Seven Sisters'' women's service
magazines.
   The others in that group are Woman's Day from Hachette's
Diamandis Communications Inc.; Good Housekeeping and Redbook from
Hearst Corp.; and Better Homes &amp; Gardens and Ladies' Home Journal
from Meredith Corp.
   William T. Kerr, president of the magazine group at New York
Times Co., said Monday the addition of McCall's to its group would
enable advertisers to reach nearly one-third of adult women in the
United States with little duplication.
   McCall's, which is owned by a joint venture of Time Inc. and
media investor Dale W. Lang known as Working Woman-McCall's Group,
is a monthly magazine with a circulation of 5.1 million. Most of
its sales are by subscription.
   Family Circle is published 17 times a year and has a circulation
of 5.9 million.
   Together, Kerr said the magazines have an unduplicated audience
of 30.4 million women readers, including paid subscribers and
pass-along readers.
   According to published reports which could not be confirmed, The
Wall Street Journal reported people familiar with the talks said
McCall's had been expected to be sold to Diamandis for a price that
would have been announced at about $120 million. But it said
subscription liabilities may have reduced the price to as low as
$70 million, the report said.
   With the acquisition, New York Times Co. will publish 17 titles,
including Golf Digest, Tennis, Snow Country, Sailing World and
Decorating Remodeling.
   Working Woman-McCall's Group would be left with the monthly
magazines, Working Woman and Working Mother.
</TEXT>
