<FIRST>r f PM-Pillsbury     05-23 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pillsbury,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pillsbury May Sell Two More Subsidiaries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pillsbury Co. says it may sell its Van de
Kamp's and Bumble Bee Seafoods businesses in another streamlining
effort since the company was bought in January by Grand
Metropolitan PLC.
   Van de Kamp's, which produces frozen fish products, and Bumble
Bee, which makes canned seafoods, both are valuable brand names but
neither is ``sufficiently linked'' to core Pillsbury businesses,
Ian A. Martin, the company's chairman, said Monday.
   Pillsbury acquired Van de Kamp's in November 1984. It had sales
for the year ended May 31, 1988, of about $135 million. Bumble Bee,
acquired by Pillsbury last August, had sales of about $283 million
for the year ended Dec. 31, 1988.
   Since buying Pillsbury in January for $5.7 billion, London-based
Grand Met has fired 550 workers at Pillsbury headquarters in
Minneapolis and an equal number of non-restaurant workers
throughout the Burger King system.
   Other streamlining moves included the sale of five food
processing units in Latin America earlier this month.
   Grand Met also disposed of Pillsbury's Azteca Mexican Foods
business and its S&amp;A Restaurant Corp., which included the chains of
Steak &amp; Ale and Bennigan's.
</TEXT>
