<FIRST>r f PM-MacmillanAssets     05-23 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Macmillan Assets,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Led by Former Macmillan Boss Buys Macmillan's Direct Marketing
Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group led by the former chairman
of Macmillan Inc. has agreed to buy the publishing giant's direct
marketing business as well as magazine operations Macmillan once
owned for a total of $310 million.
   The purchases are the first by K-III Holdings Inc., which is
headed by former Macmillan Chairman Edward P. Evans and Macmillan's
former chief financial officer, Charles G. McCurdy.
   K-III Holdings was formed in February in association with the
investment banker Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co., to acquire
acquiring and manage businesses in the publishing, information and
media fields.
   Evans had headed a Macmillan management group backed by Kohlberg
that last year lost a bitter takeover struggle for Macmillan,.
   Britain's Robert Maxwell won that fight and paid $2.5 billion
for Macmillan, which is based in New York. Evans left the company
after the takeover.
   On Monday, Maxwell Communication Corp. said it had agreed to
sell Macmillan's direct marketing group to K-III Holdings for $143
million.
   That business includes Macmillan Book Clubs and Gryphon
Editions, and mainly is involved in operating professional and
scientific book clubs.
   The direct marketing group had earnings from operations of $16
million on sales of $85 million last year, Maxwell said.
   K-III Holdings announced separately it also would acquire the
assets of Intertec Publishing Co. and Webb Publishing from a
privately-held group which bought them from Macmillan late last
year for an undisclosed price.
   Intertec and Webb publish magazines in the broadcasting,
engineering, telecommunication, horticultural and farming
industries as well as technical manuals.
   K-III Holdings did not say how much it paid for Intertec and
Webb, but gave an aggregate price for the two transactions of $310
million. Considering the price Maxwell gave for the direct
marketing group sale, the price for Intertec and Webb apparently
was about $167 million.
   Maxwell had agreed last last year to sell the book clubs along
with Intertec and Webb for $400 million to another group aligned
with Kohlberg Kravis. But that deal fell apart when it became
apparent it would not be completed in time to qualify for tax
breaks that expired at the end of 1988.
   Maxwell said its sale of the direct marketing group would be for
cash payable on completion of the deal, expected to occur June 30.
   It said the proceeds will be used to reduce borrowings.
   Maxwell already has announced about $1.4 billion of the $2
billion in asset sales it expects to make in the wake of its
Macmillan acquisition.
   Last week, Maxwell said Macmillan had agreed to sell its
Katherine Gibbs secretarial training programs and its technical
schools division for $31.5 million to Phillips Colleges, a
privately-held concern based in Gulfport, Miss.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
