<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-BritishAirways     05-23 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-British Airways,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Airways Posts 16 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways PLC said Tuesday its after-tax
profit rose 16 percent in its most recent fiscal year, with
disappointing results in continental Europe offset by strong gains
elsewhere and a slower rise in costs.
   The airline said after-tax profit for the year ended March 31,
the first to include a 12-month contribution from British
Caledonian Airways, came to 175 million pounds, or about $277
million, compared with 151 million pounds, or $239 million, in the
previous fiscal year.
   Earnings per share rose to 24.3 pence, 38 cents, from 21.0
pence, 33 cents.
   Pre-tax profit rose 18 percent to 268 million pounds ($423
million), from 228 million pounds ($360 million dollars).
   Sales rose 13 percent to 4.26 billion pounds ($6.7 billion),
from 3.76 billion pounds ($5.9 billion).
   British Caledonian, bought in late 1987 for $400 million,
contributed only to the final three months of the previous year's
earnings.
   British Airways Chairman Lord King described the results as
``first class,'' and said the company remains in the ``forefront of
the world's most profitable airlines.''
   Traffic figures for April, the first month of the new financial
year, were good, the company said, showing an increase of 10
percent from a year ago.
   Prospects for the summer months were encouraging, British
Airways said.
   British law does not require companies to issue results
quarterly.
</TEXT>
