<FIRST>r f PM-American-Planes     05-23 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-American-Planes,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Airline To Order 150 Planes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines is expected to announce orders
and options Wednesday for 150 commuter planes from a Swedish
manufacturer in a deal that could be worth as much as $1 billion, a
published report said today.
   The Dallas Times Herald reported in today's editions that the
orders would be placed with Saab-Scania.
   American has scheduled a news conference Wednesday at company
headquarters in Fort Worth to announce the ``acquisition of a
significant number of aircraft,'' said Ed Stewart, an airline
spokesman.
   The airline, the principal holding of AMR Corp., is expected to
announce an order for 50 Saab-Scania 340B turboprop commuter
aircraft, options for 50 more and 50 options for the larger
Saab-Scania 2000 model, said Paul Turk, an analyst for Avmark, a
Washington, D.C. consulting firm.
   Analysts, quoted by the newspaper, said the purchases are
expected to end a multibillion-dollar buying binge the airline
launched in the past year to position itself for growth in the
1990s.
   American's strategy is to have the flexibility to take
additional aircraft during periods of high demand or use them to
retire aging planes if the industry's growth slows, Robert
Crandall, company chairman and chief executive officer, said last
week.
   Analysts said the carrier has one of the industry's youngest
fleets with an average age of 9.4 years. That average is expected
to decrease to eight years by 1994, they said.
   The airline's officials said they are now entering a second
phase of faster growth to take advantage of a ``closing window of
opportunity'' as regulatory and capacity problems place limits on
future growth.
</TEXT>
