<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     05-23 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0329</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market opened sharply lower in
moderate trading today amid a wave of uncertainty in the currency
markets and after a stronger-than-expected rise in durable goods
orders.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 11.37 points to
2,490.65 after 30 minutes of trading at 10 a.m. EDT.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a margin of nearly 2
to 1 on the New York Stock Exchange, with 672 issues down, 323 up
and 518 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 27.3 million shares.
   Analysts said a combination of factors, including today's report
on durable goods orders and ongoing turmoil in the currency markets
weakened stock prices.
   The Commerce Department reported today that orders to factories
for ``big-ticket'' durable goods such as aircraft surged 2.9
percent in April, the strongest increase in four months. In March,
durable goods orders rose just 1 percent.
   ``The figure was above street expectations,'' said Hildegarde
Zagorski, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``It
suggests the economy is picking up steam again. If it gets too
strong it raises inflationary fears again.''
   Rumors also circulated in the market that Japan might raise its
discount rate to strengthen the yen against the rising dollar and
that the U.S. Federal Reserve might ease credit to help deflate the
American currency.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
off 0.58 to 178.77.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down
0.92 to 352.06.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average, surpassed the 2,500
level on Friday for the first time since Oct. 13, 1987, added 0.92
to 2,502.02.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 7 to 6 on the
NYSE, with 824 up, 691 down and 481 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 185.01 million shares, against 242.41
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
