<FIRST>r f BC-Thrifty-Snappy     05-23 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Thrifty-Snappy,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thrifty Agrees to Acquire Snappy Car Rental</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thrifty Rent-A-Car System Inc., which is in
an agreement to be acquired by Chrysler Corp., has agreed to buy
Ohio-based Snappy Car Rental Inc. for $40 million.
   Chrysler financed part of the Snappy acquisition announced
Monday, said Meloyde Blancett-Scott, spokeswoman for Thrifty.
   The automaker said last week it had agreed to acquire the
Tulsa-based Thrifty for $263 million.
   ``Snappy Car Rental has an excellent name and reputation in the
insurance replacement segment of the car rental industry and will
continue to operate separately under the Snappy brand name,'' said
Thrifty Chairman William E. Lobeck Jr.
   Snappy specializes in insurance replacement rentals and employs
about 1,600 people.
   Founded in 1973, Snappy has 20,000 cars operating from 250
locations. After reporting profits for five years, Snappy expects
to report a net loss of $134 million for its fiscal year ended
March 31.
   The loss was primarily because of its activity in the airport
segment of the daily car rental market, Ms. Blancett-Scott said.
The company is refocusing on the insurance replacement market.
   ``What that means is that if you wreck your car and your
insurance company agrees to a replacement while your car is being
repaired, it would come from Snappy,'' Ms. Blancett-Scott said.
   ``In the daily rental market, the customer typically wants a new
car and they want to be able to pick it up 24 hours a day,'' she
said.
   In the car replacement market, she said people generally accept
older cars, and the rates are 35 percent to 50 percent less than
the daily rate.
   Thrifty is the fifth largest car rental network in North America
in number of locations, with more than 650 locations in 23
countries and an average fleet size of more than 33,000 vehicles.
   No date has been set for completion of the Snappy acquisition,
Ms. Blancett-Scott said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
