<HEAD>Belief That Monday's Selloff Was Overdone Sends Prices Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened slightly higher
this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Prices rose on speculation by traders that yesterday's selloff
was overdone, said Dale Gustafson, an analyst with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   The U.S. dollar's rally of the past few weeks sparked a selloff
of all commodities Monday, amid concerns overseas sales of grain
will be choked off by the dollar's rise in value.
   A weaker dollar this morning added some support corn and soybean
prices.
   Soybean futures went up after the Agriculture Department
released figures today showing the April soybean crush lagged
behind the pace set for the month a year ago.
   Rumors that China is interested in buying U.S. wheat sent wheat
futures higher.
   In early trading, wheat was a { cent to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.95\ a bushel; corn was a { cent
to 1\ cent lower with July at $2.65} a bushel; oats were a { cent
to } cent lower with July at $1.74\ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent
to 3 cents higher with July at $6.95{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent to .38 cent higher with June at 70.77
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .30 cent higher with
May at 77.15 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower to .15 cent
higher with June at 49 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .75
cent to 1.80 higher with May at 36.60 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower Monday.
