<FIRST>r f BC-Schindler-Toledo     05-23 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Schindler-Toledo,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>To Close Toledo Elevator Factory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schindler Group, one of the world's largest
elevator manufacturers, said Tuesday it will close its Toledo plant
by the end of the year.
   The Schindler Elevator Corp., a Schindler Group subsidiary,
employs 100 people in its factory and about 250 people in service
and other related jobs here, she said.
   Lynn Cullen, Schindler spokeswoman, said she doesn't know how
many of the 350 workers will lose their jobs, but said some will be
offered jobs at other plants.
   ``All of the (factory) employees are being considered for
transfers either to the service-based business in Toledo or to
Schindler operations elsewhere,'' she said.
   Schindler will keep some other Toledo operations here, though
some may be scaled back, she said.
   Schindler, based in Morristown, N.J., also said that as
previously planned, a plant in Randolph, N.J. would be closed at
the end of 1990.
   Schindler Elevator was founded here in 1867 as Haughton Elevator
Co. After several changes of ownership, it was bought by Schindler
in 1979.
   Schindler is based in Ebikon, Switzerland, and is Europe's
largest and the world's second largest manufacturer of elevators
and escalators, with approximately $1.5 billion in 1988 sales. The
company employs more than 27,000 people worldwide, including 7,000
in North America.
</TEXT>
