<FIRST>u f PM-Nissan-UAW 1stLd-Writethru f0028 05-23 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nissan-UAW, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0028,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nissan, UAW At Odds Over Worker Injury Logs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEDES with 8 new grafs with state order to release records;
pickup 6th graf pvs, ``We'd like...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Department of Labor has ordered
Nissan Motor Manufacturing USA to release worker injury records
that have become the focus of a United Auto Workers organizing
drive at the company's plant.
   The UAW passed out flyers Monday detailing the workers' attempts
to examine the records before a vote over whether the UAW will
represent 2,400 production and maintenance workers at Nissan's only
U.S. plant.
   Two workers said they were told they could not see the ``Log
200'' records even though they showed a supervisor the Occupational
Safety and Health Administration regulations that said they had
that right.
   Thomas Grooms, Nissan's manager of employee relations, was
ordered to release the records after a union lawyer complained,
Nancy McNulty, spokeswoman for the state labor department, said
today.
   ``We instructed him that according to state law they are
required to provide availability to any employee, former employee
or to their representatives for examination and copying in a
reasonable manner at reasonable times,'' she said.
   Nissan has 30 days to respond to the order, Ms. McNulty said.
   Gail O. Neuman, Nissan vice president of human resources and
chief legal counsel, said earlier that Nissan would decide within a
month whether to release the records.
   The union said it has its reasons for examining the logs.
   ``We'd like to identify the areas where they're having the most
injuries so that when we win this election, we can go in there and
negotiate over that,'' said Jim Weaver, international UAW
representative and coordinator of the Nissan campaign.
   Nissan and the UAW differ sharply over worker safety. The union
says high assembly line speed causes carpal tunnel syndrome _
injuries to nerves and tendons in the hand and wrist _ along with
back and shoulder injuries.
   Ms. Neuman cited the latest National Safety Council figures,
which show an automotive industry average illness and injury rate
of 25.8 per 100 workers in 1987. Nissan's rate was 8.9 per 100
during that period.
   UAW spokesman Maxey Irwin said workers need to examine the Log
200 records to make sure Nissan is reporting all its injuries.
   ``They're ignoring these employees,'' Irwin said. ``They want to
feel that they can go to work and leave there without being
mutilated.''
   The UAW filed a qualifying petition Thursday asking the National
Labor Relations Board to conduct an election to determine if
Nissan's hourly workers want to be represented by the UAW.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890523-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Deere     05-23 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Deere,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Record Quarterly Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOLINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deere &amp; Co. said Tuesday its second-quarter
profit climbed 51 percent to its highest level for any quarter in
the company's 152-year history, citing signs of recovery in the
farm economy.
   The farm tractor and agricultural implement manufacturer said it
earned $130.5 million, or $1.74 a share, for the quarter ended
April 30, compared with $86.4 million, or $1.15 a share, a year
earlier.
   Sales for the quarter rose 15 percent to $1.67 billion from
$1.45 billion.
   Deere's previous record for quarterly income was $108.4 million
in the second quarter of 1979.
   Deere spokesman Robert J. Combs said ``the farm economy
continues to show signs of recovery and we feel good about that.''
   ``We had higher production volumes worldwide and our sales
increased. We also had better price realization because there was
less price discounting going on,'' he said.
   For the first six months of the 1989 fiscal year, Deere reported
earnings of $178.9 million, or $2.39 per share, up 16.2 percent
from earnings of $153.9 million, or $2.14 a share, a year earlier.
   Six-month revenue rose 13 percent to $2.81 billion from $2.50
billion a year earlier.
   Deere leads the United States in farm tractor and agricultural
implement manufactufing and is a major competitor in the industrial
equipment market. It has major factories in Illinois, Iowa,
Tennessee, Wisconsin and New Jersey, and in seven countries outside
the United States. Smaller Deere facilities are in several other
states.
</TEXT>
