<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1404EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-InsuranceSuit     05-23 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Insurance Suit,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Farm Accused Of Building Up Too Big A Surplus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attorney contends in a lawsuit that State
Farm has built up too big a surplus in premium dollars and asks the
court to order the company to return $6.9 billion to its customers
nationwide.
   William Shernoff, a former president of the California Trial
Lawyers Association who frequently appears in court against
insurers, filed the lawsuit Monday in Superior Court.
   He contends that Bloomington, Ill.-based State Farm holds nearly
$1 in surplus for every premium dollar, far in excess of what he
calls the industry standard of about $1 in surplus for every $2 in
premiums.
   ``State Farm ... is pursuing a bizarre policy of accumulating
more and more surplus by refusing to distribute reasonable
dividends and by plowing its extra premium and investment income
back into the surplus, thus compounding the problem,'' said
Shernoff.
   But State Farm had recently rebutted suggestions it was holding
too large a surplus in California, suggesting that distributing
surplus funds would only mean higher insurance prices later.
   ``That's about all we can say at this point,'' Jim Stahly, a
spokesman for State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Co., said
Tuesday, adding that the company had not received the lawsuit.
``It's difficult to defend on a point-by-point basis until we see
something like that.''
   He said that as a mutual company, State Farm is owned by its
policyholders, so cannot go to stockholders to expand.
   He did say that the ``surplus'' label of the fund does not mean
``excess'' or ``unnecessary,'' but is held to protect policyholders.
   Insurance companies hold funds in surplus against the
eventuality of claims.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
