<HEAD>Prices Drift Lower in Sluggish Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Tuesday in subdued trading on the Chicago Board of Trade as
the market continues to be influenced by the weather and the steady
rise in the value of the dollar.
   Improving weather and slack demand for corn and soybeans are
affecting prices, said Rich Feltes, an analyst for Refco Inc. in
Chicago.
   ``As the value of the dollar rose, soybeans broke more,'' said
Feltes of today's action in the pits. ``Whether the connection with
the dollar is real or psychological, it is having an effect. But
the weather continues to have the most influence on prices.''
   The dollar's rally of the past few weeks sparked a selloff of
all commodities Monday, amid concerns overseas sales of grain will
be choked off by the dollar's rise in value.
   Prices rose in early trading on a belief that Monday's selloff
was a little bit overdone, said Dale Gustafson, an analyst with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   A weaker dollar early Tuesday provided some support to corn and
soybean prices at the start of trading. But prices trailed off on
prospects of further rain in crop areas.
   At the close, wheat was 3 cents lower to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.95 a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 4 cents lower with July at $2.64} a bushel; oats were a { cent
to 1{ cents lower with July at $1.75 a bushel; soybeans were 8
cents lower to 5} cents higher with July at $6.99 a bushel.
