   The stock market declined in afternoon trading
today, pressured by uncertainty in the currency markets and concern
about the economy's growth.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was down 17.23 points to
2,484.79 at 3 p.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator was down 20.17
points at 2 p.m. EDT.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a margin of about 8 to
5 on the New York Stock Exchange, with 916 issues down, 564 up and
484 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 156.65 million shares.
   Analysts said today's government report on durable goods orders
and concern about the direction of the dollar helped weaken stock
prices.
   The Commerce Department reported that orders to factories for
``big-ticket'' durable goods such as aircraft climbed 2.9 percent
in April, the strongest increase in four months. In March, durable
goods orders rose just 1 percent.
   Analysts said the figure exceeded the 1 percent rise expected by
the market and provided further evidence of strength in the U.S.
industrial sector despite some weakness in other areas.
   ``It suggests the economy is picking up steam again. If it gets
too strong it raises inflationary fears again,'' Hildegarde
Zagorski, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   The U.S. dollar, meanwhile, backed off from Monday's levels
against the Japanese yen and West German mark amid speculation that
Japan might raise its discount rate and that the U.S. Federal
Reserve might ease credit to help deflate the American currency.
   ``The more important overriding factor in the equity market is
the dollar and how it's gotten out of hand,'' said Thomas Walsh,
head of equity trading for Nikko Securities International.
   Analysts said political turmoil in China, Panama and other
countries was also impacting the market.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 1.24 to 178.11.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was off
1.87 to 351.11.
