<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0230</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined today amid uncertainty
about the dollar, interest rates and the economy's growth.
   The stock market opened lower after a stronger-than-expected
durable goods report for April that suggested the pace of economic
growth might not be slowing as predicted.
   The Commerce Department reported that orders to factories for
``big-ticket'' durable goods such as airplanes climbed 2.9 percent
in April, the strongest increase in four months. In March, durable
goods orders rose just 1 percent, a figure the market expected to
be repeated last month.
   Analysts said the report provided further evidence that the U.S.
industrial sector is strong despite some weakness in other areas.
   ``The figure was above street expectations,'' said Hildegarde
Zagorski, analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``It
suggests the economy is picking up steam again. If it gets too
strong it raises inflationary fears again.''
   Traders said the report raised concern that inflation also could
mean the Federal Reserve would not move to ease credit anytime soon.
   The recent strong rise in the dollar had led to speculation that
the Fed might lower interest rates to stem the currency's upward
momentum.
   A decline in the dollar could lead to lower stock prices because
it would dampen demand by foreign investors for dollar-denominated
assets.
   
 
