<HEAD>California Thrift Buys Four Florida Branches</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT that CalFed bought $74 million in deposits,
sted paid $74 million.</UNK>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California Federal Savings &amp; Loan Association
has bought four branches of American Savings &amp; Loan Association of
Florida.
   The California institution, which already has 51 branches in
Florida, announced Tuesday it bought $74 million for the deposits
in five American Savings branches and the office buildings that
house four of the branches. The purchase price was not disclosed.
   The fifth branch building will be sold or leased separately by
American Savings.
   The staff will be kept on as the branches are switched to the
California Fededral name, said spokesman John Kaufman.
   California Federal, owned by CalFed Inc., the nation's
fourth-largest S&amp;L company, is expanding its Florida operations.
   American Savings, a subsidiary of Kinder-Care Inc. and Florida's
second-biggest thrift, said the branches didn't fit its stragegy of
expanding in areas with heavy concentrations of senior citizens.
