<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold Bjt   05-23 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, Bjt,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar's Rally Fades; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The raging dollar turned mixed Tuesday as
dealers cashed in profits from its recent strength and speculated
on what the United States and its trading partners might do next to
stabilize foreign exchange rates.
   Traders reported more dollar selling from the Federal Reserve
and central banks in Britain and Japan, but they said that once
again the market ignored the intervention.
   ``The market is sort of catching its breath here ... but there's
still very strong sentiment behind the dollar even though we're
seeing a pause right now,'' said William P. Sterling, an
international economist with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
   The slight retrenchment of the dollar against some key
currencies helped push up most interest rates in the credit markets
and weaken stock prices, analysts said.
   Gold prices were mixed in the United States, although overseas
they regained some of the steep losses that stemmed from Monday's
dollar rally. A troy ounce of gold fell $2.65 to a late bid price
of $361.85 a troy ounce, according to the Republic National Bank of
New York.
   The dollar started out strong in overnight trading, closing at
another recent high in Tokyo, but fell against most currencies in
Europe and was mixed in the United States from profit-taking and
amid speculation that Japan and the United States might be changing
their credit policies.
   Traders speculated that the Bank of Japan would soon raise its
discount rate, or the interest it charges on loans to commercial
banks, and that the Fed might ease U.S. rates, both to stem the
dollar's rise.
   The market was also rife with rumors about a possible new
currency stabilization initiative by the United States and its six
major trading partners, known as the Group of Seven.
   The dollar rose sharply on Monday, smashing the 2-mark level for
the first time in 2{ years and hitting a 1{-year high vs. the yen,
due largely to perceived weakness among the G-7 in foreign-exchange
policies.
   ``The dollar cannot turn around until there are policy changes
on either side of the water,'' said Ronald H. Holzer, chief
currency dealer with Harris Trust &amp; Co. in Chicago. ``Until then
we'll be trading off the rumors.''
   But Fed governor Robert Heller said inflation remained ``a key
factor to be considered in monetary policy-making,'' and he gave no
gave indication the central bank was considering easing credit to
depress the dollar.
   On Tuesday, the government reported that durable goods shot up
2.9 percent in April, the best showing in four months and further
indication of the economy's strength.
   In London, the British pound dropped to $1.5675 from $1.5810
late Monday _ a 22-month low _ despite intervention from the Bank
of England. Sterling fetched $1.5645 in New York, up from $1.5755.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 1.50 Japanese yen to a closing 141.95 yen,
despite intervention by the Bank of Japan for the second
consecutive day. In Londin it traded at 141.60 yen and later in New
York at 142.30 yen, up from 142.05 Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Monday,
included: 2.0110 West German marks, down from 2.01175; 1.7915 Swiss
francs, down from 1.7935; 1.19945 Canadian dollars, down from
1.20125; 6.8100 French francs, down from 6.8115; and 1,457.50
Italian lire, up from 1,456.50.
   Dollar rates in Europe compared with late Monday: 2.0079 West
German marks, down from 2.0088; 1.7820 Swiss francs, down from
1.7922; 6.7865 French francs, down from 6.7990; 2.2570 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.2640; 1,451.50 Italian lire, down from
1,455.75; and 1.1975 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1956.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold bullion for current
delivery rose to $363.80 a troy ounce from $363.20 Monday.
   In London, gold jumped to a late bid price of $364.25 a troy
ounce, up from $360.75 Monday. In Zurich, gold rose to $364.25 an
ounce from $359.80 Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold gained $2.76 to close at $363.97 an
ounce.
   Silver prices also gained. On New York's Comex silver bullion
for current delivery rose to $5.173 a troy ounce from $5.106
Monday. Silver rose sharply in London, to $5.26 an ounce from $5.14.
</TEXT>
