<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Oil Prices Head Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures prices rose in brisk trading
Tuesday on speculation OPEC members may maintain their current
production levels and benchmark price.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the major grade of U.S. crude, settled at
$19.04 a 42-gallon barrel, up 43 cents. The June contract expired
Monday and finished at $20.93, with a gain of 33 cents from
Friday's close.
   Prices of crude oil contracts for delivery later than July all
posted gains.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale home
heating oil for delivery in June rose 0.52 of a cent to 47.50 cents
a gallon after falling 1.08 cents on Monday. The June contract for
unleaded gasoline rose 0.34 cent to 64.24 cents a gallon following
Monday's decline of 1.29 cents.
   Analysts said crude demand was sparked by new theories about the
possible outcome of next month's meeting of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   The latest speculation centered on the possibility the cartel
may decide against adjusting its output ceiling and altering its
$18-a-barrel benchmark price when members gather in Vienna on June
5.
   Previous reports have indicated various cartel members are
producing above their self-imposed output targets.
   Andrew Lebow, a broker with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures
Inc., said a comment by Kuwaiti Oil Minister Sheikh Ali Khalifa Al
Sabah appeared aimed at playing down a report Monday which
suggested Kuwait might increase production unilaterally if the
cartel didn't agree to grant it a larger share of the overall
output quota.
</TEXT>
