<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-23 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold and Silver Show Modest Price Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar showed just enough weakness early Tuesday to give a
boost to gold and silver futures prices on New York's Commodity
Exchange, but platinum prices retreated as demand for the metal
ebbs.
   On other markets, grain and soybean futures were mostly lower,
livestock prices were higher and pork futures mixed, and energy
prices climbed.
   The dollar continues to exert its influence on precious metals,
but in a positive manner as gold and silver prices gained for the
first time in days.
   Gold settled 50 cents to $1.10 higher with the contract for
delivery in June at $364.30 a troy ounce; silver was 6.7 cents to 7
cents higher with May at $5.173 a troy ounce.
   ``Buying interest reflected a weaker dollar early in the day and
indications the administration may want to put a lid on the
dollar,'' said Stephen Platt, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc. in Chicago. ``The dollar's comeback to be higher on the day
touched off some profit taking.''
   Platinum, particularly weak because of pressure from overseas
selling, was $8.30 to $9.10 lower with July at $489.20 a troy ounce.
   Platt said investors were disappointed the Japanese were not
doing aggressive buying of the metal, primarily used in the
manufacture of automobile pollution control devices.
   Copper prices were forced lower on the Comex on technical
trading, as prices broke through several price support levels,
triggering additional selling.
   News that Comex-approved copper warehouses increased their
stocks by 1,278 tons added to bearish sentiments on the market.
   Copper was 1.65 cents to 2.05 cents lower at $1.09 cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower in subdued trading
on the Chicago Board of Trade as the market continues to be
influenced by the weather and the strong dollar.
   ``Whether the connection with the dollar is real or
psychological, it is having an effect,'' said Rich Feltes, an
analyst with Rifco Inc. in Chicago. ``But the weather continues to
have the most influence on prices.''
   The dollar's rally of the past few weeks sparked a selloff of
all commodities Monday, amid concerns overseas sales of grain will
be choked off by the dollar's rise in value.
   Wheat settled 3 cents lower to } cent higher with July at $3.95
a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 4 cents lower with July at $2.65 a
bushel; oats were a { cent to } cent lower with July at $1.75 a
bushel; and soybeans were 6 cents lower to 6\ cents higher with
July at $6.99{ a bushel.
   Livestock prices were higher and pork futures were mixed on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Livestock prices climbed because of the belief the market was
oversold, said Tom Morgan, an analyst for Sterling Research Corp.
in Arlington Heights.
   Pork futures received some support from Monday's Agriculture
Department monthly cold storage report that placed on-hand supplies
of frozen pork bellies at 145.3 million pounds. The total was below
trade expectations.
   Live cattle was .10 cent to .75 cent higher with June at 70.97
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent to 43 cent higher with
May at 77.07 cents a pound; hogs were .40 cent lower to .30 cent
higher with June at 48.65 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.53 cent lower to .25 cent higher with May at 34.32 cents a pound.
   Energy futures were higher in moderate trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   Crude oil prices advanced on reports Kuwait is in favor of an
$18-a-barrel benchmark for crude, and will not push for an increase
of its production quota, said Peter Beutel, an analyst for Elders
Futures Inc. in New York.
   Gasoline prices were higher as traders anticipate the upcoming
Memorial Day weekend, the traditional start of the driving season.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 11 cents to 43 cents
higher with July at $19.04 a barrel; heating oil was .05 cent to
.52 cent higher with June at 47.50 a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.34 cent to .77 cent higher with June at 64.24 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
