<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 1913EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     05-23 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Surge in Durable Goods Orders Knocks Bonds Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most bond prices weakened Tuesday, hurt by a
government report on surging orders for American products that
suggested the economy remains strong and inflation is still a
threat.
   Credit-market analysts said the drop in bond prices would have
been much more severe were it not for the strong dollar, which
attracts foreign capital to U.S. investments.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond fell about $2.50 per
$1,000 face amount, while its yield, which moves in the opposite
direction from price, rose to 8.61 percent from 8.59 percent late
Monday.
   The main reason behind lower bond prices was a Commerce
Department report that showed orders for large durable goods surged
2.9 percent in April, the biggest advance of the year.
   Despite earlier evidence of an economic slowdown, the report
resurrected some fear that the economy is growing powerfully,
creating inflationary pressures that erode the value of fixed
income securities such as bonds.
   ``That durable goods number shows the economy is still strong,''
said Carl Steen, a bond-market economist with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. in New York. ``To the extent the economy remains
strong, inflation is still a problem.''
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments fell about 1-16 point, intermediate maturities fell
about \ point and long-term issues also fell about \ point, the
Telerate Inc. financial information service reported.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 0.80 to 1,154.17.
   Corporate bond prices were unchanged to slightly higher. Moody's
Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return
on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, rose 0.59 to 314.60.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 3-32 point. The average yield to
maturity remained virtually unchanged from Monday at 7.41 percent.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.54 percent as the
discount fell 5 basis points from the level at auction Monday to
8.26 percent. Yields on six-month bills fell to 8.76 percent as the
discount fell 3 basis points from the level at auction Monday to
8.29 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 8.77 percent as the
discount rose 1 basis point to 8.14 percent.
   The rates on three- and six-month bills quoted late Monday were
for bills issued before Monday's auction. A basis point is
one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield is the annualized
return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The discount is the
percentage that bills are selling below the face value, paid at
maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 911-16 percent, unchanged from late Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
