<FIRST>u f BC-NorthwestImage     05-23 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Northwest Image,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest Airlines Unveils New Color Scheme, Logo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Planes and other equipment at Northwest
Airlines will be repainted in the next three years to incorporate a
new logo and color arrangement, the nation's fourth-largest carrier
said Tuesday.
   The airline will continue to paint the tails of its aircraft
red, but will add to the tails a logo of an encircled ``N'' with an
arrow pointing upward and to the left.
   The logo and color scheme, which includes bold use of red, gray,
blue and white, were unveiled at the company's hub and maintenance
base at Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport.
   The new image will be applied to employee uniforms, ticket
counters, ground equipment, and aircraft interiors and exteriors.
   Northwest Airlines Chairman Steven Rothmeier said the change is
designed to acknowlege the carrier's growth since it acquired rival
Republic Airlines in 1986.
   The chairman did not take questions about the takeover battle at
Northwest parent NWA Inc. Several groups have expressed interest in
buying the airline or investing in it, including friendly and
hostile suitors. The company is urging bidders to provide proposals
next Tuesday.
   ``We are now well-prepared for long-term growth, and it is an
appropriate time to symbolize our progress with a new look that
embodies the spirit of Northwest Airlines,'' Rothmeier said.
</TEXT>
