<FIRST>r f BC-Drexel-Funds     05-23 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drexel-Funds,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drexel To Sell Two Mutual Fund Managers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. announced plans
Monday to sell two companies that manage close to $3 billion of its
its domestic mutual fund assets.
   Drexel, the Wall Street investment firm rocked by securities
fraud charges, said it had reached agreements to sell Drexel
Management Corp., which manages $2.8 billion in assets, and Drexel
Burnham Lambert Management Corp. with its $181 million in assets.
   Terms of the deals were not disclosed.
   Drexel Management is being sold to a partnership of Eugene J.
Glaser, a Drexel senior vice president and marketing director, and
Martin E. Zweig, a leading money manager.
   Drexel Management is the investment advisor to Drexel Series
Trust, DBL Cash Fund Inc. and DBL Tax-Free Fund Inc.
   A group led by I.W. Burnham II, the firm's founder, has agreed
to buy the stock of Drexel Burnham Lambert Management, which
operates the Drexel Burnham Fund.
   Burnham, who will remain honorary chairman of Drexel Burnham
Group Inc., founded the fund in 1969 and has been its chairman
since 1975. The fund will take its original name, the Burnham Fund,
and is expected to be distributed through broker-dealers.
   Drexel recently sold a portion of its retail brokerage
operations amid a slowdown on Wall Street.
</TEXT>
