<FILEID>AP-NR-05-23-89 2203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Exxon-Bell     05-23 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon-Bell,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Names Griffin Bell To Investigate Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special Exxon Corp. legal committee has named
former Attorney General Griffin B. Bell to head an investigation
into the Alaska oil spill, according to a published report.
   Bell's task will be to try to determine responsibility for the
accident and recommend to Exxon's board whether lawsuits should be
filed against former or current Exxon officials.
   ``I'm going to interview everyone who knows anything about the
spill,'' Bell was quoted as saying in Tuesday's editions of the
Wall Street Journal.
   Bell's investigation is expected to begin in about three weeks
and include questioning of Exxon Chairman Lawrence G. Rawl about
the nation's worst oil spill.
   The tanker Exxon Valdez ran aground on March 24 and spilled 10.9
million gallons of oil into Alaska's Prince William Sound.
   Exxon says it has spent nearly $100 million trying to clean up
the oil that has stained hundreds of miles of Alaska's southern
coastline and killed thousands of animals.
   The ship's former captain, Joseph Hazelwood, was indicted by a
grand jury Monday on three felony counts for his role in the spill.
If convicted, he could be sentenced to up to 15 years in prison and
a $150,000 fine.
   Exxon's board set up the three-member litigation committee of
outside directors after receiving letters from shareholders'
attorneys calling for such a probe.
   Rawl told the Journal in an interview that he expected to
cooperate with the Bell investigation.
   Bell, who served in the administration of former President Jimmy
Carter, in 1985 conducted a similar inquiry into a check-kiting
scandal at E.F. Hutton &amp; Co. Bell found that senior managers
weren't involved.
   Hutton eventually pleaded guilty to 2,000 counts of check-kiting
and agreed to pay $2.75 million in fines and legal fees.
</TEXT>
